1. d4
{ Hi there! My name is Mikhail Belous and I'm a FIDE master from Ukraine with two international master norms from Ukraine. Thanks for giving me the opportunity to become your guide to the rich and fascinating Nimzo-Indian world! You have made the right choice when choosing Chessable as this platform is interactive and makes the process of learning any opening effective and entertaining.   The Nimzo-Indian course covers all the reasonable continuations for Black after 4. Qc2. Every move has been commentated so that it's easier to follow and learn the opening lines. Why did I choose this particular move, 4. Qc2, against the Nimzo-Indian? I believe that one has to play the most critical and challenging variations in order to pose the biggest problems for an opponent. Unless you play on the grandmaster level, you can hardly expect that your opponent will be able to execute a lot of theoretical lines by heart. Even in this case, they can only make a draw.   The Classical system, 4. Qc2, has been played since the Nimzo-Indian has existed with periods of ups and downs. But this variation has always been seen as one of the two main continuations against the Nimzo-Indian along with the Rubinstein system, 4. e3. You'll find a wide variety of positions, both quiet positional and sharp dynamic ones in this course, which gives you a possibility not only to learn a new opening but also to study a lot of interesting plans and ideas.  The course includes a Quickstarter Guide which is an excellent possibility for you to be introduced to the Nimzo-Indian and to learn the most popular variations without wasting too much time. }
