1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... O-O
{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this line. This is the reason why I decided to include this variation in the Quickstarter Guide. We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as  5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  .  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d5
{ The most principled way to fight for the center. Black is going to simply win the pawn on e4 with ...Ne4. }
6. e5
{ In my opinion, the only reasonable move. We avoid the pawn loss and win more space in the center. }
6... Ne4
{ The most principled reply. It's well known that a Knight should be centralized because it controls literally more squares and becomes more dangerous for an opponent. Besides, Black puts more pressure on the pinned c3-Knight in this situation. }
7. Bd3
{ The most popular move by a wide margin, which is not surprising at all, because we're attacking the central Knight on e4 and developing a minor piece, following one of the most important opening principles. }
7... c5
{ Black has to stick to the dynamic style of the opening line. Black attacks the d4-pawn, forcing us to defend it somehow. This is, by the way, a typical way to deal with such a 'French' pawn structure, when white pawns are placed on d4 and e5 and Black's - on d5 and e6. }
8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than  8.Nge2  . White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... cxd4
{ One of the main advantages of Classical variation in Nimzo-Indian for White is applying constant pressure to our opponent. Black must play extremely actively and precisely, or else White can win quickly. }
9. Nxd4 { The only reasonable move. } 9... Nd7
{ If I were Black, I would actually choose this move among others, because Black develops a minor piece and attacks the e5-pawn. }
10. Bf4
{ Defending the e5-pawn and finally finishing the development of minor pieces. We have reached a key point in our variation, where lines branch off and Black has two completely different approaches: getting a playable position after ...Ndc5 and playing a million precise moves to make a forced draw after ...Qh4. }
10... Ndc5
{ The first one, ...Ndc5, which I decided to make main due to its popularity, tends to be quite a complicated middlegame with deep strategic plans, ideas, and maneuvers, where three results are possible. Moreover, Black intends to capture the c4-pawn and open up the d-file, attacking our Knight on d4. }
11. O-O
{ Develop your pieces, fight for the center and hide your King. Looks like we have completed all the steps, doesn't it? As our c3-Knight is free now, we're going to take the e4-Knight. }
11... Bxc3
{ Basically, it's not that great to exchange a Bishop for a Knight in quite an open position. Nevertheless, the fundamental idea of 3. ... Bb4 is to put pressure on the c3-Knight and take it at some point, mainly to damage White's pawn structure. }
12. bxc3
{ Although our pawns along the c-file aren't perfect, they aren't blocked and we can always get rid of the doubled pawns by cxd5. }
12... Bd7
{ A good move, that finishes the development of the minor pieces and liberates the c8-square for a Rook. Also, we must always have our eyes on a potential threat ...Ba4, which may be quite unpleasant for the Queen. }
13. Be2
{ Retreat does not imply defeat. Despite the fact that such approaches may appear to be passive, don't be scared to 'lose' some tempos. We must find the best move in every position, regardless of what we have played previously, and here our Bishop is no longer targeted, and a Queen feels much more free. }
13... Na4
{ A Knight on a rim isn't always dim. Black is attacking the c3-pawn now.   13. ...Ba4?!  isn't a dangerous threat anymore as there is much more room for the Queen.  14.Qb2!  Intending to trap a Knight with f3 and h4 afterward. }
14. cxd5
{ If Black does not take the pawn on d5, Black will capture on c4 at the most inconvenient time for us. In addition, we're undoubling the pawns and isolating a pawn in Black's camp. }
14... exd5
{ 14. ...Naxc3?!  This intermediate move is also worth considering because there is only one option that provides White an advantage.  15.d6!  Creating a far advanced protected passed pawn, which will be a headache for Black for ages. }
15. f3
{ The most ambitious continuation! We invite Black to 'win' a pawn on c3 and fall into our well-prepared trap. And in general, it's a good idea to kick a Knight out of the center. }
15... Nec5
{ The safest move, however, a Knight on a4 looks completely unsettled, as a c3-pawn isn't actually attacked anymore.   15. . ..Nexc3?!  It looks tempting to grab a pawn, but the black Knights become less coordinated and, more importantly, there aren't any black minor pieces on the kingside at all, which significantly increases chances for White to launch an attack.  16.Bd3  Attacking a pawn on h7. White has more than enough compensation for a pawn thanks to the active pieces and great chances to launch an attack on the kingside. }
16. Qd2
{ Black's Rook will end up being on c8 anyway, X-raying our Queen on c2, so we need to move it somewhere and d2-square seems to be an excellent choice because we have some ideas connected with Bg5 or transferring a Queen to the kingside. White is slightly better. }
