[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Black plays 4.. O-O: 5.. d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... O-O
{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this line. This is the reason why I decided to include this variation in the Quickstarter Guide. We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as  5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  .  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d6
{ It's a more quiet alternative. Black wants to fight for the center with ...e5. }
6. e5
{ Since we have chosen the most fighting variation against the Nimzo-Indian, 4. Qc2, we should pursue this strategy and keep playing the most aggressive moves. }
6... dxe5 7. dxe5
{ The main idea of placing the pawn on e5 is to cross the middle of the board and to gain a space advantage in the center. An achievement, like a gain of space advantage, does not come easy, because a far advanced pawn can be easier disturbed and attacked. }
7... Ng4
{ The most active way to attack the e5-pawn. A far advanced piece can be either attacked at the same time. One has to evaluate risks and make responsible decisions. }
8. Nf3
{ We develop a minor piece and defend the e5-pawn at the same time. The series of natural moves follow for a while. }
8... Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 9. Bf4
{ One more natural move that develops a minor piece and protects the e5-pawn. We want to take control of the d-file via Rd1 with tempo and trap, as anticipated, the quite vulnerable g4-Knight via h3. }
9... Nd4
{ Since Black has chosen the fighting ...Ng4 move, they must maintain the initiative. }
10. Qd2
{ It would be a big blunder to capture on  d4  with  10.Nxd4  because after  10. . ..Qxd4  Black has the double attack on the f4-Bishop and the e5-pawn. Therefore, we need to place the Queen on the safe d2-square, where it will be attacking the d4-Knight. }
10... Nxf3+
{ The threat to trap the g4-Knight is still alive, so Black doesn't have time to support the central d4-Knight with ...c5. }
11. gxf3
{ Our pawn structure has been damaged, but it's difficult to come up with a good square for the g4-Knight. }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2
{ Don't be afraid to lose the right to castle in an endgame, because a King becomes a strong piece, that should be centralized when it comes to a position without Queens on a board. }
12... Rd8+
{ The most challenging continuation, because Black tries to avoid playing ...Nh6 in order to save the pawn structure on the kingside in its current form. }
13. Kc2
{ 13.Ke2  would be much worse because it's important to keep the f1-Bishop open as it defends the c4-pawn, which can be critical after ...Rd4. }
13... Rd4
{ Attempting to force the Bishop to leave the f4-square, from where it controls two important retreat squares: e5 and h6. }
14. Ne4
{ Centralizing the Knight and keeping the Bishop on f4. Since the e4-Knight has been hanging, we can't take the g4-Knight instantly, so we want to trap it with Rg1. }
14... Nxf2
{ If Black retreats the Knight to h6, the pawn structure will be irrevocably damaged. }
15. Nxf2 { We must accept this sacrifice. } 15... Rxf4
{ It seems like Black has just won a pawn, haven't they? } 16. Nd3
{ There is a fork, that ruins all the black plans and ideas! } 16... Rxc4+
{ Winning the second pawn with tempo. } 17. Kb3
{ One more double attack! The King helps us to win a minor piece. } 17... Rh4
18. Nxb4
{ Black has only two pawns for a minor piece, which is obviously not enough for full compensation. }
*

