{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as  5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  .  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d6
{ It's a more quiet alternative. Black wants to fight for the center with ...e5. }
6. e5
{ Since we have chosen the most fighting variation against the Nimzo-Indian, 4. Qc2, we should pursue this strategy and keep playing the most aggressive moves. }
6... Nfd7
{ This is a less active approach. However, we still have to play accurately because we have advanced our pawns quite far and they are strong and vulnerable at the same time. }
7. Nf3 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 7... c5
{ An interesting way to attack our pawn center. } 8. exd6
{ As Black has left the d6-pawn unprotected, we are jumping at the opportunity to grab it. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ The d4-Knight has become much more centralized and stronger. We want to improve it even more, transferring it to b5 at some point. }
9... Bxd6 10. Be3
{ First, it's better to develop the dark-squared Bishop as we have a possibilty to castle queenside now. }
10... a6 { Black prevents Nb5. } 11. O-O-O
{ As the d1-Rook x-rays the d6-Bishop, we threaten to capture the e6-pawn. }
11... Qe7 12. Bd3 { Developing a Bishop with tempo. } 12... f5
{ Black is forced to weaken the pawn structure to protect the h7-pawn. } 13.
Rhe1
{ Putting strong pressure on the e-file. White is better because the black pieces have been not developed and the e6-pawn is weak. }
