1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... c5
{ One of the main aims of an opening is to establish control of the center, which allows us to be flexible and move our pieces from one part of the board to another relatively easily. In addition, control of the center usually secures the advantage of space. So Black undermines our central d4-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ If we support the d4-pawn with  5.e3  we might end up with the isolated pawn on d4 after  5. ...cxd4  6.exd4  d5!  And now it's Black who takes the initiative. So we have no choice but to capture the c5-pawn. However, I tend to estimate our chances to get the advantage in this variation to be pretty high. }
5... Bxc5
{ Black decides to capture the c5-pawn immediately, without castling kingside. It may transpose to the main line 4. ... 0-0, however, Black can choose a different path. }
6. Nf3 Qb6
{ This is the point of taking the c5-pawn so early. Black mobilizes the Queen immediately to attack the f2-pawn. }
7. e3 { The only reasonable way to protect the f2-pawn. } 7... Qc7
{ Avoiding the double attack with Na4. However, the question arises: why even did Black play ...Qb6? They provoked e3, so it's impossible to develop the light-squared Bishop to g2 anymore. In my opinion, it's worth wasting so much time just to prevent us from playing g3. }
8. g4
{ According to my database, it's the fifth most popular move, which makes it even stronger thanks to its unexpectedness. We sacrifice the pawn either to open up the g-file in case Black accepts it, or to create a pawn storm on the kingside, as Black is probably going to castle kingside. We threaten to push the g-pawn forward to kick out the f6-Knight from the center. }
8... h6
{ Preventing g5.   8. ...Nxg4  is worth considering.  9.Rg1!  Opening up the g-file works to our advantage. }
9. Rg1
{ Since we have played g4, we don't really want to castle kingside, so we defend the g4-pawn and intend to open up the g-file with g5 at some point. }
9... b6 { This is a way to employ the light-squared Bishop on b7. } 10. Be2
{ Developing the Bishop and defending the Knight on f3. } 10... Bb7 11. a3
{ There is nothing wrong with  11.h4  , aiming to finish the plan with g5, but a sign of a classy player is the ability to play on both sides of the board at the same time. So we plan to drive the c5-Bishop away and grab space with b4. }
11... d5
{ Black fights for the center. It's literally the only way to play actively. }
12. b4
{ First, we kick the Bishop out of the active position, preparing for an advance on both sides of the board. This somehow reminds me of an artillery preparation in battle. }
12... Be7
{ Although the engine claims that  12. ...Bf8  is also possible, I don't believe, that anyone would play it. }
13. Nb5 { Activating the Knight before opening up the position. } 13... Qc6
{ Black wants to capture the c4-pawn on the next move, what makes us play forcingly. }
14. g5
{ We finally open the g-file, improving two pieces at the same time: the f3-Knight and the g1-Rook. }
14... hxg5
{ If Black moves the f6-Knight somewhere  14. ...Ne4  15.g6!  And Black's position is falling apart. }
15. Nxg5
{ Our Knights dominate both sides of the board. In addition, we are about either to finish the development with Bb2 or expose the black King with Nxf7. Although both Kings are stuck in the center, it's obviously only Black, who experiences difficulties as our pieces are much more active. }
