{ If we support the d4-pawn with  5.e3  we might end up with the isolated pawn on d4 after  5. ...cxd4  6.exd4  d5!  And now it's Black who takes the initiative. So we have no choice but to capture the c5-pawn. However, I tend to estimate our chances to get the advantage in this variation to be pretty high. }
5... Bxc5
{ Black decides to capture the c5-pawn immediately, without castling kingside. It may transpose to the main line 4. ... 0-0, however, Black can choose a different path. }
6. Nf3 Nc6
{ We'll see a lot of transpositions to the 5. ... O-O in this line. However, there are several lines, which don't transpose anywhere. }
7. a3
{ Preparing one of the most common plans in this variation - b4. We're going to grab space on the queenside and drive the c5-Bishop away. }
7... a5
{ Preventing b4. But the b5-square becomes weak.   7. ...d5  For example, Black fights for the center immediately.  8.b4  Be7  Since Black hasn't prevented b4, why not proceed with our original plan?  9.e3  Defending the c4-pawn.  9. ...O-O  10.Bb2  It doesn't make sense to develop the light-squared Bishop first, because we will just lose a tempo after dxc4. So the right strategy is to put off the f1-Bishop development as far as we can. Now we're threatening to pin the d5-pawn with Rd1.  10. ...dxc4  Black is more or less forced to take on c4, otherwise, the d5-pawn may become isolated or pinned.  11.Bxc4  As you can see, we have managed to develop the light-squared Bishop without tempo loss.  11. ...a6  Intending to play ...b5 with tempo, followed by ...Bb7.  12.Rd1  Activating the Rook with tempo.  12. ...Qc7  13.Ne4  The position looks absolutely safe but the reality is that we still have to play carefully. For example, after   13.O-O  Black can win the pawn with an unexpected discovered attack  13. ...Nxb4!  So we should play first Ne4, and only then we're going to castle kingside. Although the pawn structure is symmetrical, White is much better thanks to the great Bishop pair. }
8. Bg5 { Pinning the f6-Knight. } 8... h6
{ Black doesn't want to tolerate the strong g5-Bishop. A quiet  8. ...b6  is also possible  9.e3  Ba6  Putting pressure on the c4-pawn.  10.Be2  Rc8  11.O-O  Be7  Finally blocking this annoying pin.  12.Rfd1  Taking control of the semi-open d-file. White is better due to a space advantage, semi-open d-file, and the more active pieces. }
9. Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 9... g5
{ This is the most challenging move, which weakens the kingside a lot though.   9. ...Be7  Let's say, Black doesn't weaken the kingside and block the pin with this move.  10.Rd1  Taking control of the semi-open d-file.  10. ...O-O  11.e4!  Aiming to push the pawn forward to e5. We're totally dominating in the center now.     9. ...O-O  10.O-O-O  An interesting attempt to sharpen the position. In addition, we occupy the d-file.  10. ...b6  Intending to develop the Bishop to b7.  11.e4  Again we want to play e5. It also makes sense to secure our King with Kb1 at some point. }
10. Bg3 { The g3-Bishop remains quite active. } 10... g4
{ Kicking out the f3-Knight, which controls the key d4-square. } 11. Nd2
{ We threaten to exploit the weak dark c7- and d6-squares with Nb5. } 11... Nd4
{ This is for what it was all played. But was the weakening of the kingside worth the d4-square? I don't think so. }
12. Qd3 { Intending to attack the c5-Bishop with Nde4. } 12... Nf5
{ It turns out that the Knight is really unstable in the center. Black is going to exchange our dark-squared Bishop at least. }
13. O-O-O
{ The black King is stuck in the center and it's difficult to come up with a reasonable solution for it. We want to play against the weak dark squares with Nde4 and against the bad pawn structure on the kingside. }
