{ Black plays quite logically. They use a weakness of the d4-pawn to take initiative. }
8. dxc5
{ The most principled continuation. We're winning a pawn, forcing Black to show their compensation, if there is, of course. }
8... g5
{ Quite a risky move, which weakens the kingside a lot. On the other hand, Black makes the f6-Knight free again.   8. ...d4  This tempting move doesn't work out because of  9.O-O-O  All of a sudden, we remember, that we have the right to castle queenside. }
9. Bg3 { The only reasonable reply. } 9... Ne4
{ This is the point of the previous move. The black Knight has not been pinned anymore, and it's able to put quite a strong pressure on the c3-Knight. }
10. e3
{ We intend to develop the f1-Bishop to d3, driving away the e4-Knight. } 10...
Qa5
{ Attacking the c3-Knight the third time.   10. ...Bf5  is a big blunder. Nevertheless, it was played by several strong grandmasters like Nakamura and Karjakin. Black threatens a discovered attack ...Nxg3.  11.Bxb8!  We should get the Bishop out of the attack with tempo.  11. ...Rxb8  loses after  12.Qa4  And we're winning the b4-Bishop. }
11. Rc1 { Is slightly less popular than  11.Nge2  , but no less strong. } 11...
Nc6
{ This is another approach. Instead of collecting the pawns, Black decides to develop the pieces. }
12. Bd3
{ We want to kick the e4-Knight out of the center. It's very irritating. }
12... Nxg3
{ The most logical reply as Black exchanges our active dark-squared Bishop. }
13. hxg3
{ The possibility of involving a Rook into the game, without playing a single move, always impresses me. }
13... d4
{ This is the only chance for Black to fight for an equal position.   13. ...Qxc5?!  If Black acts too greedy, they'll find themselves in a difficult position very quickly.  14.Nf3  The main problem of Black's position is the King, which is stuck in the center.  14. ...Bg4  15.O-O  We enjoy the black awful pawn structure and intend to put pressure on the d5-pawn with Qb3. }
14. exd4 { Otherwise, we lose the c3-Knight. } 14... Nxd4 15. Qd2
{ I find this move more logical than other retreats as we x-ray the d4-Knight, which will serve us well in the near future. }
15... Bxc5 { Black wins back a pawn and avoids annoying a3. } 16. Nge2
{ Attacking the d4-Knight. This is the point of retreating the Queen to d2 because we want to capture the d4-Knight, followed by Bb5, a discovered check. The black King is stuck in the center and it's difficult to come up with an active plan for Black. }
