[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Black plays 4.. d5: 5.. exd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... d5
{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... exd5
{ There are two main continuations: ... exd5 and ...Qxd5, the so-called Romanishin system. After the text move, Black should be ready to play with an isolated d5-pawn in many lines. However, the c8-Bishop becomes active. }
6. Bg5 { We pin the f6-Knight, making Black feel uncomfortable. } 6... h6
{ This is undoubtedly a useful move, creating an escape square, even if Black doesn't play ...g5 afterward.   6. ...c6  This move is not very popular among Nimzo-Indian players as we get a position, which is similar to the Queen's Gambit Declined.  7.e3  Again we should develop a Bishop first because we don't know yet where to develop a Knight - to e2 or f3.  7. ...Nbd7  8.Bd3  We are going to develop a Knight to e2 and castle short afterward. White is slightly better. }
7. Bh4
{ It doesn't make any sense to take on  f6  .  7.Bxf6  due to  7. ...Qxf6  and we cannot capture the d5-pawn because our c3-Knight is being pinned. So we should just maintain a pin. }
7... O-O
{ Black chooses a more positional path, which leads to a type of a position that is very similar to the Queen's Gambit Declined. }
8. e3
{ 8.Bxf6  It doesn't make any sense so far to take on f6, because after  8. ...Qxf6  We can't take on d5 as our Knight is still pinned. }
8... c6
{ This is the most typical move on the Queen's Gambit for Black. Black overprotects the d5-pawn and, in general, the black pawn structure on the queenside looks stable and sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We sort of 'break' an opening rule, which states, that it's preferable to develop Knights before Bishops. We should make an exception here as the g1-Knight may go to e2 as well. }
9... Nbd7
{ There are not so many squares where the b8-Knight can be developed: a6 or d7. A choice is obvious. }
10. Ne2
{ There is nothing wrong with Nf3 as well, but I'm very fond of this setup. We maintain the f3-square vacant to push there a pawn one day to prepare a pawn storm in the center with e4. }
10... Re8
{ This is also a standard plan for Black. The e8-Rook liberates the f8-square for a Knight and puts pressure along the e-file, preventing f3. }
11. O-O
{ Castling long in such a type of position is considered, by all means, a sharper but objectively worse continuation. One plays it normally in a 'must-win' situation. }
11... Nf8
{ Opening the c8-h3 diagonal for the c8-Bishop and intending to transfer the Knight to e6 at some point. }
12. Rae1
{ This position lets us play slowly, so we jump at this opportunity and prepare e4 deliberately. }
12... Bd6 13. h3
{ We need to anticipate a plan of an opponent and get a step ahead of him. Black threatened ...Bxh2. Let me illustrate what could happen if we were not careful enough.   13.a3  Bxh2!  14.Kxh2  Ng4!  Attacking the h4-Bishop.  15.Kg3  The only way to protect it.  15. ...g5  And the game is over. }
13... Ne6 { Activating a Knight. } 14. f3
{ Since the e-file has been closed, the pawn on e3 doesn't hang anymore. We want to make our King a little bit safer with Kh1 and finally play e4, breaking through the center. }
*

