{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... Qxd5
{ This move, though counterintuitive, became popular when Romanishin, great Ukrainian grandmaster, found and developed an interesting idea of transposing into an endgame, which we will see a bit later. He significantly influenced the chess theory in the Kasparov vs Karpov era. }
6. Nf3
{ Another way to defend the d4-pawn is  6.e3  which leads to a position with symmetrical pawn structure, and White having the Bishop pair. However, in my opinion, it is too dry. We have chosen Qc2 on the fourth move to play combative chess after all! }
6... Qf5
{ This is a fascinating idea of Romanishin! I suppose I must not praise Black's moves so hard, but I can't help admiring a genius of Romanishin, who found and analyzed this move in the times when a computer could barely beat a master. It's the second counterintuitive move in a row. First, Black moves the Queen to the d5-square, which is 'controlled' by a Knight. Then Black voluntarily suggests the exchange of the Queens, doubling the pawns on the f-file. }
7. Qb3
{ Undoubtedly, we should first discuss  7.Qxf5  exf5  It looks tempting to double the black pawns, but if we would have a closer look at this position, we'll see, that Black takes control of the e4-square and liberates the e6-square for a Bishop. Unfortunately, this is enough for Black to equalize. The idea of the text move is just to avoid a position, where Black has firm control of the center and maintains tension, by keeping the Queens on the board. }
7... c5
{ I find this move even more logical than the main one, because Black doesn't want to block the c7-pawn with a Knight and fights for the center immediately. However, there is an antidote to this variation. }
8. a3
{ We should drive the b4-Bishop away as it creates a pin and defends the c5-pawn. }
8... Ba5
{ This move is the most popular as Black maintains a pin and tension. } 9. Qc4
{ We're attacking the c5-pawn and x-raying the c8-Bishop. } 9... Bxc3+
{ At least Black tested us whether we could find Qc4 or not.   9. ...Nbd7  For example, Black defends the c5-pawn immediately, leaving the Bishop on a5.  10.b4  Gaining space on the queenside and getting rid of the pin on the a5-e1 diagonal.  10. ...cxb4  Otherwise, Black loses a pawn on c5.  11.axb4  A Rook on a1 becomes suddenly involved in the game.  11. ...Bd8  This move looks weird, but it's important for Black to maintain the b6-square vacant for a Knight.  12.e3  Intending to develop a light-squared Bishop. It's not a big problem that our c1-Bishop becomes blocked, as we're going to develop it either to b2 or a3. }
10. Qxc3 { The c5-pawn is still hanging. } 10... Nbd7
{ An ideal square for the black Knight is c6, but the c5-pawn must be defended. Unfortunately, not all dreams come true. }
11. g4 { We try to distract the Queen from the defense of the c5-pawn. } 11...
Qd5
{ Refusing to accept a pawn sacrifice.   11. ...Qxg4  The first thing which we should calculate when sacrificing a pawn.  12.dxc5  Winning back a pawn immediately.     11. ...Nxg4  I think, it makes more sense to grab a pawn with a Knight as the black Queen still defends the c5-pawn.  12.Rg1  Attacking the g4-Knight so that the black Queen becomes tied to the defense of it. We're going to kick out the g4-Knight with h3. }
12. Bg2 { Developing a Bishop, which is x-raying the d5-Queen now. } 12... cxd4
13. Qxd4 { We're quite happy to open up the center as we have a Bishop pair. }
13... Nc5 { Activating a Knight, which would like to land on b3. } 14. Qxd5
{ We don't mind transposing into an endgame. } 14... Nxd5 15. Nd4
{ Centralizing a Knight and preventing ...Nb3. We are better thanks to a Bishop pair advantage and an awful Bishop on c8. }
