1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is attacking the d4-pawn immediately and transposes to a Two Knights' Tango type position, which originally arises after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  Nc6  . }
5. Nf3 { Developing a Knight and defending a pawn. } 5... d6
{ Black prepares ...e5. This is a not very popular way to deal with the Classical Variation, but it certainly deserves attention. Black wants to avoid memorizing tons of forcing lines and get an interesting position, where one should maneuver their pieces and execute some strategic plans. }
6. Bd2
{ It's also possible to force Black to exchange the dark-squared Bishop immediately with  6.a3  but it's better to take back on c3 with a Bishop. }
6... O-O 7. a3
{ It's a natural and good idea to make Black exchange a Bishop for a Knight. }
7... Bxc3
{ 7. ...Ba5??  an attempt to save a Bishop results in a catastrophe after  8.b4  Bb6  9.c5!  The Bishop is trapped. }
8. Bxc3
{ We get a long-lasting type of advantage - a Bishop pair. In addition, the c3-Bishop will be shooting along the c3-h8 diagonal after ... e5 will have been played. }
8... Qe7
{ The main plan for Black is to push the e-pawn and fight for the center.; } 9.
e3
{ On one hand,  9.e4  looks much more ambitious, but on the other hand, after  9. ...e5  10.d5  the center becomes closed and eventually, it will be harder to break through. }
9... e5 10. dxe5
{ I think, this approach is better than closing the center as we open the center and include the c3-Bishop into the game. }
10... dxe5
{ 10. ...Nxe5  I don't see much sense for Black in exchanging the Knights.  11.Nxe5  The e5-Knight is too active to be tolerated.  11. ...dxe5  12.Be2  Re8  13.O-O  b6  14.Rfd1  Activating a Rook by placing it on the open d-file.  14. ...Bb7  15.f3!  Restricting the black light-squared Bishop and aiming to launch the attack on the queenside with b4. }
11. Be2
{ Our light-squared Bishop feels much more comfortable and safer on  e2  than on  d3  . After  11.Bd3  Re8!  Black threatens a fork with ...e4, so we are anyway forced to retreat a Bishop back. We want to gain a space advantage on the queenside with b4. }
11... a5 { Preventing b4. } 12. O-O
{ We have completed our development and we're waiting for Black's choice of a plan. }
12... Bg4 { This is not the best, but for some reason the most popular move. }
13. h3
{ We're creating an escape square and forcing the black Bishop to retreat to a less protected square. }
13... Bh5 14. Nxe5 { A wonderful combination! } 14... Nxe5
{ 14. ...Bxe2?  fails due to an intermediate move  15.Nxc6!  bxc6  16.Qxe2  We end up having an extra pawn and a much better pawn structure. }
15. Bxh5
{ That's why we had to drive back the black Bishop to h5. If it was placed on g4, Black would be able to capture on g4 with the e5-Knight. }
15... Nxh5 16. Qf5 { Attacking two Knights at the same time. } 16... Nxc4
{ Winning back a pawn. } 17. Qxh5
{ We haven't won any material, but meanwhile, we have completely opened a position, where a Bishop dominates a Knight. Furthermore, we're threatening Bxg7, followed by Qg4 with a double attack. }
