18... a6
{ preventing Nd4-b5 and preparing ...b7-b5. It's objectively the best move . }
19. Bg3
{ The Bishop on f4 could be potentially attacked by ...Nc5-e6, so we're just moving it to a safer square. It might be a bit confusing, but it's difficult sometimes to come up with a concrete plan, so we have to improve our pieces slightly and start maneuvering. }
19... b5
{ sticking to the plan and intending to transfer the Knight to b6 and then to c4 at some point. }
20. Nc2
{ Opening up the d-file and putting more pressure on the d5-pawn. Nb4 is one more interesting possibility. }
20... Nb6
{ The Knight is placed behind the b-pawn, indicating good positional understanding. Pieces, particularly Knights, can readily jump through pawns, whereas pawns can't move ahead when they're blocked. }
21. Bf2
{ We sacrifice the pawn on e5 and create a small trap. However, it's not that cheap trick, because Bg3-f2 is quite useful in itself, as we put some pressure on the black Knight on c5 and f2-b6 diagonal in general.   21.Nb4  Our pieces are not ready yet to follow this plan, because after  21. ...a5  22.Nxd5?  Bc6  We lose the Knight due to the pin along the d-file. }
21... Be6
{ Overprotecting the pawn on d5.   21. ...Nc4  It looks tempting to complete the plan immediately.  22.Bxc4  We shouldn't tolerate such an active Knight.  22. ...dxc4  Black is going to occupy an outpost on d3 with ...Nd3.  23.Bxc5  We should eliminate a potentially powerful piece.  23. ...Rxc5  24.Rcd1  Creating a pin on the d-file and attacking the d7-Bishop.  24. ...Rc7  Black defends the d7-Bishop.  25.Qf2  We're going to either penetrate the black camp with Qb6 or start advancing the pawn with f4 and f5. White is clearly better thanks to the central e5-pawn and control over the d-file. }
22. Bd4
{ A clever move, that prepares Qe3 and e6, if the black Bishop leaves the e6 square one day. }
22... Nc4
{ Black finishes quite a long plan and settles the Knight on an outpost, which is, by all means, an achievement. }
23. Qf4
{ At the same time we have coordinated our pieces quite well and intend to continue maneuvering, e.g. Bf1, Qg3, Nb4. White is better because Black has a weak pawn on d5, a passive Bishop on e6, and less space due to the white far advanced pawn on e5. One more possible plan could be to take Bxc4, followed by Ne3-f4-f5. }
