{ Because we are not at war, retreat does not imply defeat. Despite the fact that such approaches may appear to be passive, don't be scared to 'lose' some tempos. We must find the best move in every position, regardless of what we have played previously, and here our Bishop is no longer targeted, and a Queen feels much more free. }
13... Na4
{ A Knight on a rim isn't always dim. Black is attacking the c3-pawn now. } 14.
cxd5
{ If Black does not take the pawn on d5, Black will capture on c4 at the most inconvenient time for us. In addition, we're undoubling the pawns and isolating a pawn in Black's camp. }
14... exd5 15. f3
{ The most ambitious continuation! We invite Black to 'win' a pawn on c3 and fall into our well-prepared trap. And in general, it's a good idea to kick a Knight out of the center. }
15... Nec5
{ The safest move, however, a Knight on a4 looks completely unsettled, as a c3-pawn isn't actually attacked anymore. }
16. Qd2
{ Black's Rook will end up being on c8 anyway, x-raying our Queen on c2, so we need to move it somewhere and d2-square seems to be an excellent choice because we have some ideas connected with Bg5 or transferring a Queen to the kingside. }
16... Rc8 { Black's Rook occupies a semi-open file and X-rays our pawn on c3. }
17. Rac1 { Defending a pawn on c3 and preparing a potential pawn push to c4. }
17... Re8
{ Again it makes sense to place a Rook on a semi-open file and put pressure on our pawn on e5. }
18. Rfe1
{ The Rooks have made perfectly symmetrical moves! Our rooks are more effective at protecting the pawns on c3 and e5, while they are willing to assist pawn breakthroughs, such as c3-c4 or e5-e6. }
18... a6
{ preventing Nd4-b5 and preparing ...b7-b5. It's objectively the best move . }
19. Bg3
{ The Bishop on f4 could be potentially attacked by ...Nc5-e6, so we're just moving it to a safer square. It might be a bit confusing, but it's difficult sometimes to come up with a concrete plan, so we have to improve our pieces slightly and start maneuvering. }
19... b5
{ sticking to the plan and intending to transfer the Knight to b6 and then to c4 at some point. }
20. Nc2
{ Opening up the d-file and putting more pressure on the d5-pawn. Nb4 is one more interesting possibility. }
20... Nb6
{ The Knight is placed behind the b-pawn, indicating good positional understanding. Pieces, particularly Knights, can readily jump through pawns, whereas pawns can't move ahead when they're blocked. }
21. Bf2
{ We sacrifice the pawn on e5 and create a small trap. However, it's not that cheap trick, because Bg3-f2 is quite useful in itself, as we put some pressure on the black Knight on c5 and f2-b6 diagonal in general.   21.Nb4  Our pieces are not ready yet to follow this plan, because after  21. ...a5  22.Nxd5?  Bc6  We lose the Knight due to the pin along the d-file. }
21... Rxe5
{ It looks tempting to eat the central pawn, but Black falls into a small trap. }
22. Bxc5
{ One, who wants to become a better chess player, has to train the ability to make unnatural decisions. Bxc5 is by no means an obvious solution because we trade the powerful Bishop, however, only this move gives us a slight advantage. You have to literally force yourself to consider all the forcing moves, like checks, captures and attacks, even if one of them looks unnatural. }
22... Rxc5 23. Qd4 Qe7
{ The only move, that doesn't lose immediately.   23. ...Qc7?  looks like there is no difference between ...Qc7 and ...Qe7, but Black has to be careful.  24.Nb4!  +- It's impossible to defend against both forks, Na6 and Nd3. }
24. Bxb5
{ A discovered attack! Opening up the e-file and attacking the Rook on e5. }
24... Rxe1+ 25. Rxe1 { The black Queen is being attacked right now. } 25... Be6
26. Bxa6
{ Collecting all the pawns on the queenside. Despite the slight compensation for Black due to the weak pawn on c3, White must be better thanks to the extra pawn on a2. }
*

