{ Basically, it's not that great to exchange a Bishop for a Knight in quite an open position. Nevertheless, the fundamental idea of 3. .. . Bb4 is to put pressure on the c3-Knight and take it at some point, mainly to damage White's pawn structure. }
12. bxc3
{ Although our pawns along the c-file aren't perfect, they aren't blocked and we can always get rid of the doubled pawns by cxd5. }
12... Bd7
{ A good move, that finishes the development of the minor pieces and liberates the c8-square for a Rook. Also, we must always have our eyes on a potential threat ...Ba4, which may be quite unpleasant for the Queen.   12. ...Nxd3  13.Qxd3  transposes to  11. ... Nxd3 }
13. Be2
{ Because we are not at war, retreat does not imply defeat. Despite the fact that such approaches may appear to be passive, don't be scared to 'lose' some tempos. We must find the best move in every position, regardless of what we have played previously, and here our Bishop is no longer targeted, and a Queen feels much more free. }
13... Na4
{ A Knight on a rim isn't always dim. Black is attacking the c3-pawn now. } 14.
cxd5
{ If Black does not take the pawn on d5, Black will capture on c4 at the most inconvenient time for us. In addition, we're undoubling the pawns and isolating a pawn in Black's camp. }
14... exd5 15. f3
{ The most ambitious continuation! We invite Black to 'win' a pawn on c3 and fall into our well-prepared trap. And in general, it's a good idea to kick a Knight out of the center. }
15... Nexc3
{ It looks tempting to grab a pawn, but the black Knights become less coordinated and, more importantly, there aren't any black minor pieces on the kingside at all, which significantly increases chances for White to launch an attack. }
16. Bd3 { Attacking a pawn on h7. } 16... Kh8
{ Setting up a nice trap. Be careful! } 17. Kh1
{ A good prophylactical move. A typical one, if you have a pawn on f3.   17.Bxh7?  This move looks tempting, but it's a huge mistake!  17. ...Qh4  -+ Attacking two Bishops at the same time. No way to protect both of them! }
17... Rc8 { Threatening some discovered attacks, such as ...Ne4. } 18. Qd2
{ Never keep your Queen on the same file with the opponent Rook! } 18... b5
{ Black plays mainly on the queenside in this variation. } 19. Rae1
{ We're going to start an attack on the kingside with Nf5 and Bg5. As Black doesn't have any defenders on the kingside, it's hard to imagine that Black will ever stop our attack. It's also possible to play Bg5, followed by Qf4 and Qh4. }
