{ It looks tempting to grab a pawn, but the black Knights become less coordinated and, more importantly, there aren't any black minor pieces on the kingside at all, which significantly increases chances for White to launch an attack. }
16. Bd3 { Attacking a pawn on h7. } 16... g6
{ One more possible way to protect the pawn on h7. Although not the best in my opinion, because it weakens the dark squares on the kingside too much. Nevertheless, Black has quite a dangerous threat - ...Qb6, attacking the Knight on d4, and after the only possible defense Be3, ...Qb2, trading the Queens. Why is this maneuver so powerful? When you are a defender, exchange Queens! Obviously, it's only White, who can create an attack, so Black has to neutralize the potential threats. }
17. Qd2
{ Moving the Queen off the c-file, which could be occupied by the black Rook in the future via...Rc8, and preventing the... Qb6,...Qb2 plan by allowing the Knight to use the c2-square. Furthermore, we have several possibilities for exploiting the weak dark squares in Bg5-Bf6-Qh6. First and foremost, we must protect the g1-b6 diagonal, particularly the Knight on d4. }
17... Re8
{ Putting some pressure on the pawn on e5 and threatening ...Qb6 now. } 18.
Rfe1
{ Overprotecting the pawn on e5 and liberating the f1-square for the Bishop in order to be able to defend the Knight on d4 with the Queen. }
18... Qb6
{ Attacking the Knight on d4 and creating the pin along the b6-g1 diagonal. }
19. Bf1
{ We confidently defend the Knight on d4, which blocks the isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@this is, by the way, what you should do when playing against an isolated pawn@@EndBracket@@. The coordination of our pieces has been finished and we are going to create deadly threats via Bg5, Bf6 and Qh6. Quite a deep middlegame with a lot of sophisticated maneuvers, isn't it? }
