11... Nxd3 { Quite a logical decision - to trade the Knight for the Bishop. }
12. Qxd3 { Not much choice left. } 12... Bxc3
{ I believe that Black anyway has to take advantage of the Nimzo-Bishop on b4 and attempt to damage the pawn structure. }
13. bxc3 b6
{ Since there is the pawn on e6, that blocks the light-squared Bishop, Black wants to develop the Bishop to a6, putting strong pressure on the pawn on c4. }
14. cxd5
{ We have to get rid of the c4-pawn, which can be potentially pinned by ...Ba6. }
14... Qxd5
{ Centralizing the Queen and intending to create a battery with ...Bb7. } 15.
Rfd1 { Threatening c4 now. After ...Nc5 the white Queen will be protected. }
15... Bb7 { Creating the battery and x-raying the pawn on g2. } 16. c4
{ We must kick the dangerous black Queen out of the center! It's the only way to avoid the mate threats, connected with the pawn on g2. }
16... Qd8
{ A weirder move, than the previous one. The black Queen is even more passive, than on d7 and still on the same file with the white Rook on d1. }
17. f3
{ There is nothing wrong with 17. Qe3 as in the previous line, but why not consider other options and plans? }
17... Nc5 18. Qe3 Qh4
{ It seems like the most active move in the position, but no man is an island! }
19. Bg5
{ You probably know that Rooks must occupy open files, but the same rule can be applied to Bishops and diagonals as well! It looks like the h4-d8 diagonal is too short to pay so much attention to it, however, there is still a big room for our Bishop. We're attacking the black Queen and aiming to invade the seventh rank with the Bishop. }
19... Qh5 20. Be7 { A double attack! } 20... Rfc8
{ If Black doesn't defend the Knight on c5, we will capture it with the Bishop and the black pawn on c5 will be dead after Nb3. }
21. Ne2
{ Our brain isn't programmed to consider moves back such as Ne2, for example, but just look at this beautiful move! We're liberating the d4-square for the Rook lift: Rd4-Rg4, and intending to transfer the Knight to the kingside via Ng3. }
