{ Black is going to meet Bh6 with ...Qg6. } 17. Nb5
{ One of the most typical manoeuvers in this type of the structure. It's so tempting to occupy either the c7- or d6-square, and why not do it? }
17... Ba6 { Finally developing the last undeveloped minor piece. } 18. Nd6
{ What a Knight! I just can't stop admiring it. } 18... Qg6
{ Offering us an exchange of the Queens. } 19. Qe3
{ Trading the Queens wouldn't be a huge mistake, but I believe that we still have a good chance to create an attack on the kingside. When you are an attacker, never exchange Queens! }
19... Bd3
{ This strange move was played by challenger Karjakin, but I think that he wanted to prevent Rd4, a rook lift. }
20. Rd2
{ Aiming to double the Rooks along the d-file. The great Knight on d6 and better coordination of the pieces secure us pleasant advantage. }
