17... Bb7 { Our task now is not to blunder the mate on g2! } 18. Be3
{ We postpone the Knight jump to d6 in order to threaten the Rook lift via Rd4 and Rg4. }
18... Qg6 { And again Black wants to go in the endgame. } 19. Qxg6
{ We can't decline this offer now, because the Queen is running out of moves. }
19... hxg6 20. Bxc5
{ But the bright sight is the exchange of the Knight, which was occupying the outpost on c5. }
20... bxc5 21. Rd6
{ This is a wonderful example of a position: a good Knight against a bad Bishop. The Knight can attack the pawn on c5 that is placed on the dark square and can't be defended by the Bishop or occupy some squares such as c4 or d6. Moreover, we control the d-file, which gives us a pleasant advantage. We can also centralize the King with Kf1-e2-d3-c4 in the future. }
