{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as   5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d5
{ The most principled way to fight for the center. Black is going to simply win the pawn on e4 with ...Ne4. }
6. e5
{ In my opinion, the only reasonable move. We avoid the pawn loss and win more space in the center. }
6... Ne4
{ The most principled reply. It's well known that a Knight should be centralized because it controls literally more squares and becomes more dangerous for an opponent. Besides, Black puts more pressure on the pinned c3-Knight in this situation. }
7. Bd3
{ The most popular move by a wide margin, which is not surprising at all, because we're attacking the central Knight on e4 and developing a minor piece, following one of the most important opening principles. }
7... c5
{ Black has to stick to the dynamic style of the opening line. Black attacks the d4-pawn, forcing us to defend it somehow. This is, by the way, a typical way to deal with such a 'French' pawn structure, when white pawns are placed on d4 and e5 and blacks - on d5 and e6. }
8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than 8. Nge2. White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... cxd4
{ One of the main advantages of Classical variation in Nimzo-Indian for White is the maintenance of our opponent in the permanent pressure and stress. Black must play extremely actively and precisely, otherwise, a game can end up in White's win quickly. }
9. Nxd4 { The only reasonable move. } 9... Nd7
{ If I were Black, I would actually choose this move among others, because Black develops a minor piece and attacks the e5-pawn.   9. ...Nc5  transposes to  10. ... Ndc5 }
10. Bf4
{ Defending the e5-pawn and finally finishing the development of minor pieces. We have reached a key point in our variation, where lines branch off and Black has two completely different approaches: getting a playable position after ...Ndc5 and playing a million precise moves to make a forced draw after ...Qh4. }
10... Qh4
{ The second one, ...Qh4, fits that kind of player, who likes the scientific side of chess and wants to challenge their opponent in the long opening lines. But we are ready, aren't we? }
11. g3 { We defend the Bishop on f4 with the tempo. } 11... Qh5
{ The best square for the Queen, to my mind. Black attacks the pawn on e5 and prepares the push of the pawn to g5 at some point in order to kick the Bishop out of the f4 square and capture the pawn on e5 afterward. }
12. O-O
{ The king safety first! We unpin the Knight on c3 and threaten to take the Knight on e4 on the next move. }
12... g5
{ It's that kind of the move, which you have to analyze at home and know precisely when you sit in front of the chess board opposite to your opponent or, in our crazy times, in front of the computer screen. }
13. cxd5
{ Choosing the most principled line. We're attacking the Knight on e4 now. }
13... Bxc3
{ An important intermediate move. Black has to eliminate the Knight before taking on d5.   13. ...Nxc3  14.dxe6  gxf4  15.exd7  Bxd7  transposes to this line  13. ... gxf4 }
14. bxc3 { There aren't any reasonable alternatives. } 14... exd5
{ After the Knight on e4 becomes protected, Black finally wants to capture the Bishop on f4. }
15. Be3
{ Intending either to capture the Knight on e4 or to kick it out with f3. }
15... Nxe5
{ We should by no means forget about our weak light squares on the kingside. One of the advantages of . ..Qh4 was the provoking of g2-g3, so we have to be careful now. Black threatens either ...Ng4 or ...Bg4, launching the deadly attack. }
16. f3
{ An essential both prophylactic and active move. We don't only prevent ...Ng4, but also drive the black central Knight away. }
16... Nxd3
{ An attempt to exploit the moment and to exchange the light-squared Bishop, while it's possible. It's 'well-known' that a Bishop is considered as a stronger piece than a Knight, however, we always have to evaluate every position separately. For instance, I'm not sure, that it's a good idea to exchange the central active Knight for the Bishop here. What piece is stronger? I think they are more or less equally good. }
17. Qxd3 Nd6
{ The Knight on d6 is more flexible and closer to the kingside. For example, Black can reply with ...Nc4 after Qd2. }
18. g4 { The only move, that gives us an advantage. } 18... Qg6 19. Qxg6+
{ We don't mind exchanging the Queens, because we win a pawn back on the next move. }
19... hxg6 20. Bxg5 { Threatening to create a double attack with Be7. } 20...
f6 { Preventing this threat, attacking the Bishop at the same time. } 21. Bf4
{ Attacking the Knight on d6. The most natural and the best move. } 21... Nc4
{ The best square for the Knight is usually in front of an isolated pawn, where it can't be attacked by opponent pawns. Black has a good outpost at c4, so why not set the Knight there? }
22. h4
{ There are no Queens on the board, so we can call this position an endgame. Therefore, it's not dangerous for us to push the pawns on the kingside and centralize the King. Moreover, we should do it! }
22... Bd7 23. Kf2
{ We want to create a passed pawn with h5, activate the Rooks with Rad1 and Rfd1 and put pressure on the isolated d5-pawn. }
