19. Nb5
{ Opening up the d-file for the Queen. We also force Black to exchange the active d6-Knight, because Nc7, followed by Nd5, is coming. }
19... Nxb5 20. Qxb5 { Again we're attacking the d5-pawn. } 20... b6
{ Aiming to develop the Bishop somewhere either to b7 or to e6. Black gives up a pawn back, attempting to get an initiative. Anyway, it's impossible to protect the pawns on d5 and g5 at the same time. }
21. Qxd5 { Attacking the a8-Rook and the g5-pawn. } 21... Be6 22. Qxg5+
{ If you are a real fighter or you just have to win on demand, you could keep the Queens on the board. However, I prefer to enter the endgame a pawn up. }
22... Qxg5 23. Bxg5 f5
{ Moreover, Black must spot the only move, that doesn't lead to a difficult position. Black wants to get rid of the isolated f-pawn and open up the f-file. }
24. Rfe1
{ Taking control over the e-file with tempo. We're going to centralize the King with Kf2 at some point and use our Rooks to invade the black side of the board. }
