16... Nxd3
{ An attempt to exploit the moment and to exchange the light-squared Bishop, while it's possible. It's 'well-known' that a Bishop is considered as a stronger piece than a Knight, however, we always have to evaluate every position separately. For instance, I'm not sure, that it's a good idea to exchange the central active Knight for the Bishop here. What piece is stronger? I think they are more or less equally good. }
17. Qxd3 Nd6
{ The Knight on d6 is more flexible and closer to the kingside. For example, Black can reply with ...Nc4 after Qd2. }
18. g4 { The only move, that gives us an advantage. } 18... Qh6
{ Not a very difficult novelty, but it seems to be an excellent choice for fighters, who want to keep the Queens on the board and discover which pawn structure is weaker. }
19. Nb5
{ Opening up the d-file for the Queen. We also force Black to exchange the active d6-Knight, because Nc7, followed by Nd5, is coming. }
19... Nxb5 20. Qxb5 { Again we're attacking the d5-pawn. } 20... Qc6
{ It's not the most logical decision in the world, as Black declined the Queen exchange few moves ago. }
21. Qxc6 { We don't mind going in the slightly better endgame. } 21... bxc6 22.
Bxg5
{ Winning back the pawn and destroying the pawn structure on the kingside. Black has two islands there. }
22... f5 { Black attempts to get rid of one of the islands. } 23. h3
{ Defending the g4-pawn. This ending is of course rather drawish, but Black still has some minor issues to deal with. For example, if we manage to invade the seventh rank with Re1-e7 and put pressure on the weak dark squares with the Bishop, Black will have a hard life. Basically, in an opposite-colored Bishop position you should aim to create an attack on a King, because your Bishop doesn't have an opponent. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Black plays 4...O-O: 10...Qh4 and 10...Qb6"]
[Black "Black plays 4.. O-O: 10.. Qh4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... O-O
{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as   5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d5
{ The most principled way to fight for the center. Black is going to simply win the pawn on e4 with ...Ne4. }
6. e5
{ In my opinion, the only reasonable move. We avoid the pawn loss and win more space in the center. }
6... Ne4
{ The most principled reply. It's well known that a Knight should be centralized because it controls literally more squares and becomes more dangerous for an opponent. Besides, Black puts more pressure on the pinned c3-Knight in this situation. }
7. Bd3
{ The most popular move by a wide margin, which is not surprising at all, because we're attacking the central Knight on e4 and developing a minor piece, following one of the most important opening principles. }
7... c5
{ Black has to stick to the dynamic style of the opening line. Black attacks the d4-pawn, forcing us to defend it somehow. This is, by the way, a typical way to deal with such a 'French' pawn structure, when white pawns are placed on d4 and e5 and blacks - on d5 and e6. }
8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than 8. Nge2. White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... cxd4
{ One of the main advantages of Classical variation in Nimzo-Indian for White is the maintenance of our opponent in the permanent pressure and stress. Black must play extremely actively and precisely, otherwise, a game can end up in White's win quickly. }
9. Nxd4 { The only reasonable move. } 9... Nd7
{ If I were Black, I would actually choose this move among others, because Black develops a minor piece and attacks the e5-pawn.   9. ...Nc5  transposes to  10. ... Ndc5 }
10. Bf4
{ Defending the e5-pawn and finally finishing the development of minor pieces. We have reached a key point in our variation, where lines branch off and Black has two completely different approaches: getting a playable position after ...Ndc5 and playing a million precise moves to make a forced draw after ...Qh4. }
10... Qh4
{ The second one, ...Qh4, fits that kind of player, who likes the scientific side of chess and wants to challenge their opponent in the long opening lines. But we are ready, aren't we? }
11. g3 { We defend the Bishop on f4 with the tempo. } 11... Qh5
{ The best square for the Queen, to my mind. Black attacks the pawn on e5 and prepares the push of the pawn to g5 at some point in order to kick the Bishop out of the f4 square and capture the pawn on e5 afterward. }
12. O-O
{ The king safety first! We unpin the Knight on c3 and threaten to take the Knight on e4 on the next move. }
12... g5
{ It's that kind of the move, which you have to analyze at home and know precisely when you sit in front of the chess board opposite to your opponent or, in our crazy times, in front of the computer screen. }
13. cxd5
{ Choosing the most principled line. We're attacking the Knight on e4 now. }
13... Bxc3
{ An important intermediate move. Black has to eliminate the Knight before taking on d5.   13. ...Nxc3  14.dxe6  gxf4  15.exd7  Bxd7  transposes to this line  13. ... gxf4 }
14. bxc3 { There aren't any reasonable alternatives. } 14... exd5
{ After the Knight on e4 becomes protected, Black finally wants to capture the Bishop on f4. }
15. Be3
{ Intending either to capture the Knight on e4 or to kick it out with f3. }
15... Nxe5
{ We should by no means forget about our weak light squares on the kingside. One of the advantages of . ..Qh4 was the provoking of g2-g3, so we have to be careful now. Black threatens either ...Ng4 or ...Bg4, launching the deadly attack. }
16. f3
{ An essential both prophylactic and active move. We don't only prevent ...Ng4, but also drive the black central Knight away. }
16... Nxd3
{ An attempt to exploit the moment and to exchange the light-squared Bishop, while it's possible. It's 'well-known' that a Bishop is considered as a stronger piece than a Knight, however, we always have to evaluate every position separately. For instance, I'm not sure, that it's a good idea to exchange the central active Knight for the Bishop here. What piece is stronger? I think they are more or less equally good. }
17. Qxd3 Nc5
{ Quite a dubious move. The black Knight is quite far away from the kingside, which only provokes the white attack. }
18. Qd2
{ Attacking the g5-pawn and putting more pressure on the kingside in general. Moreover, the d2-Queen and the e3-Bishop form a so-called "battery", which is an indicator of the excellent coordination of the pieces. }
18... h6
{ Defending the g5-pawn, but weakening the kingside at the same time. } 19. h4
{ Black has the terrible pawn structure and only one defender on the kingside, so we have to open up it instantly, because fate may not provide us with this chance. }
19... g4 { Attempting to keep the kingside closed. } 20. Ne2
{ What a quiet, but powerful move! The e2-Knight is going to land of f4. I always admire such Knight maneuvers. }
20... Ne6 { Preventing our plan. } 21. fxg4
{ Black was going to capture the pawn on f3, so we should avoid this pawn loss. }
21... Qxg4 22. Rf6
{ There is nothing wrong with taking on h6 with the Bishop immediately, but transferring the Rook to the h-file is even smarter. }
22... b6
{ With the idea of ...Ba6, disturbing the e2-Knight, that is the only piece that protects the g3-pawn. }
23. Rxh6
{ The point of transferring the Rook to the h-file is to create some mate threats with Qd3-Qh7. White is better, mainly because of the awful black King. }
*

