13. cxd5
{ Choosing the most principled line. We're attacking the Knight on e4 now. }
13... gxf4
{ Another big alternative that was played by such beasts like Caruana, Grischuk, Ding, Kramnik and Giri. }
14. dxe6
{ Before taking the e4-Knight it's a good idea to play this good intermediate move. }
14... Nxe5
{ This move is the best, the engine tells us.   14. ...Bxc3  15.bxc3  Nxe5  transposes to  13. ... Bxc3   14. ...fxe6  15.Nxe4  Nxe5  transposes below }
15. Nxe4
{ The difference between this position and the position after 15. ... Nxe5 in the main line is the availability of the Bishop on b4 and the Knight on c3, which gives us the extra possibility to take the e4-Knight with our Knight, at which we jump with pleasure. The Knight would like to land on f6 with a fork now. }
15... fxe6 { Preventing the fork. } 16. gxf4
{ This move is counterintuitive because we open up the g-file and expose our King, but we should not worry too much about it as we are going to hide the King on h1 and transfer the Rook to g1. }
16... Rxf4 17. Kh1
{ One of the main advantages of our position is the Knight on e4 that always threatens a fork on f6 and thus ties up the f4-Rook, which can't land on h4. }
17... Kh8 { A good prophylactic decision. Isn't Black just copying us? } 18.
Rg1
{ We take control over the g-file and aim to invade the seventh rank with Qc7. }
18... Nxd3
{ The position is extremely sharp, so if Black doesn't play actively, they could easily find themselves lost in a few moves. }
19. Qxd3
{ We threaten to play Qg3, attacking the Rook on f4 and creating dangerous threats along the g-file with a possible invasion of the Knight on g5. }
19... Be7 { It is vital for Black to take control over the g5-square. } 20.
Rac1
{ Getting out the last undeveloped piece and eyeing the tempting c7-square, where the Rook would love to land. White is better thanks to the centralized Knights, the wonderful Rooks, that occupy the open files and quite a bad black King. }
*

