{ Choosing the most principled line. We're attacking the Knight on e4 now. }
13... gxf4
{ Another big alternative that was played by such beasts like Caruana, Grischuk, Ding, Kramnik and Giri. }
14. dxe6
{ Before taking the e4-Knight it's a good idea to play this good intermediate move. }
14... Nxc3 { Another way to trade the c3-Knight. } 15. exd7
{ Quite an impressive number of intermediate moves, isn't it? } 15... fxg3
{ Black can also play this intermediate move. } 16. hxg3
{ We are forced to take, otherwise, we were going to get mated by ...Qxh2. }
16... Bxd7 17. bxc3 { Winning back a piece. } 17... Rac8
{ The most interesting way to protect the b4-Bishop - Black creates a pin on the c-file and attacks the c3-pawn. }
18. Bf5 { As the position is sharp, we should play actively. } 18... Bxc3
{ Black wants to take the a1-Rook with a discovered attack. } 19. Qd1
{ Avoiding the discovered attacks on the c-file and magically protecting all the hanging pieces. }
19... Qxd1 20. Raxd1
{ The d4-Knight is protected and the Rook isn't hanging anymore. } 20... Rc4
{ Black wants to get an opposite-colored Bishop ending. } 21. Bxd7 Rxd4 22.
Rxd4 Bxd4 23. Re1
{ White will get the passed f-pawn after the exchange of e- and f- pawns, which makes our position slightly better. }
*

