16... Qg6 { Placing the Queen on the same file with our King. } 17. fxe4
{ We shouldn't be afraid of exposing our King too much, because Black has the only Queen in the attack, and as you know very well: no man is an island. }
17... Bc5 { Pinning the d4-Knight. } 18. Be3 { We have to block the pin. }
18... e5
{ This is definitely the most challenging move because Black is going to give a fork with ...d4 on the next move. }
19. Nf5
{ We should play actively and put the Knight on the active position. The f5-square seems to be the right choice, doesn't it? }
19... d4
{ And again a fork! How many forks have we already seen in this line? A million? }
20. Na4 { Moving the Knight from the attack with tempo. } 20... Bxf5 21. exf5
{ We have to play extremely forcingly in a position like this. } 21... Qxg4+
{ Black wins the second pawn for the piece, which is still obviously not enough for full compensation. }
22. Qg2
{ Blocking the check with the Queen, removing all the questions whether the black attack is dangerous. }
22... Qxg2+ 23. Kxg2
{ We still attack the c5-Bishop, so Black can't win back a piece. } 23... Be7
24. Bf2
{ If you are an attacker, trade pieces, especially Queens! Black has only two pawns for a minor piece, so White is much better. }
