{ Our King is exposed now, but the black Queen is fortunately totally out of the queenside, therefore, it will be really difficult for Black to go for an attack. }
13... Ba3+ 14. Kb1
{ The computer tells us that even   14.Kd2  isn't that bad as it seems at first glance, but we have to go for more human and objectively stronger and safer Kb1. }
14... Nb6
{ The series of only moves will continue for a while. Black attacks the c4-pawn. }
15. Bf1 Qh5 { The only move that doesn't lose the Queen. } 16. Be2
{ Getting the Bishop out with tempo. } 16... Qh3
{ Even the engine doesn't understand for a while what is wrong with this move. How are we, people, supposed to understand? }
17. Nf3 { Aiming to continue chasing the black Queen with Ng5. } 17... Nxc4
{ This line illustrates very well how the black Queen can be trapped. } 18. Ng5
{ I'm a big fan of Knight manoeuvers! A Knight can totally change its position and task in just few moves. }
18... Qh6 19. h4
{ It's tempting to jump with the Knight somewhere but there aren't any good discovered attacks. Therefore, we have to overprotect the g5-Knight as Black threatens to play ...Be7, attacking the g5-Knight and liberating the a3-square for the Knight, which is going to land on a3 with a fork afterward. }
19... Be7 { Threatening a fork with ...Na3. } 20. Ka1
{ A good prophylactic move. Our King is quite safe now. } 20... Na3
{ We're following the game between two strong grandmasters Ganguly - Meier. Black ran out of reasonable moves, so we see ...Na3 on the board. The only reason to play this move is to give "gardez". This is how people called an attack on a Queen many centuries ago. }
21. Qd2 { Just moving the Queen away. } 21... Bd7 22. h5
{ Threatening to trap the Queen via the unstoppable Knight retreat, Nf3. } *

