13... f5
{ The computer first suggests this continuation as the way of equalization. And no wonder why. Black protects the centralized e4-Knight with all forces. }
14. cxd5 { Black loses the d5-pawn unless they exchange the e4-Knight. } 14...
Nxc3 15. bxc3
{ It's sometimes worth looking around and counting to understand whether we haven't lost anything along the way. }
15... Qxc3 16. Qe2
{ Of course, we don't go in the endgame, because it ends up just being a pawn down. We're attacking the e5-Knight and intending to win the b4-Bishop via Bd2. }
16... Nxd3 17. Rxd3
{ The black Queen surprisingly has the only good square to go. } 17... Qc4 18.
Be5
{ Although the engine still says, that White is only slightly better, I find the advantage overwhelming, as we're going to sacrifice the Bishop on g7, followed by Rg3 and a dangerous attack. It must be still objectively holdable for Black, but only with the help of the engine. }
