7. Bd3
{ The most popular move by a wide margin, which is not surprising at all, because we're attacking the central Knight on e4 and developing a minor piece, following one of the most important opening principles. }
7... c5
{ Black has to stick to the dynamic style of the opening line. Black attacks the d4-pawn, forcing us to defend it somehow. This is, by the way, a typical way to deal with such a 'French' pawn structure, when white pawns are placed on d4 and e5 and blacks - on d5 and e6. }
8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than 8. Nge2. White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... cxd4
{ One of the main advantages of Classical variation in Nimzo-Indian for White is the maintenance of our opponent in the permanent pressure and stress. Black must play extremely actively and precisely, otherwise, a game can end up in White's win quickly. }
9. Nxd4 { The only reasonable move. } 9... Nd7
{ If I were Black, I would actually choose this move among others, because Black develops a minor piece and attacks the e5-pawn.   9. ...Nc5  transposes to  10. ... Ndc5 }
10. Bf4
{ Defending the e5-pawn and finally finishing the development of minor pieces. We have reached a key point in our variation, where lines branch off and Black has two completely different approaches: getting a playable position after ...Ndc5 and playing a million precise moves to make a forced draw after ...Qh4. }
10... Qb6
{ It's not a very popular move, but we can't just skip it, because it was played by some grandmasters, including the former world champion Kramnik. The main idea of this move is to kick the white Knight out of the center, followed by attacking the e5-pawn. }
11. Nb3 { Threatening to take on e4, followed by the kingside castling. } 11...
Bxc3+ { The idea of this move is to damage the white pawn structure. } 12. bxc3
{ These doubled pawns are not that bad because we can always exchange the c4-pawn with cxd5. }
12... Qc7 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 13. O-O
{ Finishing the opening and indirectly protecting the e5-pawn. } 13... f6
{ Another way to put pressure on the pinned e5-pawn. } 14. Nd4
{ But the obvious drawback of this move is weakening the e6-pawn, which gives us a possibility to improve the Knight with tempos. }
14... Ndc5
{ Defending the e6-pawn and threatening to trade the light-squared Bishop with ...Nxd3. }
15. Nb5
{ I'm a big fan of such Knight zigzags! The Knight is jumping around and disturbing the black Queen. We can also invade the black camp with Nd6. }
15... Qb8 { Black tries to maintain the pin along the b8-f4 diagonal. } 16.
cxd5 { Undoubling the pawns and creating an isolated pawn on d5. } 16... exd5
{ It's probably the most natural move. } 17. Nd6
{ This invasion works out very well now. } 17... Nxd3
{ Let's check the most challenging line. } 18. Qxd3
{ Attacking the isolated d5-pawn. } 18... Nxd6
{ Taking on d5 with the Queen would be a crucial mistake as Black can block the check with ...Nf7. }
19. exd6
{ If we included the pawns on c4 and e6, Black would simply take the c4-pawn via dxc4, and the position appeared to be unclear. Now Black has the awful isolated d5-pawn, which secures a big advantage for us. }
*

