4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... O-O
{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as   5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d5
{ The most principled way to fight for the center. Black is going to simply win the pawn on e4 with ...Ne4. }
6. e5
{ In my opinion, the only reasonable move. We avoid the pawn loss and win more space in the center. }
6... Ne4
{ The most principled reply. It's well known that a Knight should be centralized because it controls literally more squares and becomes more dangerous for an opponent. Besides, Black puts more pressure on the pinned c3-Knight in this situation. }
7. Bd3
{ The most popular move by a wide margin, which is not surprising at all, because we're attacking the central Knight on e4 and developing a minor piece, following one of the most important opening principles. }
7... c5
{ Black has to stick to the dynamic style of the opening line. Black attacks the d4-pawn, forcing us to defend it somehow. This is, by the way, a typical way to deal with such a 'French' pawn structure, when white pawns are placed on d4 and e5 and Black's - on d5 and e6. }
8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than   8.Nge2  . White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move away from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves away from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... cxd4
{ One of the main advantages of Classical variation in Nimzo-Indian for White is the maintenance of our opponent in the permanent pressure and stress. Black must play extremely actively and precisely, otherwise, a game can end up in White's win quickly. }
9. Nxd4 { The only reasonable move. } 9... Nc5
{ It's an interesting pawn sacrifice! } 10. Bxh7+
{ We have to accept this challenge and go for the most ambitious line! It's too insipid just to castle kingside and allow Black to exchange the light-squared Bishop. }
10... Kh8
{ Black is going to either create the double attack on our Bishop on h7 and Knight on d4 with ...Qh4 or just capture the pawn on c4, opening up the d-file and again attacking our Knight. }
11. Nf3
{ Not the most obvious move in the world, because we, mere mortals, don't usually consider moves back. We always have an eye on the opponent King, we always want to play moves forward! Although if we look at this move straight, we'll find some reasonable points of it: we prevent ...Qh4, after ... dxc4 our Knight isn't attacked anymore and last but not least we transfer the Knight to the kingside. }
11... d4 { Oh, did we forget about the pin?... } 12. Ng5
{ No! Sacrificing the Knight on c3, we accelerate the attack on the kingside and create deadly threats. Our main plan is to transfer the Queen to h5. }
12... dxc3 { Otherwise Black would suffer only for a pawn. } 13. O-O
{ We can't blindly follow our plan without looking at the opponent's threats. The discovered check ...cxb2 is too dangerous to tolerate it. }
13... g6
{ Threats can be not only direct and obvious, such as a mate, a Queen capture or a double attack, but also positional, which is illustrated here very well. Black is going to play ...Qd3 and exchange the Queen because there is an excellent rule: when you are a defender, trade pieces! }
14. bxc3
{ Even while attacking, don't forget to collect opponent pieces and don't focus only on one part of the board. }
14... Ba3
{ One of the weirdest moves I've ever seen. Black distracts the Bishop to eliminate the dangerous Knight on g5. }
15. Bxa3
{ We're not only taking the Bishop on a3, but also attacking the Knight on c5. }
15... Qxg5 16. Bxc5
{ It's important to keep the initiative especially when you have sacrificed some pieces. }
16... Nd7
{ Giving up the exchange, but trading one of the most dangerous pieces in this position - the white dark-squared Bishop. }
17. Bxf8
{ The f6-square has been already covered by the Knight, so there aren't any practical chances to use the dark-squared Bishop. }
17... Nxf8 18. Bxg6 { Our Bishop is dead, so why not take at least one pawn? }
18... Qxg6 19. Qxg6 { When you're ahead in material, simplify the position! }
19... Nxg6 20. Rad1
{ Sacrificing the pawn on e5, but occupying the d-file and intending to invade the back rank with Rd8. It's always extremely difficult to get rid of such a pin without some material losses. }
*

