8. Nf3
{ I find this move much more active and natural than   8.Nge2  . White protects the pawn on d4 and prepares a kingside castling. We are fine according to Magnus Carlsen! 'The general rule for opening play is if you are one move away from castling, you are pretty much always fine. If you are three moves away from castling, you are almost never fine. If you are two moves away from castling, it could go either way.' }
8... Nc6
{ For example, such a natural and logical move as 8. ... Nc6 is a huge blunder. It's just too slow. }
9. O-O
{ Unpinning the c3-Knight and intending to capture the e4-Knight with Nxe4. }
9... Nxd4
{ there are many possible moves for Black, but I just want to pick one to illustrate White's big advantage. }
10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 { Attacking the h7-pawn. } 12... h6
{ Although the material is equal, it looks like a playable position even if Black has not fully equalized. }
13. Bf4
{ In fact, White is about to win a game thanks to an overwhelming advantage on the kingside and a weak pawn on d4. }
13... Bc5 14. Qe2
{ Transferring the Queen either to g4 or to h5. There are two main rules in any attack, which everyone should follow: open up the opponent King and bring all pieces in the attack. It's quite tricky to give a mate without involving a Queen in the attack. }
14... a5 15. Rad1 { Putting more pressure on an isolated pawn. } 15... a4 16.
Qh5
{ Black can't prevent both the sacrifice, Bxh6, and the rook lift, Rd3-g3. } *

