7... f5 { Another attempt to hold the Knight in the center. } 8. exf6
{ En passant! We destroy the support of the central Knight and damage the black pawn structure. }
8... Nxf6 9. Nf3 { Developing the Knight and defending the pawn on d4. } 9...
c5 { Black starts fighting for the center. } 10. a3
{ There is not a big difference between attacking the Bishop and taking the pawn on d5, but I prefer to include this quiet move to have the possibility to get rid of the pin with b4 at some point. }
10... Ba5
{ The most natural move - Black keeps the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 11.
cxd5 { A tricky move, that demands precise play for Black. } 11... cxd4
{ An important intermediate move. } 12. Nxd4
{ The Knight is perfect in the center and on d4 in particular. } 12... exd5 13.
O-O
{ Securing the King is our first priority. Moreover, the Knight on c3 isn't pinned anymore. }
13... Nc6 14. Nxc6
{ It's tricky to hold the Knight in the center or to support it. } 14... bxc6
15. Bg5
{ Creating the pin along the g5-d8 diagonal and attacking the pawn on h7. We should focus on the kingside, so it makes sense to bring more pieces there with Ne2-g3, for example. }
