{ Putting some pressure on the weak pawn on e6 } 14... Nxd4
{ Black decides to win the pawn, although isn't it too reckless to leave the pieces on the queenside totally undeveloped? }
15. Nxd4 Qxd4 16. Bb2
{ Developing the Bishop on the active square with the tempo, where it will be eyeing the kingside. }
16... Qe4 { When you are ahead in material, simplify the position! } 17. Qc3
{ Of course, we have to decline the Queen exchange offer and move our Queen somewhere. We create an excellent battery along the b2-g7 diagonal and pin the black Knight. Black is a pawn up, but our compensation is huge: the Bishop pair secures us the domination on the open diagonals, the terrible black pawn structure weakens the King and the black Queen will be chased all the time, as it's placed in the center and it's quite difficult to come up with a safe square for it. Our plan is to activate the Rooks with Rad1 and Rfd1, attacking the Queen and the pawn on e6, followed by some Rook lifts, such as Rd3-g3 or Re3-g3. }
