{ En passant! We destroy the support of the central Knight and damage the black pawn structure. }
8... Nxf6 9. Nf3 { Developing the Knight and defending the pawn on d4. } 9...
Nc6
{ Black threatens to take the c4-pawn, followed by winning the d4-pawn with ... Nxd4. }
10. Be3 { Defending the d4-pawn and developing the minor piece. } 10... Bd6
{ It looks quite weird to voluntarily retreat the Bishop, but Black liberates the b4-square for the Knight, which is going to land there with a fork. }
11. a3
{ Think prophylactically! We take control of the b4-square. Moreover, we intend to push the c-pawn forward, kicking out the black Bishop and grabbing the space on the queenside. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ Although the d4-pawn is isolated, it's not really weak, as it's well protected and there are many minor pieces on the board. }
12... Qe7 { Overprotecting the e6-pawn. } 13. Ng5
{ Activating the Knight. One of the most typical plans with an isolated pawn is pushing the pawn forward to exchange it and open up a position. Hence, we are going to play d5, opening up the c4-g8 diagonal. }
13... h6 { An attempt to get rid of the active Knight on g5. } 14. h4
{ However, our Knight is strongly fixed in place. Taking on  g5  with  14. ...hxg5  leads to catastrophic consequences after  15.hxg5  as the h-file becomes open and the white attack is unstoppable. }
