{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move because there are many good continuations such as   5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... d6
{ This is a more quiet alternative. Black wants to fight for the center with ...e5. }
6. e5
{ Since we have chosen the most fighting variation against the Nimzo-Indian, 4. Qc2, we should pursue this strategy and keep playing the most aggressive moves. }
6... dxe5
{ 6. ...Bxc3  7.bxc3  transposes to the  5. ... - other moves chapter. } 7.
dxe5
{ The main idea of placing the pawn on e5 is to cross the middle of the board and to gain a space advantage in the center. An achievement, like a gain of space advantage, does not come easy, because a far advanced pawn can be easier disturbed and attacked. }
7... Ng4
{ The most active way to attack the e5-pawn. A far advanced piece can be either attacked at the same time. One has to evaluate risks and make responsible decisions. }
8. Nf3
{ We develop a minor piece and defend the e5-pawn at the same time. The series of natural moves follow for a while. }
8... Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 9. Bf4
{ One more natural move that develops a minor piece and protects the e5-pawn. We want to take control of the d-file via Rd1 with tempo and trap, as anticipated, the quite vulnerable g4-Knight via h3. }
9... Nd4
{ Since Black has chosen the fighting ...Ng4 move, they must maintain the initiative. }
10. Qd2
{ It would be a big blunder to capture on d4   10.Nxd4  because after  10. ...Qxd4  Black has the double attack on the f4-Bishop and the e5-pawn. Therefore, we need to place the Queen on the safe d2-square, where it will be attacking the d4-Knight. }
10... f6
{ This is another approach. Black wants to take the f3-Knight, followed by eliminating the e5-pawn, which provides White a big space advantage. Moreover, the h3 threat is not that dangerous now, as Black can capture on e5 with ...Nxe5. }
11. O-O-O
{ Pinning the d4-Knight with the queenside castling is the only reasonable way to prevent ...Nxf3. Moreover, we put strong pressure on the d4-Knight. }
11... c5
{ Since the trapping of the g4-Knight with h3 has not been a threat anymore due to Nxe5, Black can afford to play quite slowly without capturing a piece on every move. }
12. Bd3
{ It's a good idea to develop a minor piece and connect the Rooks. Taking the d4-Knight   12.Nxd4  would be a blunder because of  12. ...cxd4  13.Qxd4  Qxd4  14.Rxd4  fxe5  forking the Rook and the Bishop. }
12... Bd7
{ Black also develops the light-squared Bishop, which intends to land on a4, where it will be attacking the d1-Rook and shooting along the a4-d1 diagonal. It will be also smart to transfer the Queen to the queenside with ...Qa5. }
13. exf6
{ We have to first launch the attack in the center and not to allow Black to take the initiative. }
13... Nxf6
{ Black again threatens to start the attack on the queenside with ...Ba4, followed by ...b5. }
14. Bd6
{ Attacking the f8-Rook and surprisingly pinning the c5-pawn with the threat to win the d4-Knight. }
14... Qa5
{ Giving up the exchange is the best decision Black can make here. Moving the Rook somewhere means a simple loss of the d4-Knight. If Black decides to save the material equality by trading the central Knight   14. ...Nxf3  15.gxf3  Rf7  The white Bishops dominate after  16.Be5  White is much better thanks to the open g-file, that can be occupied by Rhg1, the advantage of the Bishop pair, and great prospects on the kingside. }
15. Bxf8
{ It's also possible not to accept this forced sacrifice and play something like   15.Rhe1  but, in my opinion, a bird in the hand is worth two in the bush. }
15... Rxf8 16. Ne5
{ The e5-square is an excellent one for our Knight because it's on the opponent's side of the board and cannot be attacked by a pawn. }
16... Ba4
{ Since the c3-Knight has been pinned, Black is able to move the Bishop to a4. Moreover, Black aims to take control of the d-file with ...Rd8. }
17. Kb1
{ Moving the d1-Rook to e1   17.Rde1  is too dangerous because of  17. ...Bb3  I'm afraid, we will have to give up more than the exchange to escape. Don't be penny-wise and pound-foolish! }
17... Bxd1
{ We give back the exchange but the King becomes quite safe as there is not the annoying light-squared Bishop on the queenside anymore. }
18. Rxd1
{ We are going to launch an attack on the kingside with g4. Doubling the pawns with ...Bxc3 isn't a big problem for us because we will kick the central d4-Knight out of the center. White is better thanks to the perfectly centralized e5-Knight and better chances to create an attack. }
