{ This is a more quiet alternative. Black wants to fight for the center with ...e5. }
6. e5
{ Since we have chosen the most fighting variation against the Nimzo-Indian, 4. Qc2, we should pursue this strategy and keep playing the most aggressive moves. }
6... dxe5
{ 6. ...Bxc3  7.bxc3  transposes to the  5. ... - other moves chapter. } 7.
dxe5
{ The main idea of placing the pawn on e5 is to cross the middle of the board and to gain a space advantage in the center. An achievement, like a gain of space advantage, does not come easy, because a far advanced pawn can be easier disturbed and attacked. }
7... Ng4
{ The most active way to attack the e5-pawn. A far advanced piece can be either attacked at the same time. One has to evaluate risks and make responsible decisions. }
8. Nf3
{ We develop a minor piece and defend the e5-pawn at the same time. The series of natural moves follow for a while. }
8... Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 9. Bf4
{ One more natural move that develops a minor piece and protects the e5-pawn. We want to take control of the d-file via Rd1 with tempo and trap, as anticipated, the quite vulnerable g4-Knight via h3. }
9... Bc5
{ I find this decision not very logical because Black moves the Bishop second time for a short time without being forced. However, Black attacks the f2-pawn twice, making us react precisely. }
10. Rd1
{ This is the novelty I'm quite proud of. In our age of supercomputers, it's difficult to come up with a fresh idea on the tenth move. }
10... Bxf2+ { The most challenging move that must be checked twice. } 11. Qxf2
{ We'll see the series of the forcing moves for a while. } 11... Nxf2 12. Rxd8
{ If Black takes the d8-Rook, we will have two minor pieces for a Rook. } 12...
Nxh1 13. Rxf8+ { We have to play forcingly as much as possible. } 13... Kxf8
{ Black is a pawn and an exchange up, but the h1-Knight is "jailed". } 14. Nb5
{ Attacking the vulnerable c7-pawn. } 14... a6 15. Nxc7
{ We take a pawn with tempo. } 15... Rb8 16. a3
{ Preparing to advance the b-pawn and gain a space advantage on the queenside. }
16... Ke7 17. b4
{ We want to push the b-pawn forward to kick the c6-Knight out. } 17... Kd8
{ Black manages to trap our Knight. } 18. Nd5
{ But it's not that simple! We're sacrificing the Knight to get an overwhelming advantage in the center. }
18... exd5 19. cxd5
{ This is really a paradoxical position! Although Black is technically a Rook up, White has a huge advantage thanks to the great pawns in the center and the awful Knight on h1, that is not going to be rescued. If the c6-Knight retreats somewhere, we can create a discovered attack with e6. }
