{ 6. ...Bxc3  7.bxc3  transposes to the  5. ... - other moves chapter. } 7.
dxe5
{ The main idea of placing the pawn on e5 is to cross the middle of the board and to gain a space advantage in the center. An achievement, like a gain of space advantage, does not come easy, because a far advanced pawn can be easier disturbed and attacked. }
7... Ng4
{ The most active way to attack the e5-pawn. A far advanced piece can be either attacked at the same time. One has to evaluate risks and make responsible decisions. }
8. Nf3
{ We develop a minor piece and defend the e5-pawn at the same time. The series of natural moves follow for a while. }
8... Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 9. Bf4
{ One more natural move that develops a minor piece and protects the e5-pawn. We want to take control of the d-file via Rd1 with tempo and trap, as anticipated, the quite vulnerable g4-Knight via h3. }
9... Bc5
{ I find this decision not very logical because Black moves the Bishop second time for a short time without being forced. However, Black attacks the f2-pawn twice, making us react precisely. }
10. Rd1
{ This is the novelty I'm quite proud of. In our age of supercomputers, it's difficult to come up with a fresh idea on the tenth move. }
10... Qe8
{ This is a smart retreat. Although it looks much more tempting to play   10. ...Qe7  but it's much worse due to the following line  11.Rd2  defending the f2-pawn.  11. ...f6  this is the only way to get rid of the e5-pawn.  12.Bd3  Attacking the h7-pawn.  12. ...f5  Unfortunately, this must be played because ...Qh5 isn't possible as the black Queen is placed on e7.  13.h3  Kicking the active Knight out.  13. ...Nh6  A Knight on the rim is dim. This situation isn't an exception.  14.O-O  White is much better thanks to the terrible black pawn structure and the awful Knight on h6. Therefore, Black must play ...Qe8 to be able to transfer the Queen to h5 on occasion. }
11. Ne4
{ Protecting the f2-pawn and attacking the c5-Bishop at the same time. } 11...
Bb4+ { Black moves the Bishop with tempo. } 12. Ned2
{ This is really a sophisticated maneuver. The Knight is placed on d2 way better than on c3, because it doesn't block the c-file. It's important to have an option to play c5 in the next line. You'll see it soon. }
12... f6
{ Black attempts to get rid of the annoying e5-pawn as fast as possible. } 13.
Bd3 { Attacking the h7-pawn. } 13... Qh5
{ Black defends the h7-pawn and intends to capture on e5 with the Knight, as Black has enough attackers now. }
14. O-O { Just finishing the opening. } 14... Ngxe5 15. Bxe5
{ We should take on e5 with the Bishop in order to save the initiative. After   15.Nxe5  fxe5  the f4-Bishop will be attacked and we will kind of lose a tempo. }
15... fxe5 16. c5
{ We're going to occupy the great outpost on e4 with Knight. Moreover, the b4-Bishop appears to be trapped and it's not easy to come up with its rescue. }
