8. Nf3 { Again we develop a minor piece and defend the e5-pawn. } 8... h6
{ In general, this is a good prophylactic decision. However, Black has to play more actively. }
9. Bf4
{ It's difficult to come up with a better square than c6 for the black Knight, so we need the Bishop on f4 to protect the e5-pawn. }
9... c5
{ I find this move more interesting than ...Nc6 immediately, as Black wants to support the Knight on d4 with the c-pawn. }
10. O-O-O { Anyway, we need to castle queenside. } 10... Qa5
{ Putting more pressure on the c3-Knight. } 11. h4
{ We're going to execute an amazing plan! } 11... Nc6 12. Rh3
{ That's why we played h4! We have liberated the h3-square for the Rook, which aims to land on g3. }
12... Bxc3 13. bxc3
{ Although we have the damaged pawn structure on the queenside, our attack on the kingside is overwhelming. We want to expose the black King with Bxh6 and Rg3. }
