{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... O-O
{ We will concentrate on the most popular and natural black move in this chapter. }
5. e4
{ It took me really a long time to choose the most practical and challenging move for White on the fifth move, because there are many good continuations such as   5.a3  ,  5.Nf3  or  5.Bg5  I think, that we have to follow the fighting spirit of the classical variation of the Nimzo-Indian and go for the most principled lines. With 5. e4 we capture the center and force Black to show a decent level of opening knowledge or to think on their own from the first moves. }
5... c5
{ This is the third most popular move. Black undermines the center immediately. }
6. e5
{ We should reply with e5 as it's the only way to fight for an advantage. }
6... cxd4
{ Black goes for the sharpest continuation. The c3-Knight is pinned and attacked. }
7. a3
{ The mindless capture on  f6  7.exf6  would lead to a lost position.  7. ...dxc3  8.bxc3  Qxf6  The c3-pawn is surprisingly pinned as the a1-Rook isn't defended. So we have to kick the b4-Bishop out first. }
7... Bxc3+
{ I don't think that the exchange of the dark-squared Bishop can lead to something good. }
8. bxc3 { The f6-Knight is still attacked. } 8... Ne8
{ Black plays too passively. } 9. cxd4
{ Look at our wonderful pawns in the center! They provide us a big space advantage. But great power is always a great responsibility. We have to be careful about our pawns. }
9... d6 { Trying to decrease our power in the center. } 10. Nf3
{ We should protect the e5-pawn one more pawn. } 10... dxe5 11. dxe5
{ Our pawn structure is not that great as was before but the e5-pawn still secures a solid space advantage. }
11... Nc6
{ The most natural move. Black is going to take the e5-pawn, followed by ...Qa5. }
12. Bd3
{ Instead of the passive defense of the e5-pawn, I prefer to launch the attack instantly. We're attacking the h7-pawn. }
12... Nxe5 { The most challenging continuation. } 13. Nxe5
{ There is nothing wrong with taking the h7-pawn immediately. The move order doesn't matter. }
13... Qa5+ 14. Kf1
{ Blocking the check with   14.Bd2  would be a horrible mistake as we lose the a1-Rook after  14. ...Qxe5 }
14... Qxe5 { Attacking the a1-Rook. } 15. Bxh7+
{ Winning back a pawn with tempo. } 15... Kh8 16. Bb2
{ In the sharp positions it's important to play dynamically and keep the initiative. So we develop the dark-squared Bishop with tempo, placing it on the great a1-h8 diagonal. }
16... Qh5
{ This hardly can be considered as an initiative but Black also attempts to play forcingly. }
17. Bd3 { Retreating the Bishop to the safe square. } 17... Bd7 18. Re1
{ When you want to carry out an attack, you should follow two important rules: open up the opposing King and bring all the pieces into the attack. We definitely need the Rook in our attack. }
18... f5 { An attempt to close the kingside. } 19. Re3
{ We're going to play Rh3 on the next move. White has great prospects on the kingside. }
