{ If Black doesn't take the e5-pawn instantly, we can support it with f4 and increase our domination in the center. }
8. dxe5
{ The d-file becomes open now, which gives us an opportunity to put pressure on the d8-Queen with Rd1 in the future. }
8... Nfd7 { A safe retreat. } 9. Nf3 { We protect the e5-pawn. } 9... h6
{ This is prophylaxis against Ng5. } 10. Bd3
{ The obvious drawback of the previous black move is the slowness. In an opening, one should develop minor pieces as fast as possible instead of pushing pawns. }
10... Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 11. Ba3
{ A very good intermediate move! Instead of the simple defense of the e5-pawn with Bf4, we take advantage of the black fifth move ...Bxc3 and the open c1-a3 diagonal. }
11... Ncxe5
{ 11. ...Re8  is a natural but very passive decision. After  12.Rd1  Black is running out of the moves. }
12. Nxe5
{ Winning the exchange on f8 instantly   12.Bxf8  leads to the position with the terrible pawn structure after a good intermediate move  12. ...Nxf3! }
12... Nxe5 { Black opens up the d-file and attacks the d3-Bishop. } 13. Rd1
{ We want to win the black Queen with a discovered check Bh7. } 13... Nxd3+ 14.
Rxd3 { Black doesn't have a chance to save the exchange. } 14... Qg5
{ An attempt to create the counterplay on the kingside. Black is attacking the g2-pawn now. }
15. Bxf8 { Finally taking the f8-Rook. } 15... Qxg2 16. Rf1
{ For whose benefit was the g2-pawn captured? The g-file is open now, which gives us excellent chances to start the attack there. }
16... Kxf8 17. Rg3 { Taking control of the g-file. } 17... Qc6 18. Rfg1
{ Doubling the Rooks on the open g-file and attacking the g7-pawn. Although the material is equal, White's attack is crushing. }
*

