{ There are two main moves in this position: Bf4 and Bg5. Although Bg5 seems to be more active and tempting, according to my analysis it leads to an equal position. There is definitely more theory after Bf4, but it's worth studying it, as we get a chance to fight for the advantage in the interesting middlegame with many deep complicated plans. }
8... Bb7
{ Black has completed their plan and wants to push the d-pawn on the next move.   8. ...Nc6  9.Rd1  Bb7  transposes to the line below }
9. Rd1
{ It's not very typical to develop a Rook while the Bishop is still stuck on f1, but we should prevent ...d5 and Black cannot exploit our delay in the development. }
9... Nh5
{ Attacking the Bishop on f4. I find this move not very ambitious as Black normally offers a draw by retreating the Knight back to f6 after Bc1. }
10. Ng5
{ Of course, we play for a win and decline all the proposals for peace! We're threatening mate in one now. }
10... g6 { Black is forced to weaken the pawn structure on the kingside. } 11.
Bc1
{ We shouldn't forget about our hanging Bishop, so we get it to the safe square. }
11... Be7
{ This is an attempt to get rid of the annoying Knight on g5.   11. ...d5  It's overoptimistic to fight for the center this way as White has many pieces which attack the d5-square.  12.cxd5  We want to create an isolated pawn.  12. ...exd5  13.e4!  We're attacking the pinned d5-pawn one more time.  13. ...d4  14.b4  We shouldn't move our Knight anywhere as the d4-pawn is pinned.  14. ...Be7  15.Nf3  Again attacking the d4-pawn.  15. ...Nc6  16.Bb5!  The d4-pawn is under huge pressure and Black has to work really hard to save it. }
12. h4
{ The g5-Knight provides an opportunity for an attack on the kingside and keeps pressure on the opponent, so we should protect it instead of retreating. }
12... Nc6 13. e4
{ We have to develop the Bishop somehow, so we should push the e-pawn. Obviously, e3 doesn't work as we close the c1-g5 diagonal, so the only option is left. }
13... Qc7
{ Black connects the Rooks and intends to play ...Rad8, followed by ...Nf4.   13. ...f5?  is a huge blunder because of  14.Nxe6!  White is winning thanks to the pinned d7-pawn.     13. ...Rc8  is more logical. As usual, Black wants to put more pressure on the c4-pawn either with ... Ne5 or ... Na5.  14.Be2  Attacking the h5-Knight.  14. ...Ng7  15.Nf3  It looks weird to voluntarily retreat the Knight but we prevent ... Ne5 and prepare h5.  15. ...Na5  Attacking the c4-pawn.  16.b3  The black attack on the queenside isn't very promising while we want to either open up the kingside with h5 or attack the d7-pawn with Qd2. }
14. Nb5 { We should break the black plans and disturb the Queen. } 14... Qb8
15. Be2
{ Finally developing the light-squared Bishop and attacking the h5-Knight. It's too dangerous to take the pawn on d7 immediately   15.Rxd7  because of  15. ...a6  16.Nc3  Bd6!  And White has some problems with the Rook on d7. }
15... Nf4 { Attacking the g2-pawn. } 16. Rxd7
{ It is surprisingly a perfect moment to capture the d7-pawn despite the fact that our g2-pawn is hanging. }
16... a6
{ Taking on g2   16. ...Nxg2  leads to the lost position after  17.Kf1  Nf4  18.Rxb7!  a nice tactic  18. ...Qxb7  19.Bxf4  We have two minor pieces for a Rook. }
17. Nc3
{ Again we want to take on f4, followed by Rxb7. The Rook on the seventh rank is a beast! }
17... Bc8 18. Rxe7
{ We sacrifice the exchange to launch the attack as soon as possible. } 18...
Nxe7 19. h5
{ We aim to open the h-file to include the h1-Rook into the attack. We have a pawn as well as excellent prospects on the kingside for the sacrificed exchange. }
