8... Bb7
{ Black has completed their plan and wants to push the d-pawn on the next move.   8. ...Nc6  9.Rd1  Bb7  transposes to the line below }
9. Rd1
{ It's not very typical to develop a Rook while the Bishop is still stuck on f1, but we should prevent ...d5 and Black cannot exploit our delay in the development. }
9... d5
{ I don't think that pushing the pawn on the file where the opponent's Rook is placed, can be ever a good idea, but it was played by some strong players, including grandmasters, so we have to consider this line as well. }
10. cxd5
{ This is how you should normally reply to this move. We want to create the isolated pawn on d5. }
10... exd5 11. e3
{ Fixing the d5-pawn and intending to develop the light-squared Bishop. } 11...
Nbd7 12. b4
{ There is nothing wrong with developing the Bishop immediately, but by kicking out the black Bishop, we exclude the possibility of Black to play ...d4, which could be quite unpleasant. }
12... Be7 13. Bd3
{ Although we're blocking the d-file, the Bishop is much more active on d3 than on e2. }
13... Rc8 { Black pins our Knight on c3. } 14. Qb3
{ Before castling kingside, we should get rid of the pin on the c-file and put pressure on the d5-pawn at the same time. }
