10... Bb7 11. O-O-O
{ Since we have played h4, it's too dangerous to castle kingside. In addition, the Rook on d1 becomes really strong as it occupies the semi-open d-file. }
11... Nc6 { It looks like the most logical move here. } 12. e4
{ Sooner or later we have to develop the light-squared Bishop and e4 seems to me more active than e3 as we grab space in the center. }
12... Nf6
{ 12. ...h6  a more concrete approach  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.g4!  We launch the pawn storm on the kingside.  14. ...Nf4  15.g5  We want to either expose the black King with gxh6 or create a double attack on the f4-Knight and the d7-pawn with Qd2. }
13. e5
{ Opening the c2-h7 diagonal and attacking the f6-Knight. Not so easy for Black to find a good square for the Knight. }
13... Ng4 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 14. Bf4
{ The only reasonable way to protect the e5-pawn. } 14... Rc8
{ Black places the Rook on the one file with the Queen and the King. } 15. Kb1
{ A standard prophylactic move after queenside castling. } 15... f5
{ Black tries to grab some space. } 16. exf6
{ We should take en passant to open up the e-file as well as the c2-h7 diagonal. }
16... Nxf6 17. Ng5
{ Threatening to capture the e6-pawn as the d7-pawn is pinned and putting pressure on the h7-pawn. }
17... Qe8 { Moving the Queen away from the pin on the d-file. } 18. Bd3
{ Attacking the h7-pawn one more time. The problem is that if Black moves either the g-pawn or the h-pawn, then the kingside will be weakened so bad that Black won't have any chance to survive. }
18... Qh5 { Protecting the h7-pawn. But a Queen is a bad defender! } 19. Ne2
{ Transferring the Knight to g3, which is a crucial maneuver. White is winning. }
