{ This move has been not a very frequent guest in the elite division, but I believe, we should and we can breathe new life into this variation. }
8... Nd4 { The most principled move. } 9. Nxd4 { We have to take the Knight. }
9... Bxd4
{ Black threatens to exploit the pin along the d4-a1 diagonal with ... Ne4. }
10. e3 { Playing a useful move with tempo. } 10... Be5
{ Black should keep the Bishop on the big diagonal to maintain tension. All other retreats are worse. For example,  10. ...Bxc3  A trade of a Bishop for a Knight should be approached responsibly. I don't think, that this exchange is justified here.  11.Qxc3  b6  12.Bb2  We have a great battery, which consists of the b2-Bishop and the c3-Queen.  12. ...Bb7  13.Be2  Setting up a little trap.  13. ...Qe7  Taking on g2 would be a disaster because Black loses the f6-Knight after Rg1.  14.O-O  White has great pieces and a space advantage on the queenside.     10. ...Bb6  In my opinion, the Bishop is totally useless on b6.  11.Bb2  d5  An attempt to play actively.  12.Rd1!  Pinning the d5-pawn.  12. ...Qe7  13.c5  Now we have not only a space advantage on the queenside but also the pawn majority there.  13. ...Bc7  14.Bd3  Putting pressure on the h7-pawn. We are only one move away from being fully developed. White is better thanks to the pawns on the queenside and the excellent Bishops. }
11. Bb2
{ First of all, we should solve the issue with the pinned Knight on c3. } 11...
b6 { Intending to develop the light-squared Bishop. } 12. f4
