{ We threaten to win the pawn with Bxf6, followed by cxd5. } 8... Be7
{ Black blocks the pin and avoids the pawn loss. } 9. e3
{ We want to develop the light-squared Bishop. } 9... Nc6 10. Bd3
{ Attacking the h7-pawn. } 10... dxc4
{ 10. ...h6  Let's say, Black maintains the tension in the center.  11.Bf4  The Bishop is quite active on f4.  11. ...Nh5  On one hand, Black exchanges the Knight for the Bishop, which is, by all means, an achievement. On the other hand, Black loses several important tempos.  12.Rd1  Pinning the d5-pawn.  12. ...Nxf4  13.exf4  Qa5  Threatening to win the c3-Knight with ... d4  14.O-O  Although the f-pawns are doubled, our pieces are much better placed, especially the light-squared Bishop. }
11. Bxc4
{ We get the symmetrical pawn structure, but our light-squared Bishop is much better placed than the black one. }
11... Bd7 12. O-O { We have finished the development. } 12... h6 13. Bf4
{ Getting the Bishop to the open diagonal. } 13... Rc8 14. Rad1
{ Although the position is quite dry, our light-squared Bishop is much better as well as the black Queen feels quite uncomfortable. }
