1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... c5
{ One of the main aims of an opening is to establish control of the center, which allows us to be flexible and move our pieces from one part of the board to another relatively easily. In addition, control of the center usually secures the advantage of space. So Black undermines our central d4-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ If we support the d4-pawn with   5.e3  we might end up with an isolated pawn on d4 after  5. ...cxd4  6.exd4  d5!  And now it's Black who takes the initiative. So we have no choice but to capture the c5-pawn. However, I tend to estimate our chances to get the advantage in this variation to be pretty high. }
5... O-O
{ We have approached the first big critical moment in this line. It is no wonder that the main move is the kingside castling because this move looks logical and natural. Moreover, Black usually waits for a3 to be played, and only then they take the pawn on c5. }
6. a3
{ The excessive greed, like Be3, would significantly slow down the development and paralyze the kingside. In addition, Black aims to execute a nice Knight maneuver: ...Na6 and ...Nxc5. So we should force our opponent to define the position of the Bishop. }
6... Bxc5
{ Winning back the c5-pawn is, by all means, a more challenging decision than giving up the Bishop for the c3-Knight. }
7. Nf3
{ It's hard to come up with a more natural move than this one. However, even this move can be explained: we usually should develop Knights before Bishops. For example, in such classical openings like the Ruy Lopez or the Queen's gambit, we play either Nf3 or Nc3 before we move our Bishops. We have reached the second big critical moment in this variation, where Black has a big number of different approaches. }
7... Qb6 { Attacking the f2-pawn. This move looks scarier than it really is. }
8. e3
{ Simply blocking the f2-b6 diagonal and intending to drive the Bishop back from the center with b4. }
8... Qc7 { A weird move. I don't see the point of the whole ... Qb6 plan. } 9.
b4 { Again the same idea works very well here. } 9... Be7 10. Bb2
{ We have a chance to develop the Bishop to b2 now. Why not jump this opportunity? }
10... a6 { Preventing Nb5. } 11. Bd3 { Our Bishops are admirable. } 11... d6
12. g4
{ All our minor pieces have been developed, so I don't see the reason why we should postpone the attack. }
12... Nxg4
{ 12. ...h6  This only creates a possibility for us to open the kingside immediately.  13.g5!  hxg5  14.Nxg5  We're going to play Rg1 with an unstoppable attack. }
13. Bxh7+ { First of all, we should win back a pawn. } 13... Kh8 14. Rg1
{ Improving the Rook with tempo. } 14... f5 15. Rxg4
{ A charming combination. } 15... fxg4 16. Qg6
{ We're going to liberate the b2-g7 diagonal with a discover attack Nd5 in order to give mate with Qxg7 as well as simply to play Qh5. }
16... Rf6 { The only move that requires us to play precisely. } 17. Qe8+ Bf8
{ 17. ...Kxh7  is the most principled move  18.Ng5  A series of forcing moves follows, which ends up in mate after all.  18. ...Kh6  19.Qh8  Kxg5  20.Qxg7  Rg6  21.Ne4  Kf5  22.Ng3  Kg5  23.f4  gxf3  24.h4  Kxh4  25.Qxg6  The black King is dead. }
18. Nd5 { Including the b2-Bishop into the attack. } 18... exd5 19. Qh5
{ Intending to give mate in two with Bg6 and Qh7.   19. ...Rh6  isn't possible anymore because of  20.Qxh6!  the g7-pawn is pinned. }
*

