{ We have approached the first big critical moment in this line. It is no wonder that the main move is the kingside castling because this move looks logical and natural. Moreover, Black usually waits for a3 to be played, and only then they take the pawn on c5. }
6. a3
{ The excessive greed, like Be3, would significantly slow down the development and paralyze the kingside. In addition, Black aims to execute a nice Knight maneuver: ...Na6 and ...Nxc5. So we should force our opponent to define the position of the Bishop. }
6... Bxc5
{ Winning back the c5-pawn is, by all means, a more challenging decision than giving up the Bishop for the c3-Knight. }
7. Nf3
{ It's hard to come up with a more natural move than this one. However, even this move can be explained: we usually should develop Knights before Bishops. For example, in such classical openings like the Ruy Lopez or the Queen's gambit, we play either Nf3 or Nc3 before we move our Bishops. We have reached the second big critical moment in this variation, where Black has a big number of different approaches. }
7... a6 { Preventing Nb5 and preparing ...b5 at some point. } 8. Bf4
{ As usual, we develop the Bishop to f4. } 8... b5
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice.   8. ...Nc6  A simple Knight development doesn't look logical in combination with the ...a6 move.  9.e3  d5  Fighting for the center.  10.Rd1  Pinning the d5-pawn.  10. ...Qa5  11.Nd2  The Knight threatens to land on b3 with a fork.  11. ...Be7  12.Be2  We are much better developed, so we can choose between a calm continuation castling kingside or launching the attack with ambitious g4. }
9. cxb5 { It's not a mistake to play e3 to protect the c4-pawn. } 9... axb5 10.
e3
{ Taking on b5 with   10.Nxb5  leads to unnecessary complications after  10. ...Bb4! }
10... b4 { An attempt to exploit the pinned a3-pawn. } 11. Na4
{ Surprisingly, the c5-Bishop cannot leave the c-file because of Bc7 and Nb6 afterward. }
11... d6 12. Nxc5 { Finishing our little maneuver. } 12... dxc5 13. Bc4
{ Finishing the development of minor pieces.   13.Qxc5  It's too dangerous to take the c5-pawn because our kingside is totally undeveloped.  13. ...bxa3!  14.Rxa3  Nbd7  And we are still two moves away from being castled. Black has a good initiative. }
13... Bb7
{ Developing the Bishop to the open diagonal and aiming to double the pawns at some point. }
14. O-O { We have completed the development finally. } 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3
{ Although the doubled pawns might look not very beautiful, we have exchanged a strong light-squared Bishop. }
15... Nc6 16. Rfd1 { Taking control of the only open file in this position. }
16... Qb6 17. a4
{ Creating an outside passed pawn, which may play a huge role later, in the endgame, for instance. In addition, we have a bishop pair advantage as well as control of the open d-file. }
