8... Nxg4 { We should analyze the straightforward capture of the g-pawn. } 9.
Rg1 { Attacking the g4-Knight and x-raying the g7-pawn. } 9... Ne5
{ An attempt to save the g7-pawn.   9. ...Nxh2  Winning the second pawn is, by all means, overoptimistic.  10.Nxh2  Qxh2  11.Rxg7  Winning back the first pawn.  11. ...Nc6  12.a3  We're going to play b4, followed by Bb2 and castling queenside. It's still a big question how to hide the black King and to develop the light-squared Bishop. In addition, our Rook on g7 puts huge pressure on the h7-pawn as well as on the f7-pawn. }
10. Nxe5 { It's too slow to spend a tempo to defend the f3-Knight. } 10... Qxe5
{ Protecting the g7-pawn. } 11. f4
{ A drawback of a centralized Queen is that it can be relatively easily attacked. }
11... Qf6 12. Bd2 { Developing the Bishop and intending to castle queenside. }
12... Qh4+
{ Trying to create a counterplay. But again, it's a bad idea to move the Queen all the time while the minor pieces on the queenside are still not developed. }
13. Rg3
{ We don't want to lose the right to castle, and the pin along the e1-h4 diagonal isn't dangerous at all. }
13... Qxh2 { Winning the second pawn, but losing time. } 14. Rh3
{ Saving the Rook with tempo. } 14... Qg1 15. O-O-O
{ I hardly believe, that Black can come out of this alive. We're going to regroup our pieces with Ne4 and Bc3, followed by winning everything on the kingside. }
