{ If we support the d4-pawn with   5.e3  we might end up with an isolated pawn on d4 after  5. ...cxd4  6.exd4  d5!  And now it's Black who takes the initiative. So we have no choice but to capture the c5-pawn. However, I tend to estimate our chances to get the advantage in this variation to be pretty high. }
5... Bxc5
{ Black decides to capture the c5-pawn immediately, without castling kingside. It may transpose to the main line 4. .. . O-O. However, Black can choose a different path. }
6. Nf3 Qb6
{ This is the point of taking the c5-pawn so early. Black mobilizes the Queen immediately to attack the f2-pawn.   6. ... 0-0  7.a3  transposes to the 5. ... - O-O     6. ...b6  7.Bf4  Bb7  8.a3  0-0  transposes to the 5. ... O-O }
7. e3 { The only reasonable way to protect the f2-pawn. } 7... Be7
{ This is one more way to avoid the Na4-fork. } 8. e4
{ Threatening to push the e-pawn forward and liberating the c1-g5 diagonal for the c1-Bishop. }
8... d6 { Preventing e5. } 9. Be3
{ It always makes me happy to develop a piece with tempo. } 9... Qa5
{ Pinning the c3-Knight.   9. ...Qc7  There is not a big difference between this and the main move. However, I like this move less because of the extra possibility of Nb5  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  a6  Preventing Nb5.  12.Rfd1  We have the same pawn structure as in the main line, where White should be slightly better. }
10. Be2 { Developing the last minor piece. } 10... O-O 11. O-O a6 12. Rac1
{ This is a standard Maroczy pawn formation, where White is better thanks to a space advantage and the weak d6-pawn. It's usually difficult for Black to break through with ...d5 because of the c- and e-pawns. }
