9. Bd2
{ We're quite happy to exchange the opposite Bishop with our Bishop indeed! }
9... Bxd2+
{ Voluntarily exchanging the Bishop, which I find is not the most challenging way to deal with this position. }
10. Qxd2
{ The Queen is already eyeing the d6-square, which will play an important role a little bit later. }
10... Qc7 11. c5
{ Again we totally paralyze the black queenside with this superb move. } 11...
Nc6 12. Nb6 { Occupying a great outpost. } 12... Rb8 13. Qd6
{ We are burying the black pieces on the queenside alive. } 13... Qxd6 14. cxd6
{ All we should do now is to play carefully and not to allow Black to get out of it without material loss. }
14... Nb4
{ Threatening a fork with ...Nc2. According to the engine, the best move is   14. ...Nd5  But after  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Rd1  We're simply winning the d5-pawn. }
15. Rc1 { We avoid the fork and attack the c8-Bishop. } 15... O-O
{ Black is going to exchange the great Knight on b6 with ...Nfd5. } 16. Bc4
{ Preventing ...Ne4. It turns out that Black is buried forever if play carefully enough. }
