{ We'll see a lot of transpositions to the 5. ... O-O in this line. However, there are several lines, which don't transpose anywhere. }
7. a3
{ Preparing one of the most common plans in this variation - b4. We're going to grab space on the queenside and drive the c5-Bishop away. }
7... d5 { Black starts fighting for the center. } 8. b4
{ Since Black hasn't prevented b4, why not proceed with our original plan? }
8... Be7 { Retreating the Bishop to the safest square. } 9. e3
{ Defending the c4-pawn. } 9... O-O 10. Bb2
{ It doesn't make sense to develop the light-squared Bishop first, because we will just lose a tempo after dxc4. So the right strategy is to put off the f1-Bishop development as far as we can. Now we're threatening to pin the d5-pawn with Rd1. }
10... dxc4
{ Black is more or less forced to take on c4, otherwise, the d5-pawn may become isolated or pinned. }
11. Bxc4
{ As you can see, we have managed to develop the light-squared Bishop without tempo loss. }
11... a6 { Intending to play ...b5 with tempo, followed by ...Bb7. } 12. Rd1
{ Activating the Rook with tempo. } 12... Qc7 13. Ne4
{ The position looks absolutely safe but the reality is that we still have to play carefully. For example, after   13.O-O  Black can win the pawn with an unexpected discovered attack  13. ...Nxb4!  So we should play first Ne4, and only then we're going to castle kingside. Although the pawn structure is symmetrical, White is much better thanks to the great Bishop pair. }
