{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... c5
{ One of the main aims of an opening is to establish control of the center, which allows us to be flexible and move our pieces from one part of the board to another relatively easily. In addition, control of the center usually secures the advantage of space. So Black undermines our central d4-pawn. }
5. dxc5
{ If we support the d4-pawn with   5.e3  we might end up with the isolated pawn on d4 after  5. ...cxd4  6.exd4  d5!  And now it's Black who takes the initiative. So we have no choice but to capture the c5-pawn. However, I tend to estimate our chances to get the advantage in this variation to be pretty high. }
5... Na6
{ This is another way to win back the c5-pawn. Black relies rather on the Knight than on the Bishop in this variation. }
6. a3 { We force Black to decide on a plan and where to place the Bishop. }
6... Bxc3+
{ This is the most consistent continuation as Black wants to finish their original plan with transferring the Knight to c5. }
7. Qxc3
{ If we took the Bishop on c3 with the b2-pawn, this position might easily get in a book of funny chess memes. }
7... Nxc5 { Black wants to stabilize the queenside with ...b6 and ... Bb7. } 8.
b4
{ For that reason, we should play actively and be the first who takes initiative on the queenside. }
8... Nce4 { Centralizing the Knight with tempo. } 9. Qb2
{ It looks a little bit weird to retreat the Queen to b2.   9.Qc2  looks way more natural, but allows  9. ...Nxf2!?  10.Kxf2  Ng4  11.Ke1  Qf6!  Since the white Queen has been placed on c2, the f6-square hasn't been controlled. Black is attacking the a1-Rook and threatening ... Qf2. White still could get a big advantage after 11. Kg3! but the position becomes way too complicated. }
9... d5
{ Black fights for the center and prepares ...Nd6, if f3 is played.    In addition, we threaten to significantly worsen the position of the e4-Knight with f3. For example, after inaccurate   9. ...O-O?  10.f3!  Nd6  The only available square for the Knight.  11.e4!  Threatening e5. The black Knights find themselves in big trouble. }
10. c5
{ A wonderful move. We take control of the d6-square and threaten to trap the black Knight with f3 on the next move. Furthermore, we create a pawn majority on the queenside. }
10... d4 { Black creates the escape square on c3 for the Knight. } 11. e3
{ We don't only undermine the center, but also liberate the f1-a6 diagonal for our Bishop. }
11... Ng4
{ Attacking the f2-pawn. However, you cannot just rush up and start an attack without preconditions. Black will be punished for that. }
12. Nh3
{ Protecting the f2-pawn. Although we place the Knight on the edge of the board, it's pretty useful here. Threatening to win the d4-pawn with exd4. }
12... dxe3
{ 12. ...Nc3  The Knight seems to be very unstable here.  13.Bd2  Putting some pressure on it.  13. ... 0-0  14.exd4  The c3-Knight becomes unprotected  14. ...Nd5  15.Be2  Driving one more Knight out of our territory.  15. ...Ngf6  16. 0-0  We're going to improve our Knight with either Ng5 or Nf4. Black doesn't have any compensation for a pawn. }
13. Qxg7
{ Choosing the most principled continuation. Attacking two pieces at the same time. }
13... exf2+
{ 13. ...Ke7  This is an interesting way to protect the h8-Rook.  14.f3  Creating a fork.  14. ...Rg8  15.Qb2  Nef2  The only way to save the Knight.  16.Nxf2  Nxf2  17.Bxe3  Sacrificing the h1-Rook for a huge initiative.  17. ...Nxh1  18.Bd4  Threatening Bf6.  18. .. .Rg6  19.O-O-O  Threatening to win the d8-Queen again with Bf6  19. ...Qe8  20.Bc4  The h1-Knight is trapped, so we're going to get almost the full material equality. Black cannot really hope to survive with such a bad King. }
14. Nxf2
{ Since the h8-Rook has been hanging, we can afford to sacrifice the Knight. }
14... Qf6 { Defending the h8-Rook and saving the g4-Knight at the same time. }
15. Qxf6
{ Taking on g4   15.Qxg4  would be too dangerous because of  15. ...Qxf2  . }
15... Ngxf6 16. Bb2 { What a great Bishop and a pin! } 16... Rg8
{ Getting the Rook out of this x-ray. } 17. Bd3
{ Activating the Bishop and attacking the e4-Knight. } 17... Nxf2 18. Kxf2
{ We are much better due to our great Bishop pair. I can hardly imagine, that Black can come out of this without material loss on the kingside. }
*

