{ Black fights for the center and prepares ...Nd6, if f3 is played.    In addition, we threaten to significantly worsen the position of the e4-Knight with f3. For example, after inaccurate   9. ...O-O?  10.f3!  Nd6  The only available square for the Knight.  11.e4!  Threatening e5. The black Knights find themselves in big trouble. }
10. c5
{ A wonderful move. We take control of the d6-square and threaten to trap the black Knight with f3 on the next move. Furthermore, we create a pawn majority on the queenside. }
10... h6
{ Surprisingly, it's also a way to save the e4-Knight. Black prepares the retreat ...Ng5. }
11. f3
{ Anyway, we should kick the Knight out of the center and worsen it as much as possible. }
11... Ng5 12. h4 { Forcing Black to move the Knight to the corner. } 12... Ngh7
13. Bf4
{ Developing the Bishop to the most active position and threatening to deprive Black of the right to castle with Bd6. }
13... O-O { Black castles in the nick of time. } 14. e3
{ We want to develop all the minor pieces. } 14... Nd7
{ Preparing ...e5.   14. ...Re8  with the idea to activate the h7-Knight with ...Nf8, followed by ...Nf8-d7  15.Bb5!  is a clever move, as we force Black to occupy the d7-square immediately, making the above-mentioned maneuver impossible.  15. ...Bd7  16.Bd3  We're going to finish the development with Ne2 and Kf2, followed by a pawn storm with g4. }
15. Bb5 { Taking control of the b5-e8 diagonal and x-raying the e8-square. }
15... a6
{ 15. ...e5  doesn't make sense anymore, as Black won't be able to occupy the semi-open e-file with ... Re8 afterward. }
16. Ba4
{ It's important to keep the Bishop on the a4-e8 diagonal. We're going to develop the Knight to e2 on the next move. White is much better due to the Bishop pair, the pawn majority on the queenside and the passive black Bishop on c8 and the Knight on h7. }
