9... Nd6 { Black transfers the Knight to c4. } 10. c5
{ The most principled move. We grab space and chase the black Knight. } 10...
Nc4
{ 10. ...Nf5  Apparently, Black is having trouble finding a good square for the Knight.  11.g4!  An unexpected combination! We want to open the g-file.  11. ...Nxg4  12.Nf3  Developing the Knight and liberating the g1-square for the Rook.  12. ...Nf6  13.Rg1  Taking control over the g-file and intending to eliminate a defender of the g7-pawn with Bh3.  13. ...Rg8  14.Bg5!  Threatening Bxf6. White has huge compensation for the sacrificed pawn thanks to the active pieces and the totally blocked c8-Bishop and the black King in the center. }
11. Qc3
{ In my opinion, we should keep the Queen on the a1-g7 diagonal, because we're going to create a battery there in the future. }
11... d5
{ Defending the c4-Knight.   11. ...b5  This is another way to protect the c4-Knight.  12.e4!  Using the fact, that the f6-Knight is pinned, we grab space on the center and attack the c4-Knight.  12. ...Bb7  13.Bxc4  getting rid of the only active black piece  13. ...bxc4  14.f3  Before winning the c4-pawn, we stabilize the center.  14. ...d6  15.Be3  There is nothing wrong with winning the c4-pawn now, but in any case, it cannot run anywhere.  15. ...O-O  16.cxd6  Black cannot take back the d6-pawn because of Bc5! }
12. e4
{ A powerful combination! We open the f1-c4 diagonal to attack the c4-Knight and create big tension in the center. }
12... b5
{ An interesting way to protect the c4-Knight one more time. Accepting the sacrifice with   12. ...Nxe4  is, probably, the most challenging continuation.  13.Qxg7  We can see now, why it was important to keep the Queen on the big diagonal.  13. ...Qf6  defending the h8-Rook.  14.Qxf6  Nxf6  15.Bg5  developing the Bishop with tempo.  15. ...Ne4  16.Bh4  Rg8  17.Bxc4  exchanging the f1-Bishop, which hasn't made any moves, for the c4-Knight, which has already made five moves. A good trade, isn't it?  17. ...dxc4  Black wants to break through the queenside with ...a5.  18.Ne2  Intending to drive the e4-Knight away with f3, as the c3-square has been controlled.  18. ...Rxg2  19.O-O-O  Threatening mate in one with Rd8. We shouldn't hope that Black will blunder this mate, but, anyway, we have a great compensation for a pawn, because the black pieces on the queenside are still not developed and our pieces are much better coordinated. }
13. Bxc4 { Again, by exchanging the c4-Knight, we win a lot of tempos. } 13...
bxc4
{ 13. ...dxc4  is equally good.  14.f3  defending the e4-pawn.  14. ...O-O  15.Ne2  Qe7  16.O-O  We aim to pin the f6-Knight with Bg5. Our Bishop is incomparably better than the black one. }
14. Ne2
{ The e4-pawn is still invulnerable, so we can afford not to waste a tempo to protect it. }
14... O-O { Taking on e4   14. ...Nxe4  would allow  15.Qxg7 } 15. Bb2
{ Creating a battery on the big a1-h8 diagonal. The f6-Knight is being under big pressure now. }
15... Bd7 16. exd5 { Making the d5-pawn isolated. } 16... exd5 17. O-O
{ We're going to attack the d5-pawn with Rad1 and transfer the Knight to the kingside with Ng3. }
