{ Pinning the a3-pawn and putting more pressure on the c3-Knight. Black threatens to damage our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. This is, by all means, the most active way to save the b4-Bishop. }
7. Bd2 { We have to defend the c3-Knight. } 7... Nxc5 8. f3
{ We aim to take control of the center with e4. } 8... Bxc3
{ Although the Bishop wasn't hanging, it's psychologically hard to maintain tension. That's probably why this move is the most popular one. }
9. Bxc3
{ We don't want to simplify the position by exchanging the Queens with Qxc3. }
9... Qa4 { Black would be happy to transpose into the endgame. } 10. Qd2
{ Intending to transfer the Queen to the kingside. } 10... Nb3
{ The most principled reply. } 11. Qg5
{ Sacrificing the a1-Rook for a huge initiative on the kingside. } 11... Nxa1
{ It's too late to call the original plan off. } 12. Qxg7
{ Attacking two pieces at the same time. } 12... Rg8 13. Qxf6
{ Black is still an exchange for a pawn up, but the dark squares together with the King are extremely weak. }
13... Qxc4 14. e3
{ Opening the f1-a6 diagonal for the light-squared Bishop with tempo. } 14...
Qc5 { Attacking the e3-pawn. } 15. Kf2
{ The f2-King is relatively safe. We're going to develop the Bishop to d3, attacking the h7-pawn. We have great compensation due to the awful black pieces on the queenside, the King, and the weak dark squares. }
*

