dxc4
{ Black wants to get rid of tension in the center and get a symmetrical pawn structure. }
10. Bb4
{ We drive away the Queen and deprive Black of the right to castle kingside. }
10... Qc7 11. Bxc4
{ Developing the Bishop without time loss.   11.a4  doesn't work now because of  11. ...Na6  12.Ba3  Qa5!  is a quite unpleasant check. }
11... Na6
{ Blacks doesn't want us to retreat to c3, so that's why Black decided to make this little concession - develop the Knight to the edge of the board. }
12. Bd2
{ 12.Bb5  is possible, but the series of exchanges follows, which leads to a nearly equal position. }
12... Bd7 { Threatening to pin the c4-Bishop with ...Rc8. } 13. Rc1
{ We should overprotect the c4-Bishop to be prepared for the ...Rc8 move. }
13... Rc8 { ...b5 can be quite unpleasant on the next move. } 14. Nf3 O-O
{ 14. ...b5  is possible, but not so dangerous, as it could be.  15.Bd3  Qb7  And the black Queen doesn't attack the g2-pawn, so we can simply retreat the Queen.  16.Qb1 }
15. Qb1
{ Threatening to win the Knight on a6. If Black doesn't blunder the discovered attack, we will castle kingside and enjoy our Bishop pair in an open position. }
