7. e3 { Protecting the c4-pawn. } 7... Nc6
{ By refusing to immediately fight in the center, Black settles for a worse position. }
8. a3 { Forcing Black to exchange the dark-squared Bishop. } 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ The c3-Bishop is very well placed, as it takes control of the c3-g7 diagonal. We want to play b4 as well. }
9... a5
{ Preventing b4, but weakening the b5-square.   9. .. .Qe7  Voluntarily retreating the Queen to the safe square to avoid possible attacks.  10.Nf3  d6  11.Be2  Not blocking the semi-open d-file  11. ...e5  12.O-O  O-O  13.Rfd1  We're going to attack the d6-pawn as well as grab space on the queenside with b4. }
10. Nf3
{ Since b4 has been not possible anymore, we should simply develop our pieces. }
10... e5
{ Black fights for the center.   10. ...d5  Another way to fight for the center is also possible.  11.b3  Defending the c4-pawn and intending to play Qb2 at some point.  11. ...O-O  12.Qb2!  Creating a strong battery.  12. ...dxc4  13.Bxc4  And again a Bishop pair and a battery give us a stable advantage. }
11. b3
{ Black wouldn't mind fixing the white pawns on the queenside with ...a4, so we should prevent this move. In addition, the b2-square is an excellent square for our Queen, as we have already seen many times in the previous lines. }
11... d6 12. Be2
{ 12. Bd3 is also possible, but I don't want to block the d-file. In addition, the ...e4 fork will be always an annoying threat, with which we must reckon. }
12... O-O 13. O-O
{ We're going to transfer the Rook to the d-file to attack the d6-pawn and launch a pawn storm with b4. }
