{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... d5
{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep the tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... exd5
{ There are two main continuations: ...exd5 and ...Qxd5, the so-called Romanishin system. After the text move, Black should be ready to play with an isolated d5-pawn in many lines. However, the c8-Bishop becomes active. }
6. Bg5 { We pin the f6-Knight, making Black uncomfortable. } 6... h6
{ This is undoubtedly a useful move, creating an escape square, even if Black doesn't play ...g5 afterwards.   6. ...c5  7.dxc5  h6  8.Bh4  transposes to the line below   6. ...O-O  7.e3  h6  8.Bh4  c6  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
7. Bh4
{ It doesn't make any sense to take on f6   7.Bxf6  due to  7. ...Qxf6  and we cannot capture the d5-pawn because our c3-Knight is being pinned. So we should just maintain a pin. }
7... c5
{ Black plays quite logically. They use the weakness of the d4-pawn to take initiative.   7. ...c6  8.e3  Nbd7  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Nge2  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
8. dxc5
{ The most principled continuation. We're winning a pawn, forcing Black to show their compensation, if there is, of course. }
8... g5
{ Quite a risky move, which weakens the kingside a lot. On the other hand, Black makes the f6-Knight free again.   8. ...d4  This tempting move doesn't work out because of  9.O-O-O  All of a sudden, we remember, that we have the right to castle queenside.  8. ...Nc6  9.e3  g5  10.Bg3  Black cannot defend the d4-pawn. White is much better. }
9. Bg3 { The only reasonable reply. } 9... Ne4
{ This is the point of the previous move. The black Knight has not been pinned anymore, and it's able to put quite a strong pressure on the c3-Knight. }
10. e3
{ We intend to develop the f1-Bishop to d3, driving away the e4-Knight. } 10...
Qa5 { Attacking the c3-Knight the third time. } 11. Rc1
{ Is slightly less popular than   11.Nge2  , but no less strong. } 11... Qxa2
{ Accepting the pawn sacrifice is, by all means, the most challenging continuation. }
12. Bb5+
{ We have sacrificed a pawn to quickly finish the pieces development and take initiative. }
12... Bd7 { Everything else allows us to smoothly finish the development. } 13.
Bxd7+ Nxd7 { Black wants to damage our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. } 14. Ne2
{ Defending the c3-Knight. We're ready to castle kingside. } 14... Nxc3
{ 14. ...Qa5  Black wants to 'improve' the position of the Queen and win the c5-pawn by ...Qxc5.  15.O-O  Unpinning the Knight and threatening Nxd5.  15. ...Qxc5  16.Qd3  Again attacking the d5-pawn.  16. ...Bxc3  17.Nxc3  Nxg3  18.fxg3!  I could have stopped the variation a little bit earlier, but I wanted to show this beautiful and paradoxical move. By all rights, we had to take with the h-pawn, but we worsen tour pawn structure to open up the f-file, where our Rook dominates. In addition, it's impossible for Black to defend against Nb5 and Nxd5 at the same time. }
15. Nxc3
{ Taking with the b2-pawn   15.bxc3  leads to a difficult endgame after  15. . ..Qxc2  16.Rxc2  Bxc5 }
15... Qc4
{ The only possibility for Black to keep more or less equal chances is to prevent us from castling kingside. }
16. h4
{ Since we have not been able to castle kingside, we should take advantage of the h1-Rook and start playing on the h-file. }
16... Nxc5 { Black wins a pawn and threatens ...Nd3 on the next move. } 17. Rd1
{ Taking control of the d3-square and threatening to win the g5-pawn. } 17...
Rg8 { Black doesn't lose the g5-pawn but allows the h-file to be opened. } 18.
hxg5
{ Since we have not had the right to castle kingside, it's highly important to involve the h1-Rook into the game. }
18... hxg5 19. Rd4
{ Activating the Rook and kicking the black Queen out of the center. } 19...
Qa6 20. f3
{ It's too dangerous to win the d5-pawn with   20.Rxd5  as it allows Black to exchange our important defender.  20. ...Rd8!  21.Rxd8  Kxd8  The d3-square has not been controlled anymore and Black has a strong initiative. Therefore, we should make our King a little bit safer. }
20... Bxc3+
{ After the white King moves to f2, the c3-Knight becomes really strong, so Black should exchange it in advance. }
21. Qxc3 { Attacking the c5-Knight. } 21... Rc8
{ Black threatens ...Nd3, followed by ...Rc1. } 22. Rd1
{ We defend the back rank and threaten to win the pinned c5-Knight. } 22... Ke7
{ The black Rooks become connected, so the c5-Knight isn't pinned anymore. }
23. Rh7
{ Although the position is objectively about equal, I believe, that it's only White who plays for a win thanks to the activity of the pieces. }
*

