15... Be6 { This move is inaccurate, although deserves attention. } 16. a3
{ Forcing Black to make an unpleasant decision. } 16... Bxc5
{ Obviously, Black doesn't want to agree to trade the dark-squared Bishop for the c3-Knight with   16. ...Bxc3  and be down a pawn without visible compensation. }
17. b4 { Creating a fork. } 17... Qxa3 18. bxc5
{ We are a piece up, but the position is sharp, so have to be extremely careful. }
18... O-O-O
{ Making the King safe and threatening a fork with ... Nb3   18. ...Nb3  Fortunately, this move doesn't work out immediately because of  19.Bb5!  Kf8  20.Qd6  Getting the first piece out of the attack.  20. ...Kg7  21.Rd1  All our pieces are safe now and Black doesn't have enough compensation. }
19. Nb1
{ The only move which gives us an advantage! We want to drive away the black Queen, which restricts freedom of our pieces.   19.Rb1  looks tempting but leads to a forced and unexpected draw after  19. ...Nb3  20.Qc2  And  20. ...Na1!  We are forced to repeat the moves. }
19... Qa4 20. Qb2
{ Avoiding the b3-fork and aiming to develop the g1-Knight to e2, finally finishing the development. }
