{ We intend to develop the f1-Bishop to d3, driving away the e4-Knight. } 10...
Qa5 { Attacking the c3-Knight the third time. } 11. Rc1
{ Is slightly less popular than   11.Nge2  , but no less strong. } 11... Nc6
{ This is another approach. Instead of collecting the pawns, Black decides to develop the pieces. }
12. Bd3
{ We want to kick the e4-Knight out of the center. It's very irritating. }
12... Bxc3+
{ This is the most unambitious move in the position. Black voluntarily gives up a dark-squared Bishop. }
13. bxc3 { We're still attacking the e4-Knight. } 13... Nxc5
{ Winning back a pawn.   13. ...Nxg3  looks tempting but opens up the h-file.  14.hxg3  The h1-Rook becomes active.  14. ...Be6  15.Nf3  Threatening Ng5.  15. ...O-O-O  16.O-O  Intending to block the d5-pawn with Nd4 and take control of the b-file with Rb1. }
14. Nf3
{ I would recommend playing h4 to weaken the black pawn structure, followed by castling short. We want to play against the d5-pawn and the weak black King. We are much better because Black will hardly solve the King problem and the isolated d5-pawn is a reason of long-term suffering for Black. }
