{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep the tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... exd5
{ There are two main continuations: ...exd5 and ...Qxd5, the so-called Romanishin system. After the text move, Black should be ready to play with an isolated d5-pawn in many lines. However, the c8-Bishop becomes active. }
6. Bg5 { We pin the f6-Knight, making Black uncomfortable. } 6... h6
{ This is undoubtedly a useful move, creating an escape square, even if Black doesn't play ...g5 afterwards.   6. ...c5  7.dxc5  h6  8.Bh4  transposes to the line below   6. ...O-O  7.e3  h6  8.Bh4  c6  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
7. Bh4
{ It doesn't make any sense to take on f6   7.Bxf6  due to  7. ...Qxf6  and we cannot capture the d5-pawn because our c3-Knight is being pinned. So we should just maintain a pin. }
7... c5
{ Black plays quite logically. They use the weakness of the d4-pawn to take initiative.   7. ...c6  8.e3  Nbd7  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Nge2  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
8. dxc5
{ The most principled continuation. We're winning a pawn, forcing Black to show their compensation, if there is, of course. }
8... O-O
{ Castling short is a much less popular continuation as it doesn't really fit the spirit of this sharp and ambitious line. However, it is objectively not bad and Black has a chance to reach equality. }
9. e3
{ As in the main line, we want to develop the f1-Bishop either to d3 or e2. }
9... Be6
{ There are not so many squares available for the black light-squared Bishop, so Black is forced to develop it to a passive position. Nonetheless, it defends the d5-pawn and does its work. }
10. Nf3 { First Knights, and only then Bishops. } 10... Nbd7
{ Black doesn't develop the Knight to c6, as it will block the c-file, which can be potentially a powerful weapon in the hands of Black. }
11. Be2
{ There is nothing wrong with Bd3, but again I'm not very fond of blocking files, which can be useful for us. }
11... Rc8
{ Black takes control of the almost open c-file. It's just a matter of time before the c-pawn falls. }
12. c6
{ A brilliant strategical decision. We want Black to close the c-file with their own hands. }
12... bxc6
{ Black has so-called 'hanging pawns' on c6 and d5 instead of an isolated pawn.   12. ...Rxc6  looks tempting but Black loses a tempo after  13.Nd4  Rc8  If we played Nd4 instead of c6, we would end up in the same position, but with the black Knight on c5.  14.O-O  Re8  15.Rad1  The positions with an isolated pawn are always extremely interesting and unbalanced. I believe, that we have managed to place our pieces more or less correctly: A Knight blocks an isolated pawn, a Rook puts pressure on it, a Bishop pins the f6-Knight. However, there is always room for improvement: for example, we want to get rid of the pin along the c-file with Qb1 as well as push the f-pawn to f4 at some point. }
13. O-O { We have finished the pieces development. } 13... Nc5
{ This was played by another grandmaster. The b4-Bishop and the c5-Knight feel a little bit awkward, in my opinion. }
14. Rac1 { Placing the Rook on the semi-open c-file. } 14... Qe7
{ Connecting the Rooks and overprotecting the c5-Knight.   14. ...Bxc3  If Black doesn't handle the pressure, then  15.bxc3  we have a Bishop pair advantage and we intend to push the c-pawn forward to c4. }
15. Nd2
{ Taking control of the e4-square and aiming to disturb the b4-Bishop with a3. }
15... g5
{ The idea of this move is to get rid of a pin and to place a Knight on e4 after all. }
16. Bg3 Bxc3 { Black wants to transfer a Knight to e4 as fast as possible. }
17. bxc3
{ It's also possible to take back with a Queen but I prefer to play this way as we can push the c-pawn forward to c4 and attack the center. }
*

