{ Black plays quite logically. They use the weakness of the d4-pawn to take initiative.   7. ...c6  8.e3  Nbd7  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Nge2  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
8. dxc5
{ The most principled continuation. We're winning a pawn, forcing Black to show their compensation, if there is, of course. }
8... Be6
{ I don't see the point of deviating from the original idea of playing ...g5, followed by ...Ne4. }
9. e3 { Intending to develop a Bishop somewhere along the f1-b5 diagonal. }
9... Nbd7
{ Black doesn't want to waste time castling kingside.   9. ...O-O  transposes to  8. ... O-O }
10. Bb5
{ This move is even better than usual   11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  as we create the inconvenience for Black in connection with a pin. }
10... Qa5 { For example, Black attacks the b5-Bishop immediately. } 11. Bxf6
{ We want to damage the black pawn structure. } 11... Qxb5
{ 11. ...gxf6  is a positional disaster. } 12. Bxg7 { Winning one more pawn. }
12... Rg8 13. Bd4 { It's important to keep a Bishop along the big diagonal. }
13... Rxg2 14. Ne2
{ The g2-Rook seems quite annoying but we're going to castle queenside anyway. }
14... Nxc5 { Threatening ...Nd3. } 15. O-O-O
{ Unpinning the c3-Knight and attacking the b5-Queen. White is better because of an isolated pawn on d5, a bad King, and a passive Bishop. }
*

