11... Be7 { Black blocks a pin but doesn't attack the e3-pawn anymore. } 12. f3
{ With the idea to play e4. } 12... b5
{ Looks like Black breaks nearly a hundred opening principles, but they win space on the queenside and create an enjoyable trap.   12. ...c5?!  is definitely premature.  13.Rad1  X-raying the d5-pawn.  13. ...cxd4  14.Nxd4  We are happy to play against an isolated pawn on d5. }
13. Bf2
{ First of all, we should get the Bishop out of the undefended h4-square. If we inaccurately proceed with our plan   13.e4?  b4  14.Na4  dxe4  15.fxe4  Nxe4!  A typical combination for the Queen's Gambit. After  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  The e4-Knight is enough protected. }
13... Bb7 { Black wants to defend the b5-pawn with ...a6, followed by ...c5. }
14. Ng3
{ The board is full of pieces and the pawn structure is not symmetrical, which makes the position extremely interesting. We want to finally play e4, and Black would rather play on the queenside. }
