8... Re8 { Black x-rays our King immediately. } 9. Bd3
{ Again we should develop our Bishop first because most likely we will develop the g1-Knight to e2. }
9... c5
{ All moves on the eighth move, except ...c6, make sense only if Black plays ...c5 later on. Black threatens ...cxd4. }
10. Ne2
{ The Knight on e2 is extremely useful - we're defending the c3-Knight, the d4-pawn and blocking the e-file. }
10... Nc6
{ For example, Black maintains tension in the center and threatens ... cxd4. }
11. O-O { Finally getting the King out of the center. } 11... cxd4
{ 11. ...c4?  is a blunder  12.Bh7  again a little bit hidden but enjoyable move.  12. ...Kh8  13.Bxf6  Since the d5-pawn is hanging, Black is forced into taking back with the pawn.  13. ...gxf6  14.Bf5  We totally dominate the position due to black's poor pawn structure. }
12. Nxd4
{ It's better to take on d4 with a Knight as we open the e-file, which we might use later. }
12... Nxd4 13. exd4
{ We still want to take on f6 and damage the black pawn structure. } 13... Be6
{ Defending the d5-pawn, making it possible to take back on f6 with a Queen. }
14. h3
{ It's a good idea to create an escape square for a King. We're going to take control of the e-file with Rfe1 on the next move. }
