4... d5
{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep the tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... exd5
{ There are two main continuations: ...exd5 and ...Qxd5, the so-called Romanishin system. After the text move, Black should be ready to play with an isolated d5-pawn in many lines. However, the c8-Bishop becomes active. }
6. Bg5 { We pin the f6-Knight, making Black uncomfortable. } 6... h6
{ This is undoubtedly a useful move, creating an escape square, even if Black doesn't play ...g5 afterwards.   6. ...c5  7.dxc5  h6  8.Bh4  transposes to the line below   6. ...O-O  7.e3  h6  8.Bh4  c6  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
7. Bh4
{ It doesn't make any sense to take on f6   7.Bxf6  due to  7. ...Qxf6  and we cannot capture the d5-pawn because our c3-Knight is being pinned. So we should just maintain a pin. }
7... O-O
{ Black chooses a more positional path, which leads to a type of a position that is very similar to the Queen's Gambit Declined. }
8. e3
{ 8.Bxf6  It doesn't make any sense so far to take on f6, because after  8. ...Qxf6  We can't take on d5 as our Knight is still pinned. }
8... Be6 { Black wants to develop a Bishop first, and only then a Knight. } 9.
a3 { Forcing Black to make a decision where to move the b4-Bishop. } 9... Be7
{ Keeping the dark-squared Bishop on the board seems to be more logical.   9. ...Bxc3  is too unenthusiastic, in my opinion.  10.Qxc3  Bf5  A clear achievement is that Black can develop a Bishop to f5.  11.Nf3  Nbd7  12.Be2  I'm not fond of Bd3 as we exchange the light-squared Bishops in this case, which is bad for us because we have pawns mainly on the dark squares.  12. ...c6  13.Nd2  After castling short we're going to perform the so-called 'minority attack' with b4 and b5. }
10. Nge2
{ 10.Bd3  Our standard continuation is too risky here because of  10. ...c5  11.dxc5  d4!  This position is completely unclear. }
10... c6 11. Nf4
{ Although it takes two moves to develop a Knight, it's all worth it - a Knight on f4 is perfect. }
11... Bc8
{ Black threatens a fork ...g5.   11. . ..Bd7  would block the d7-square, which was planned to be occupied by a Knight. }
12. Bg3
{ A Bishop on g3 looks a bit awkward, but it's the only reasonable way to avoid a fork. }
12... Nbd7 13. Bd3 { A strange position. Usually, a Knight is placed on f3. }
13... Re8 14. O-O Nf8 15. b4
{ We want to execute a typical plan, the so-called 'minority attack', for the Queen's Gambit. The point is to push the b-pawn forward to b5 and take on c6 and thus creating a structural weakness. We should also not forget about a good old plan, f3 and e4. }
