{ This is undoubtedly a useful move, creating an escape square, even if Black doesn't play ...g5 afterwards.   6. ...c5  7.dxc5  h6  8.Bh4  transposes to the line below   6. ...O-O  7.e3  h6  8.Bh4  c6  transposes to  8. ... c6 }
7. Bh4
{ It doesn't make any sense to take on f6   7.Bxf6  due to  7. ...Qxf6  and we cannot capture the d5-pawn because our c3-Knight is being pinned. So we should just maintain a pin. }
7... g5 { Black chooses to play the original idea of this line. } 8. Bg3
{ The only possible continuation. } 8... Ne4
{ Since Black has weakened the kingside with ... g5, Black should play actively as much as possible. Black centralizes a Knight and puts more pressure on the c3-Knight at the same time.   8. ...Nc6  9.e3  h5  10.Bb5  transposes here     8. ...c5  9.dxc5  Ne4  10.e3  transposes to the main line }
9. e3 { Light-squared Bishop development is our priority number one. } 9... h5
{ Black threatens to trap our g3-Bishop with ...h4.   9. ...c5  10.dxc5  transposes to the main line }
10. f3
{ Driving away the centralized e4-Knight and creating an escape square on f2 for the g3-Bishop. }
10... Nxg3
{ On one hand, Black exchanges a Knight for a Bishop, which is, by all means, an achievement for them in this open position. On the other hand, the black Knight has already made several moves and reached an active square in the center. However, Black doesn't have a wide choice.  10...Bxc3  I'm quite surprised that this move was played by two brilliant grandmasters Daniil Dubov and Vasily Smyslov. To be honest, it's the only reason why I even consider this continuation. Its idea is to force White to take back on c3 with a pawn, which is not bad for us, in fact. The main drawback is that Black trades their strong dark-squared Bishop without being forced.  11.bxc3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  Opening the h-file.  12. ...Qd6  Attacking the g3-pawn.  13.g4!  The h5-pawn is pinned.  13. ...h4  14.Nh3  Developing a Knight and attacking a pawn on g5.  14. ...Rg8  15.c4  The black King is stuck in the center, which makes a black position very difficult. We're going to take on d5, followed by Bc4. Activating a Rook with Rb1 also looks like a good idea. }
11. hxg3
{ On one hand, our pawns become doubled, but on the other hand, we have managed to activate the h1-Rook without even moving it. }
11... Qd6
{ For example, instead of attacking the e3-pawn with ...Qe7, Black attacks the g3-pawn. Such forcing moves should be always taken into account. }
12. Kf2
{ I find this move a little bit paradoxical, as we 'break' an opening rule, and amazing at the same time. On the board full of pieces the King feels safe on f2, creating an astounding connection with the pawns on g2, g3, f3, e3. The King protects them and they, in turn, protect it. In addition, we're threatening Nb5 now. }
12... Nc6 { Blocking the c-file. } 13. Nb5
{ Anyway, it's a good idea to activate a Knight with tempo. After immediate   13.a3  Black can capture our Knight with  13. ...Bxc3  14.bxc3  This position is normal, but we can win a tempo. }
13... Qe7 { Black has to keep the c7-pawn protected. } 14. a3
{ There is no Knight on c3 right now, so we force the black Bishop to retreat. }
14... Ba5 15. Nc3
{ This maneuver looks a bit weird but this way we're going to win a tempo. }
15... Qd6 { After  15. ...Be6  16.Bb5  is very unpleasant. } 16. Nh3
{ Developing a Knight with tempo. } 16... Bxc3
{ It's hard for Black to tolerate the c3-Knight as it puts pressure on the d5-pawn and has an option to jump on b5. }
17. bxc3
{ We're going to break through the center with c4. Black still suffers due to the awfully located King. }
