g5 { Otherwise, what's the point of the whole variation? } 9. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black centralized their Knight and puts pressure on the pinned c3-Knight. }
10. Bd3 { Developing a Bishop with tempo. } 10... Bf5 11. Ne2
{ It's also possible to develop a Knight to f3, but I prefer this move because we protect the c3-Knight as well. }
11... h5
{ This move was played by two grandmasters but objectively it's bad. Black wants to push the h-pawn forward.   11. ...Nxg3  is objectively the best continuation.  12.hxg3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Qd7  14.a3  Forcing Black to make a decision about the b4-Bishop.  14. ...Bxc3  15.Nxc3  O-O-O  16.Na4  Transferring the Knight to c5. White has good prospects on the queenside. }
12. O-O { Making the King safer and unpinning the c3-Knight. } 12... Nxg3
{ 12. ...h4?  loses due to a beautiful combination  13.Bxc7!  Qxc7  14.Nxd5  Destroying a defender of the e4-Knight.  14. ...Qd6  15.Bxe4  White is absolutely winning. }
13. fxg3
{ A novelty. It looks not very obvious as we weaken our pawn structure a lot, but at the same time, we open up the f-file and include the f1-Rook into the game. }
13... Bxd3 14. Qxd3
{ We're going to invade the f5-square with either the Queen or the f1-Rook, attacking all the black pawns. }
