{ There are two main continuations: ...exd5 and ...Qxd5, the so-called Romanishin system. After the text move, Black should be ready to play with an isolated d5-pawn in many lines. However, the c8-Bishop becomes active. }
6. Bg5 { We pin the f6-Knight, making Black uncomfortable. } 6... c6
{ This move is not very popular among Nimzo-Indian players as we get a position, which is similar to the Queen's Gambit Declined. }
7. e3
{ Again we should develop a Bishop first because we don't know yet where to develop a Knight - to e2 or f3. }
7... Nbd7 { Defending the f6-Knight and untying the Queen. } 8. Bd3 Qa5
{ I tend to find this move the most challenging. Black creates tension on the queenside immediately. }
9. Ne2
{ This is why we developed a Bishop first. A Knight on e2 comes in handy! }
9... O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. a3
{ We want to create a minority attack, so we should clear a path for our pawns. }
11... Bd6 12. b4 { Launching a pawn storm on the queenside with tempo. } 12...
Qc7 13. Bf4
{ Since most of the black pawns are placed on the light squares, we should exchange the dark-squared Bishops. We're going to continue our minority attack with b5 afterward. White has a very good version of the Queen's Gambit. }
