{ 10.Nxa4?  is a blunder because of  10. ...Bxd2  11.Nxd2  Nxd4!  Black wins back a pawn and threatens ...Nc2. }
10... Bd6
{ It's also quite logical to keep the dark-squared Bishop on the board. } 11.
h3
{ The old good idea - we want to disturb the black Queen with g4 with an eye to trap it one day. }
11... e5
{ The most challenging continuation - Black starts a fight in the center. } 12.
e4 { Cleverly sacrificing a pawn. } 12... Qh5
{ Threatening ...exd4.   12. ...Nxe4  is possible, there is no line which refutes this move immediately  13.Bd3  Pinning the Knight  13. ...Nxc3  14.Bxc3  Aiming not only to win the Queen but also a pawn on e5.  14. ...e4  Do we really lose a piece?  15.Qe2!  No! Never miss a chance to learn a topic 'a pin'.  15. ...O-O  16.Bxe4  Winning back a pawn and intending to castle long if Black let us, of course. The isolated d4-pawn is rather good as we're ready to push it to d5, activating our c3-Bishop significantly. }
13. d5 { There is no need to give Black more space with dxe5. } 13... Nd4
{ Centralizing a Knight.   13. ...Ne7  is worse than it looks like.  14.Qc2  We're going to castle long and chase the black Queen with Be2 and g4. }
14. Be2
{ 14.Nxd4  exd4  would significantly improve the black e5-pawn and leave the e4-pawn unprotected. }
14... Nxe2 15. Qxe2
{ A Bishop is considered as a better piece than a Knight, but the d4-Knight is obviously much more active than our e2-Bishop. Moreover, this position is relatively closed, so our Knights can be even more helpful than the black Bishops. }
15... O-O 16. O-O-O
{ Threatening g4, followed by trapping the black Queen with Nh4. } 16... Nd7
{ Liberating the f6-square for the Queen and threatening ...f5. } 17. g4
{ Chasing the black Queen and preventing ...f5 at the same time. } 17... Qg6
18. Nh4
{ We can't trap the black Queen now, but the point of this move is to transfer a Knight to a better square. }
18... Qf6 19. Nf5
{ We're going to continue the attack on the kingside with h4. } *

