[White "11) Black plays 4...d5: 5...Qxd5 - Romanishin Variation"]
[Black "Black plays 4.. d5: 5.. Qxd5 (Romanishin Variation) #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... d5
{ Black strikes immediately in the center, preventing e4 and attacking the c4-pawn. We have to decide now what we should do with the hanging c4-pawn. }
5. cxd5
{ It's also possible to keep tension in the center by defending the c4-pawn with e3, for example, but I tend to choose the most theoretically challenging move. }
5... Qxd5
{ This move, though counterintuitive, became popular when Romanishin, great Ukrainian grandmaster, found and developed an interesting idea of transposing into an endgame, which we will see a bit later. He significantly influenced the chess theory in the Kasparov vs Karpov era. }
6. Nf3
{ Another way to defend the d4-pawn is   6.e3  which leads to a position with symmetrical pawn structure, and White having the Bishop pair. However, in my opinion, it is too dry. We have chosen Qc2 on the fourth move to play combative chess after all! }
6... Qf5
{ This is a fascinating idea of Romanishin! I suppose I must not praise Black's moves so hard, but I can't help admiring a genius of Romanishin, who found and analyzed this move in the times when a computer could barely beat a master. It's the second counterintuitive move in a row. First, Black moves the Queen to the d5-square, which is 'controlled' by a Knight. Then Black voluntarily suggests the exchange of the Queens, doubling the pawns on the f-file. }
7. Qb3
{ Undoubtedly, we should first discuss   7.Qxf5  exf5  It looks tempting to double the black pawns, but if we would have a closer look at this position, we'll see, that Black takes control of the e4-square and liberates the e6-square for a Bishop. Unfortunately, this is enough for Black to equalize. The idea of the text move is just to avoid a position, where Black has firm control of the center and maintains tension, by keeping the Queens on the board. }
7... c5
{ I find this move even more logical than the main one, because Black doesn't want to block the c7-pawn with a Knight and fights for the center immediately. However, there is an antidote to this variation. }
8. a3
{ We should drive the b4-Bishop away as it creates a pin and defends the c5-pawn. }
8... Ba5
{ This move is the most popular as Black maintains a pin and tension.   8. ...Bxc3  9.Qxc3  transposes to the line below }
9. Qc4 { We're attacking the c5-pawn and x-raying the c8-Bishop. } 9... Bxc3+
{ At least Black tested us whether we could find Qc4 or not. } 10. Qxc3
{ The c5-pawn is still hanging. } 10... Nbd7
{ An ideal square for the black Knight is c6, but the c5-pawn must be defended. Unfortunately, not all dreams come true. }
11. g4 { We try to distract the Queen from the defense of the c5-pawn. } 11...
Nxg4
{ I think, it makes more sense to grab a pawn with a Knight as the black Queen still defends the c5-pawn. }
12. Rg1
{ Attacking the g4-Knight, so that the black Queen becomes tied to the defense of it. }
12... O-O
{ It seems to me quite unnatural to voluntarily place the King on the one file with a white Rook, but the King in the center is even worse.   12. ...cxd4?!  It looks logical to avoid dxc5 and simplify the position in the center.  13.Qxd4  Attacking the g4-Knight  13. ...Nge5  14.Nh4  Driving the black Queen away from the kingside  14. ...Qc2  15.Bf4  It turns out that almost everything in the black camp is hanging: the e5-Knight and the g7-pawn. }
13. h3 { We want to open the g-file completely. } 13... Ngf6 14. Bh6
{ Exploiting the pin on the g-file. } 14... Ne8
{ Well, Black is by all means not happy about this decision, as a black Knight and a Rook become passive, but there is no choice. }
15. dxc5 { Liberating the c3-g7 diagonal to attack the g7-pawn one more time. }
15... f6 { Black intends to win back the c5-pawn. } 16. Be3
{ Defending the c5-pawn and removing the Bishop from h6, where it had been constantly attacked. }
