6... c5
{ This move doesn't fit the spirit of the variation and has been not very popular last years. Anyway, the point of this move is to start fighting for the center immediately. }
7. Bd2 { Unpinning the c3-Knight and threatening to capture the Queen. } 7...
Bxc3
{ 7. ...Qf5  would be a blunder now because of  8.e4!  This move has become possible as our c3-Knight isn't pinned anymore. }
8. Bxc3 { We get a Bishop pair advantage. } 8... Nc6
{ The most natural move in this position. Black develops a Knight and attacks the d4-pawn at the same time.   8. ...O-O  9.dxc5  Qxc5  10.Rc1  Nc6  11.e3  transposes to the line below }
9. dxc5 { Opening up the c3-g7 diagonal. } 9... Qxc5
{ Black wants to exploit the pin on c-file with ...Nd5 and deprive us of a Bishop pair. }
10. Rc1 { Defending the c2-Queen and thereby unpinning the c3-Bishop. } 10...
O-O
{ 10. ...Bd7  Black wants to put more pressure on the c-file with ...Rac8 as fast as possible.  11.e3  Rc8  12.Qb1  Avoiding ...Nb4 and threatening Bxf6.  12. ...Qe7  13.Bd3  White is enjoying a Bishop pair. }
11. e3 { We should not forget about development. } 11... Nd5
{ Black wants to deprive us of the main advantage - a Bishop pair. } 12. Bd3
{ Attacking the h7-pawn. } 12... Nxc3
{ A natural   12. ...h6??  loses immediately after  13.Bh7  Kh8  14.Bxg7  A discovered attack! }
13. Bxh7+
{ The c3-Knight is not going to run anywhere, so we can first win a pawn. }
13... Kh8 14. Bd3
{ Black was going to trap our Bishop with ...g6, so we have to rescue it as fast as possible. }
14... Nb4
{ Black has to play actively, otherwise, they end up being a pawn down without any compensation. }
15. Qd2 { Intending to win back a piece with Rxc3. } 15... b6
{ Intending to pin the d3-Bishop with ... Rd8 and attack it with ... Ba6.   15. ...Rd8?!  was played once.  16.Rxc3  Winning back a piece and defending the d3-Bishop at the same time.  16. ...Qd5  17.Bb1  Fortunately, there isn't any good discovered attack for Black  17. ...Qa5  X-raying our c3-Rook.  18.Qe2  Nxa2  19.Qc2!  Threatening mate in one.  19. ...f5  20.Bxa2  Qxa2  21.O-O  +-  The black King is completely exposed and we're going to play Rc7 and Ng5. }
16. O-O
{ We're getting the King from the center, where the main battle is played out, to safety. }
16... Qa5
{ Unpinning the c3-Knight and intending to retreat it on the next move. } 17.
bxc3
{ 17.Rxc3?  is a blunder, although it looks more natural, as we don't ruin our pawn structure.  17. ...Nxd3  18.Qxd3  Ba6!  We're losing an exchange. }
17... Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Ba6
{ 18. ...Qxa2  Winning a pawn is overoptimistic as White can develop a quick attack with  19.Ng5!  g6  20.Qd4!  Black's position is falling apart. }
19. c4
{ The a2-pawn is invulnerable, as the a5-Queen is tied to the defense of the kingside. Black doesn't have enough compensation for a pawn. }
