11. e3 { We should not forget about development. } 11... Bd7
{ This move was played once by an English grandmaster Michael Adams, but I don't see any reasonable idea behind it. }
12. Qb1 { X-raying the c5-Queen and threatening Bxf6. } 12... Qe7 13. Bc4
{ It looks a little bit weird to develop a Bishop to a more or less closed diagonal, but the idea to prepare ourselves for ...Nd5. }
13... Nd5 14. Bxd5
{ It's not very natural to voluntarily give up a Bishop pair, but we get instead a weak isolated pawn. }
14... exd5 15. Rd1 { Activating a Rook with tempo. } 15... Be6 16. O-O
{ The c3-Bishop is much better than the e6-one. In addition, we're going to play against the weak isolated d5-pawn by doubling the Rooks on the d-file and making our position safer by creating an escape square. }
