5... Nxd5
{ I think it's a dubious move because Black voluntarily gives up control of the center. }
6. e4
{ Of course, we should place the pawns on d4 and e4, once we have such an opportunity. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ We transpose to the following line:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  Be7?!  but we're a tempo up. }
7... Be7
{ 7. ...Ba5  An attempt to maintain a pin on the a5-e1 diagonal.  8.Nf3  c5  Threatening ...cxd4, exploiting the pin.  9.dxc5  This is the only reasonable way to avoid ...cxd4. Moreover, we're just winning a pawn.  9. ...Qc7  Attacking the c5-pawn.  10.Nd4  There are two types of defense: a direct one and an indirect one. By playing Nd4 we don't straightforwardly defend a pawn on c5, but prepare a trap.  10. ...O-O   10. ...Qxc5?!  is a mistake due to  11.Nb5!  Black can't prevent Ba3.  11.Nb3  Just in two moves our Knight has jumped from the kingside to the queenside and is defending the c5-pawn as well as attacking the a5-Bishop. }
8. Nf3 { First, we develop Knights, and only then - Bishops. } 8... c5 9. Be2
{ We develop a light-squared Bishop first to castle a King as fast as possible. }
9... O-O 10. O-O cxd4
{ 10. ...b6?!  What if Black decides to develop a light-squared Bishop immediately?  11.d5!  We're going to support our central pawn with c4 on the next move.  11. ...exd5  12.exd5  Qxd5  The most challenging continuation, which must be considered.  13.Bd3!  Attacking the h7-pawn and threatening Bxh7.  13. ...Bb7  Defending against Be4.  14.Bxh7  First winning back a pawn.  14. ...Kh8  15.Re1!  And again a double attack! We're attacking the e7-Bishop as well as Be4.  15. ...Qh5  Attacking our h7-Bishop.  16.Be4!  The black position is falling apart. }
11. cxd4 b6 { Intending to develop a Bishop to b7. } 12. Bf4
{ We're developing a Bishop to the most active square.   12.d5?!  It doesn't make sense to advance the d5-pawn now because we can't support it with c4 after  12. ...exd5  13.exd5  Bb7 }
12... Bb7 13. Rad1
{ We have complete control over the center and we aim to play d5 at some point. }
