{ This is a critical continuation. We are not shy to capture a space advantage in the center and Black has to prove their compensation. }
6... exd5
{ This move can transpose to the main line if Black decides to play ...Qe7 on the next move. }
7. exd5
{ 7.cxd5  leads to a pawn loss after  7. ...Qe7!  Black is attacking the e4- and d5-pawns. Although we can still get here a decent compensation, obviously, there is no need to choose this path. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ In the main line we had difficulty developing a light-squared Bishop. Now we can do it without problems. }
8... b5 { Playing in the style of Benko gambit. } 9. cxb5
{ Black will not get enough compensation, so we should choose the most challenging continuation. }
9... a6 { Black aims to open up the queenside and the a8-Rook, in particular. }
10. Ne2
{ Anyway, we should develop a Knight to e2 in order to close the e-file and avoid ...Re8 with a check. }
10... axb5 { Opening up the a-file. } 11. Bxb5 Nxd5
{ Black wins back a pawn but loses the most valuable resource in an open position, which is time. }
12. O-O { We are several tempos ahead. } 12... Bxc3
{ 12. ...Nxc3  13.bxc3  Taking on c3 with the Knight doesn't change much.  13. ...Ba3  14.Rd1  The d1-Rook is shooting along the d-file, putting pressure on the black d7-pawn. }
13. bxc3
{ We have an outside passed pawn on the a-file, which we want to push to a4. In addition, we're going to occupy the d-file with Rd1. }
