1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... b6
{ This is an interesting move, which avoids the main lines and makes the position more dynamic and complicated. }
5. e4
{ Once we have a possibility to take control over the center, we should do it immediately. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the second most popular move. Black is attacking the e4-pawn. } 6.
Bd3 { We develop a Bishop and protect the e4-pawn at the same time. } 6...
Bxc3+
{ Black takes the opportunity to damage the pawn structure as the white Queen is tied to the defense of the e4-pawn.   6. ...d6?  This natural move is just a blunder  7.Qa4!  A double attack!  7. ...Nc6  8.d5  Black loses a piece. }
7. bxc3
{ The doubled pawns on the c-file are not great but we have a Bishop pair and a strong pawn center. }
7... d6 8. f4
{ It would be too toothless to simply develop a Knight. We should launch a pawn storm and put a Knight behind a pawn. }
8... e5
{ Black has to fight for the center, but it might be too late.   8. ...Nbd7  9.Nf3  Qe7  10.O-O  e5  transposes to the variation below    8. ...c5  doesn't make much sense, as it doesn't stop e5.  9.Nf3  Nc6  10.d5!  The first step of taking full control of the center.  10. ...Na5  11.e5!  White totally dominates the position. }
9. Nf3
{ Attacking the e5-pawn.   9.fxe5  Winning a pawn on e5 leads to a catastrophic pawn structure.  9. ...dxe5  10.dxe5  Nfd7  Looks ugly, doesn't it? }
9... Nbd7
{ Black wants to keep the e5-pawn in the center.   9. ...Nfd7  Another way to protect the e5-pawn. A bit weird, though. Black wants to avoid a pin on the g5-d8 diagonal.  10.O-O  O-O  11.Qf2  A smart way to transfer the Queen to the kingside, where it will support our attack.  11. ...f5  Black creates a counterplay, but at the cost of weakening the d5-g8 diagonal and the e6-square in particular.  12.Ng5  Threatening Ne6 and defending the e4-pawn.  12. ..fxe4  13.Nxe4  Nf6  14.Ng5!  We move our Knight back to g5 to threaten a fork again.  14. ...e4  Black gains a space advantage in the center.  15.Be2  Qe7  16.f5!  We shouldn't deviate from our main plan - transferring the Knight to g5.  16. ...Bc8  17.d5!  The black resources to stop Ne6 have run out. }
10. O-O
{ The f1-Rook becomes involved into the game immediately with a pawn on f4 . }
10... Qe7
{ Protecting the e5-pawn and intending to castle kingside.   10. ...O-O  It's too reckless to castle kingside as our pieces have been already eyeing the kingside.  11.fxe5  Opening up the c1-h6 diagonal for the c1-Bishop.  11. ...dxe5  12.Bg5  Pinning the f6-Knight.  12. ...Re8  13.Rae1  Improving a Rook and defending the e4-pawn. We are much better thanks to a Bishop pair, a pin, and a strong pawn center. In addition, we're going to transfer the f3-Knight to f5, which can become the last nail in Black's position. }
11. fxe5 { We should open a way for our c1-Bishop. } 11... dxe5 12. Bg5
{ Pinning the f6-Knight. } 12... O-O-O
{ It would be too risky for Black to castle kingside.   12. ...h6  An attempt to drive away our g5-Bishop only helps White.  13.Bxf6!  It turns out that Black cannot take our Bishop with a piece because they lose a pawn on e5.  13. ...gxf6  14.c5  First, we open up the center.  14. ...bxc5  15.Nh4  We're transferring the Knight to a great outpost - the f5-square. White is nearly winning. }
13. a4
{ However, there is already probably no good square for the black King. We're going to push the pawn forward. }
13... a5 { At the cost of weakening the queenside Black stops our plan. } 14.
c5
{ We should open files and diagonals as many as possible to execute a successful attack. }
14... bxc5 15. Rab1
{ Our attack is deadly: we're going to bring the Queen into the game with Qb2, leaving Black with insoluble problems. }
*

