{ Once we have a possibility to take control over the center, we should do it immediately. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the second most popular move. Black is attacking the e4-pawn. } 6.
Bd3 { We develop a Bishop and protect the e4-pawn at the same time. } 6... c5
{ This move usually gives us a solid advantage due to a space advantage after d5. }
7. d5 { The black b7-Bishop becomes shut out. } 7... d6
{ It's also possible to avoid taking on d5, but I don't see much point in this as Black loses the opportunity to play on the e-file. }
8. Ne2
{ Anyway, we should develop a Knight to e2 as there is still a chance that Black opens the e-file. }
8... Nbd7 9. a3
{ We force Black to make a decision about the b4-Bishop: either to capture the c-Knight or to retreat to a worse a5-square, where it can be trapped one day with b4. }
9... Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 { We have a Bishop pair now. } 10... Ne5 11. Be2
{ There is no need to give Black a chance to deprive us of a Bishop pair advantage. }
11... Ng6 12. h4
{ Since AlphaZero has been released, we have been seeing pawn marches on the a- and h-files way more often. }
12... exd5 13. cxd5
{ The e4-pawn isn't hanging, so there is no problem capturing with the c-pawn. }
13... h5 14. Bg5
{ The Bishop cannot be kicked out of the g5-square, so this pin tends to be dead. }
14... a6 15. a4
{ With this move we prevent ...b5. We're going to castle kingside and continue developing our space advantage with f4. }
