{ The d5-pawn secures a solid space advantage as well as restricts the b7-Bishop. }
8... Nd4
{ This is the whole point of ...Nc6. The black Knight infiltrates the center to create tension there.   8. ...Ne7  doesn't fit the spirit of the line.  9.a3  Forcing Black to trade a dark-squared Bishop.  9. ...Bxc3  10.Nxc3  d6  11.f3  Stabilizing the pawn structure.  11. ...O-O  12.Be3  We're going to castle queenside and launch a pawn storm on the kingside with g4, h4, and so on. }
9. Nxd4 { Choosing the most challenging continuation. } 9... exd4 10. a3
{ Fortunately, we can get rid of the source of the b4-e1 pin. } 10... Bxc3+ 11.
bxc3 { Black even fails to double our pawns. } 11... dxc3 12. e5
{ Playing actively and fearlessly. } 12... Qe7 13. Qe2
{ Blocking the e-file and forcing Black to make a highly unpleasant decision. }
13... Ng8 { The only available square for the Knight. } 14. O-O
{ Black is technically up a pawn, but, obviously, the c3-pawn is dead. We're going to play a4, followed by Ba3 at some point. }
