5... Bxc3+ { Black can also try and damage our pawn structure immediately. } 6.
bxc3 { We have to take with a pawn, otherwise, we lose the e4-pawn. } 6... d6
{ 6. ...Bb7  7.Bd3  d6  transposes to  5. ... Bb7 } 7. e5
{ As Black prefers to develop the pawns instead of the minor pieces, we should play actively. }
7... dxe5 8. dxe5 Nfd7 9. Qe4
{ The only move, which gives a big advantage. We're attacking the a8-Rook and defending the e5-pawn at the same time. }
9... Nc5 { Black provokes us into taking the a8-Rook. } 10. Qxa8
{ We're happy to be provoked! } 10... Bb7
{ The idea of this sacrifice is to trap our Queen somehow. } 11. Qxa7
{ The only move. } 11... Nba6
{ 11. ...Nc6  doesn't make sense because there is the a3-square, available for our Queen.  12.Qa3!  We have saved the Queen. }
12. Ba3 O-O 13. h4
{ A clever move, which prevents ...Qh4 and ...Qg5. It's a good idea to prevent the possible counterplay of the opponent. }
13... Qd7 { Threatening to trap our Queen with ...Ra8. } 14. Bxc5
{ The b7-Bishop is hanging now. } 14... Nxc5 15. Qa3
{ We have saved our Queen and Black doesn't have any compensation for a Rook. }
