{ This is the square where we usually should develop our light-squared Bishop. After   10.Bd3  Black can play  10. ...Bb7  which becomes even more unpleasant because Black wants to take a Knight and double our pawns on the f-file. }
10... Bb7 { The black Bishop is a beast along the big diagonal. } 11. b4
{ There are two helpful ideas behind this pawn advance. First, we liberate the b2-square for the c3-Bishop. Secondly, we launch a pawn storm and win space on the queenside. }
11... Ne4
{ Black centralizes a Knight and intends to exchange a Knight for a Bishop. }
12. Bb2
{ We should save our Bishop pair advantage, despite the fact, that the e4-Knight is quite active and the position isn't still open. The pawn structure isn't defined though, so we shall have a chance one day to open the position. }
12... f5
{ Black supports the e4-Knight and expects to use the f6-square as a 'springboard' to transfer some pieces to the kingside.   12. ...c5  13.O-O  f5  transposes here }
13. O-O
{ Castling kingside doesn't look like a completely safe move, but hiding the King on the queenside is even scarier, isn't it? }
13... Rf6
{ As has been said, Black uses the f6-square to transfer a Rook to the kingside: either g6 or, more likely, h6. }
14. d5 { We should turn on our main trump - a Bishop pair. } 14... Rh6
{ Black wants to close the center with ...e5 now and develop an attack on the kingside. As is well known, a recipe for a successful attack is a closed center with a defined and fixed pawn structure. }
15. dxe6
{ We want to open the center to prevent Black from a smooth attack.   15.Nd4?  is a mistake due to  15. ...Qh4! }
15... Qxe6
{ Black wants to fix our c-pawn with ...c5 and thereby imprison our light-squared Bishop. }
16. c5 { A great pawn sacrifice which liberates the c4-square for our Bishop. }
16... dxc5
{ Black deprives themselves of the opportunity to block the c4-g8 diagonal with ...d5. }
17. Rfd1 { Threatening to win the Queen with Bc4. } 17... Qe7 18. bxc5
{ Luring the d7-Knight to the queenside, where it will no longer control the e5-square. }
18... Ndxc5 19. Bc4+ { Fully turning on a power of our Bishop pair. } 19... Kf8
{ 19. ...Kh8  is even worse as after  20.Ne5!  Black can't really prevent Nf7. }
20. Be5
{ We're going to activate a Rook with Rac1 and prepare Ng5 with h4 and Bf4. } *

