1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The Nimzo-Indian Defence! This opening is named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who developed it and brought it to competitive chess in the early 20th century. Despite its long existence, the Nimzo-Indian has stood the test of time and is still used by the top GMs nowadays, e.g Magnus Carlsen, Garry Kasparov, Vladimir Kramnik, Fabiano Caruana and other legends.  The Nimzo-Indian is one of the best openings for Black against 1. d4 and it fully deserves to hold the title 'classical.' It is worth studying even if you don't play it regularly, as it will improve your general understanding of chess via learning new pawn structures and deep strategical plans.  I believe that White shouldn't deviate from the main route and should face the main lines fearlessly and well-prepared. Moreover, I'm confident that White can get the advantage in most of the variations. In the few lines where White can't get an advantage, Black has to show a decent level of knowledge. }
4. Qc2
{ As a chess coach, author, and player I always recommend playing the most ambitious and challenging lines. On the fourth move, I would highlight two variations, that stand out:   4.e3  - the Rubinstein system, and  4.Qc2  - so-called Classical or Capablanca variation. I tend to evaluate the Rubinstein system as a quieter way of combating the Nimzo-Indian, and the Classical variation as a sharper and more straightforward line. A lot of chess players are struggling to memorize all the opening moves. However, I believe, that many of us have to fundamentally change the approach to learning openings and chess in general. It's important to not just straightforwardly memorize the moves, but to grasp the concept, and get the main idea. For example, what's the point of 4. Qc2? To answer this question we have to understand what our opponent has planned and what he is going to play on the next move. Since the Knight on c3 has been pinned, it makes sense to either put more pressure on this Knight with ...Ne4 at some point or just capture the Knight with ...Bxc3, damaging the White pawn structure. Therefore, 4. Qc2 prevents both continuations and supports the e-pawn push to e4. }
4... d6 { Black transposes to Bogo-Indian type of the position. } 5. Bd2
{ We block the b4-e1 pin and want to take on c3 with a Bishop.   5.e4  It looks tempting to play the same move as in the first chapter but after  5. ...c5!  6.e5?  This move would work if there wasn't any pawn on d6.  6. ...cxd4  7.a3  Bxc3  8.bxc3  dxe5!  Black is two pawns up. }
5... O-O
{ 5. ...Nbd7  6.a3  Bxc3  7.Bxc3  O-O  transposes to  7. ... Nbd7     5. ...Nc6  6.Nf3  transposes to  4. ... Nc6 }
6. a3 { Forcing Black to exchange a Bishop for a Knight. } 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ That's why we played Bd2 earlier - to take on c3 with a Bishop and to take control of the c3-g7 diagonal and the e5-square, in particular. }
7... Qe7 { The main plan for Black is to fight for the center with ...e5. } 8.
Nf3 { We develop a Knight and put off ...e5 at least for a move. } 8... Nbd7
{ We have already seen a very similar position in the previous chapter 4. ... Nc6.   8. ...Nc6  transposes directly to  4. ... Nc6 }
9. e3
{ It's also possible to play a more active   9.e4  but I don't believe it's a good idea to imprison the own light-squared Bishop, what happens after  9. ...e5! }
9... b6
{ This move has not been analyzed in the 4. ... Nc6 chapter, because it doesn't really make sense to develop a Bishop to b7 when a Knight stands on c6 and blocks the big a8-h1 diagonal. Here, on the contrary, it's more than logical to consider a fianchetto as the Knight stands on d7 and doesn't block anything. }
10. Be2
{ This is the square where we usually should develop our light-squared Bishop. After   10.Bd3  Black can play  10. ...Bb7  which becomes even more unpleasant because Black wants to take a Knight and double our pawns on the f-file. }
10... Bb7 { The black Bishop is a beast along the big diagonal. } 11. b4
{ There are two helpful ideas behind this pawn advance. First, we liberate the b2-square for the c3-Bishop. Secondly, we launch a pawn storm and win space on the queenside. }
11... Ne4
{ Black centralizes a Knight and intends to exchange a Knight for a Bishop. }
12. Bb2
{ We should save our Bishop pair advantage, despite the fact, that the e4-Knight is quite active and the position isn't still open. The pawn structure isn't defined though, so we shall have a chance one day to open the position. }
12... f5
{ Black supports the e4-Knight and expects to use the f6-square as a 'springboard' to transfer some pieces to the kingside.   12. ...c5  13.O-O  f5  transposes here }
13. O-O
{ Castling kingside doesn't look like a completely safe move, but hiding the King on the queenside is even scarier, isn't it? }
13... c5 { Black fights for the center. } 14. Rad1
{ As the black d6-pawn has been weakened, it makes sense to take control of the potentially open d-file. }
14... Rac8 { Black follows the same idea, but on the c-file. } 15. dxc5
{ Opening up the d-file as well as the b2-g7 diagonal. } 15... bxc5 16. Nd2
{ It's a good idea to exchange the most active black piece. } 16... Ng5
{ 16. ...Nb6  was played by a strong grandmaster Amin  17.b5!  We're going to create a passed pawn on the queenside with a4 and a5 at some point. Moreover, we want to either trade the e4-Knight or kick it out with f3. }
17. f4 { Preventing ...f4 once and for all and winning space on the kingside. }
17... Ne4 18. b5
{ A clever move that gives us a long-term advantage - a possibility to create an outside passed pawn with a4, a5 and so on. }
18... Nxd2 19. Rxd2
{ We want to double the Rooks on the d-file and attack the d6-pawn more. }
19... Be4 20. Qd1 { Attacking the d6-pawn. } 20... d5 21. a4
{ Following our original plan - we want to push the pawns on the queenside as far as possible. }
*

