{ An essential move if Black wants to develop a Knight to c6. If   7. ...Nc6  immediately, then  8.d5  exd5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Qxg7!  Winning a pawn and defending the g5-Bishop.    If Black plays quietly   7. ...d6  then  8.e4!  we play actively  8. ...c5  9.d5!  It's important to win space in the center and restrict the b7-Bishop.  9. ...Nbd7  10.h4  Protecting the g5-Bishop to prevent ...Nxe4.  10. ...O-O  11.O-O-O  With the idea to transfer a Knight to the kingside with Ne2-g3. }
8. Bh4 { We should not leave the h4-d8 diagonal to keep a pin. } 8... d6 9. e4
{ Taking full control of the center. } 9... c5
{ Black tries to fight for the center.   9. ...g5  is overoptimistic  10.Bf2  Nbd7  11.O-O-O  Threatening c5.  11. ...Qe7  12.Ne2  We want to play a prophylactic move Kb1, followed by h4. }
10. d5 { Creating a space advantage and shutting out the b7-Bishop. } 10...
Nbd7
{ 10. ...Nxd5  doesn't work as after  11.Bxd8  Nxc3  12.Bh4  Na4  13.b3  Nc3  14.Kd2+-  seals the win.     10. ...g5  weakens the kingside too much.  11.Bg3  e5  12.h4!  an excellent way to exploit the weakness on the kingside. We intend to open up the h-file with hxg5. }
11. Bg3
{ Attacking the d6-pawn and getting a Bishop out of the h4-d8 diagonal.   11.O-O-O  is a mistake due to a discovered attack  11. ...Nxe4!  12.Qe1  g5! }
11... exd5 12. cxd5
{ 12.exd5  is much worse due to  12. ...O-O  Black is going to give an annoying check with ...Re8 }
12... Qe7 13. O-O-O
{ We want to liberate a way for our g2-pawn with either Bf2 or Be1, followed by g4. }
*

