5. Qxc3
{ The engine claims that  5.bxc3  is also possible, but it is one of those rare moments when we can say, that we, people, understand a position better than an engine. }
5... O-O { This is probably the most natural continuation. } 6. Bg5
{ As Black doesn't have a dark-squared Bishop, it makes sense to create a pin, which can't be blocked. }
6... h6 { Black creates an escape hole on h7 with tempo. } 7. Bh4
{ Of course, we should maintain a pin. } 7... d6 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3
{ The d3-Bishop is excellently eyeing the kingside. } 9... b6 10. Ne2
{ It's important to keep the f3-square vacant to have the opportunity to restrict the black light-squared Bishop with f3. }
10... Bb7 11. O-O { Making a short castling and defending the g2-pawn. } 11...
g5 12. Bg3 { Black has weakened the kingside too much. } 12... Ne4 13. Qc2
{ Attacking the e4-Knight. } 13... f5 14. f3
{ That's why we played Ne2 a couple of moves ago. } 14... Nxg3 15. Nxg3 Qe7 16.
Rae1
{ We want to open up the position with f4 and e4. The black King is too exposed. }
