1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nf3
cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nd7 10. Bf4 Ndc5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Be2 Na4 14. cxd5
exd5 15. f3 Nexc3 16. Bd3
{ We have analyzed everything up to this moment in our chapter. } 16... Qh4
{ We haven't looked at this move, although it looks quite logical. Black activates the Queen and attacks the f4-Bishop. }
17. Qd2
{ It's a good idea to leave the c-file as Black is going to x-ray the the Queen with ...Rac8. }
17... Rac8 18. Kh1
{ A great prophylactic decision against ...Qxd4, Qxd4, ...Ne2+ with a fork which can show up in some positions. White also plans to put a Rook on g1. We threaten to trap the black Queen with Bg5. }
18... Kh8
{ Defending against immediate Bg5.   Let's play a random move for Black to demonstrate the white threats.  18. . ..a6  19.Bg5!  Black cannot take the d4-Knight because of Bxh7!  19. ...Qh5  20.g4  Chasing the black Queen.  20. ...Qh3  21.Rg1  Black cannot stop Rg3. }
19. Rae1
{ It's a good idea to include the last undeveloped piece in the game. } 19...
b5 20. Bc2
{ Defending the d4-Knight with the Queen and threatening Bg5.   20.g4?!  is an interesting attempt to block the fourth rank and trap the black Queen afterward but it fails due to  20. ...Nc5!  21.Qxc3  Ne6!  A discovered attack! The f4-Bishop is hanging.  22.Qd2  Nxd4  Black has equalized. So it's much better to play  20.Rg1!  first. Now we have a threat to play g4. The difference is that we have a possibility to reply with Rg3 immediately after Black retreats the Queen to h3. }
20... Rc4 21. Bb3
{ White should kick out the Rook of the active position, where it attacks the d4-Knight and prevents Bg5. }
21... Rcc8 22. Bg5 { The beginning of the end for Black. } 22... Qh5 23. g4
{ White proceeds with chasing the black Queen. } 23... Qg6 24. Bc2 Qb6 25. Qd3
{ Threatening mate in one. } 25... Qg6 26. Qe3 Qb6 27. Qf2
{ White doesn't want to repeat the moves, of course. The idea of this move is to transfer the Queen to h4. }
27... Nxa2 28. Bxh7
{ A beautiful combination! There are two important principles when attacking: include all the pieces in the attack and open up the enemy King. }
28... f6
{ 28. ...Kxh7  is a principled line  29.Qh4!  Involving all the pieces in the attack.  29. ...Kg8  30.Bf6!!  Black can't prevent Qg5. After  30. ...gxf6  31.exf6  The original threat Qg5 is still unstoppable. }
29. exf6 gxf6 30. Bf4
{ The black King is completely exposed and White wants to play Qh4 on the move. Black resigned.   30. ...Rf7  is the best attempt to defend the position but after  31.Bg6  Rg7  32.Qh4  Kg8  33.Nf5!  Black is collapsing. We bring one more piece in the attack which is crucial. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Fridman, Daniel vs. Efimenko, Zahar, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nf3
cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nd7 10. Bf4 Ndc5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Be2 Qa5
{ We haven't analyzed this move in our chapter because of its unpopularity. However, it's certainly a reasonable idea to attack our c3-pawn. }
14. cxd5
{ This move isn't the best but also poses some practical problems.   14.Rfc1  It was better just to protect the c3-pawn.  14. ...Na4  15.cxd5  Nexc3  Black cannot take on c3 with the Queen.  16.d6  White is much better thanks to the d6-pawn. Our advantage becomes even bigger with the Queens on the board. }
14... Qxc3
{ White is going to have a big space advantage after d6, so it's a good idea for Black to exchange the Queens. }
15. Qxc3 Nxc3 16. d6
{ It is the d6-pawn which will determine the outcome of this game. } 16...
Nxe2+ { It makes sense to deprive White of a Bishop pair advantage. } 17. Nxe2
Rfc8 18. Rfd1
{ The best squares for the white Rooks are c1 and d1. Daniel Fridman, who is a high-class grandmaster, understands it very well. }
18... Na4 { Black wants to invade the second rank with the c8-Rook. } 19. Rac1
{ The c-file is the only open file in the position, so it's vital to fight for it. }
19... Rxc1
{ The only way to maintain equality was to transfer the Knight to  d5  with  19. ...Nb6  20.Be3  Nd5  White is still slightly better, but it's much harder to break through. }
20. Rxc1 Rc8 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. Be3
{ It looked logical for Black to trade the Rooks as Black lacks space. Nevertheless, the a7-pawn is hanging now and Black has to play extremely precisely. }
22... b6
{ This move is inaccurate but it was challenging to come up with the best plan.   22. ...f6!  It was crucial to liberate the f7-square for the King.  23.f4  We have to protect the e5-pawn.  23. ...b6  Preventing Bxa7  24.Bd4  Restricting the a4-Knight.  24. ...f5  25.Ng3  With the idea to transfer the Knight to h5.  25. ...Kf7  26.Nh5  Kg6  White doesn't manage to hold the Knight on h5 and attack the g7-pawn anymore. }
23. Bd4 { White restricts the a4-Knight. } 23... Kf8
{ 23. ...Nc5?  An attempt to activate the Knight fails due to  24.Bxc5  bxc5  25.Nc3  Kf8  26.Na4!  Attacking the c5-pawn.  26. ...c4  27.Nc5!  It turns out that the black Bishop doesn't have any squares.  27. ...Ke8  28.Kf1!  The c5-pawn will inevitably fall. }
24. Ng3 { Transferring the Knight to h5. } 24... Bb7 25. Nh5
{ The black King cannot leave the f8-square and we threaten to capture the g7-pawn. }
25... Bd5 { 25. ...Bc6  Black had to stop the d-pawn with this move. } 26. a3
{ 26.Nxg7!  Distracting the black King from stopping our d-pawn.  26. ...Bxa2  Fridman was probably afraid of this move.  27.Nh5!  We threaten to occupy a great outpost on f6 with the Knight, followed by Be3 and Bh6. Black doesn't have a reasonable defense. }
26... a5
{ After   26. ...Bc6  Black stops the d-pawn and still has some hopes to make a draw. }
27. Nxg7 { A very nice deflection! } 27... b5 28. Nh5
{ Fridman wants to transfer the Knight to f6, followed by Be3 and Bh6. } 28...
b4 29. axb4 axb4 30. Nf6
{ Fortunately, the black pawn is too far from the back-rank. } 30... b3 31.
Nxh7+ { Winning a pawn with tempo. } 31... Ke8 32. Nf6+ Kd8
{ If the black King goes back to  f8  32. ...Kf8  then  33.Be3  threatening mate in one.  33. ...Kg7  34.Bc1  White has to stop the b-pawn.  34. ...Bc6  An attempt to stop the white pawn.  35.d7  Bxd7  36.Nxd7  b2  37.Bxb2  Nxb2  White is two pawns up which must be more than enough to win the game. }
33. h4 { Including one more pawn in the game. } 33... b2 34. Bxb2 Nxb2 35. f4
{ 35.h5  wins as well but it's much better to create a solid pawn chain first. }
35... Nd3 36. g3
{ The pawn chain is perfect now and we are ready to push the pawns. } 36... Nc5
37. h5 Nd7
{ The only chance for Black to stop the h-pawn is to exchange the Knights. }
38. Nxd7 Kxd7 39. g4
{ We have three passed pawns which must more than enough to win. } 39... Be4
40. Kf2 f6 41. Kg3 fxe5 42. fxe5 Ke8 43. g5 Bc6 44. g6
{ We're going to transfer the King to g5 and push the pawns afterward. The black position is hopeless. }
