1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 c5 6. e5 cxd4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 Ne8 9. cxd4 d6 10. Nf3 Nc6
{ We have analyzed a very similar move, but still not absolutely the same.   10. ...dxe5  11.dxe5  Nc6  12.Bd3!  Instead of defending the e5-pawn, we attack the h7-pawn. }
11. Bb2
{ Overprotecting the e5-pawn.   11.Bd3  dxe5  12.dxe5  transposes to the same chapter. }
11... dxe5 12. dxe5 f5
{ Black closes the kingside to prevent White from creating some threats on the kingside by developing the f1-Bishop to d3. }
13. Be2
{ It doesn't make sense to develop the Bishop to d3 anymore as the d3-h7 diagonal has been closed. }
13... Rf7 14. O-O h6 15. Rfd1 { It's a good idea to fight for the open file. }
15... Rd7 16. c5
{ Zubov wins more space in the center and liberates the c4-square for a Bishop. The black pieces are not developed and passive. }
16... Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Qe7 18. Nd2
{ 18.g3!  There was an unexpected way to prevent the only active black plan ...Nc7 and .. .Nd5.  18...Nc7  19.Nh4!  Nd5?  isn't possible anymore because of  20.Nxf5! }
18... Nc7 19. Bf3
{ Activating the Bishop and intending to transfer the Knight from d2 to d6 with Nc4. }
19... Na6 { Black attacks the c5-pawn. } 20. Nc4
{ Zubov sacrifices a pawn to transfer the Knight to the outpost on d6. } 20...
Qxc5 21. Qe2
{ Getting the Queen out of the pin and aiming to finally play Nd6. } 21... Qb5
22. Qc2 Qc5 23. Qe2 Qb5 24. h4
{ 24.Bc1!  It was better to launch the attack on the kingside immediately  24. ...Nc5  25.Bxh6!  Opening up the enemy King  25. ...gxh6  26.Bxc6  Liberating a way for the Queen.  26. ...Qxc6  27.Qh5  It's important not only to open up the enemy King but also to include all the pieces in the attack.  27. ...Kg7  28.Nd6!  Threatening Qf7. The white attack is overwhelming. }
24... Nc7 25. Qc2 Qc5 26. Qb3
{ Zubov tries to get of the pin on the c-file again. } 26... Rb8 27. Bxc6
{ Destroying a defender of the back-rank. } 27... Qxc6 28. Rd8+
{ It's important not only to control an open file but also to invade the opponent camp at some point. }
28... Kh7 29. h5
{ Fixing the black pawns on the kingside and intending to transfer the Queen to g6. }
29... Nd5 30. Qg3 Ne7 31. Nd6 { Occupying a great outpost. } 31... Qa4 32. Ne8
{ Threatening mate in one. } 32... Qg4 33. Qxg4 fxg4 34. Nf6+
{ A beautiful combination! } 34... gxf6 35. exf6
{ It turns out that Black cannot stop f7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Chuchelov, Vladimir, 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 8. Bf4
Nh5 9. Bg5 Be7 10. h4 Bb7 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. e4 Nf6 13. e5 Ng4 14. Bf4 Rc8 15.
Kb1 f5 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Ng5 Qe8 18. Nb5
{ 18.Bd3  is the best move that was analyzed in our chapter. It's very hard to calculate the following lines, even for such a great player as Garry Kasparov.  18. ...g6  19.Nxh7!  There are two important principles when attacking: include all the pieces in the attack and open up the enemy King.  19. ...Kxh7  20.h5  Opening up the h-file.  20. ...Kg7  21.hxg6  Threatening Bh6.  21. ...Rh8  22.Rxh8  Qxh8  23.Qc1!!  I assume, this is the move that Kasparov missed. It's hard to blame him as it's almost impossible to find so far in advance. White wants to transfer the Rook to h1, followed by Bh6. White is winning. }
18... e5 19. Bd3 { A very interesting piece sacrifice. } 19... e4
{ 19. ...exf4  What happens if Black accepts the piece sacrifice?  20.Bxh7!  First, we grab a pawn.  20. ...Kh8  21.Bg6  Qd8  22.Rhe1!  It's really amazing if Kasparov found this idea during the game. The idea behind this move is totally prophylactic - White prevents a good defensive move ...Ne5.  22. ...Ba6  With the idea to trade an active Knight on b5. If the b5-Knight leaves the b5-square, then Black has unpleasant pressure on the c4-pawn, especially after ...Na5.  23.Bf7!  A wonderful move! We liberate the g6-square for the Queen. I find this combination outstanding because White doesn't play forcingly in the sense that White doesn't give any checks and doesn't create any obvious threats.  23. ...Bxb5  24.Qg6!  Sacrificing the second minor piece in order not to slow down the pace of an attack.  24. ...Ba4  25.h5!  Sacrificing a Rook to open up the enemy King.  25. ...Bxd1  26.h6!  Black can't avoid mate. }
20. Be2 h6
{ Black is 'attacking' the Knight on g5 but doesn't really want to take it as this would open up the h-file and include the h1-Rook in the attack. }
21. Nd6
{ As already mentioned, it's a good idea to ignore the previous black move as it doesn't really threaten anything and continue the original plan. }
21... Bxd6 22. Bxd6 { The f8-Rook is trapped. } 22... hxg5 23. hxg5
{ Black starts playing desperately - this is an attempt at least to win some material. }
23... Nh7 24. Rxh7
{ A magnificent combination! We sacrifice an exchange to destroy the only defender and open up the enemy King. }
24... Kxh7 25. Bxf8
{ Winning back an exchange and deflecting the black Queen from the defense of the e4-pawn. }
25... Qxf8 26. Qxe4+ Kg8 27. Qd5+
{ 27. ...Kh7  If Black moves the King to the h-file we can give a forced mate with  28.Rh1  Kg6  29.Bd3  Qf5  30.Qxf5     27. ...Qf7  loses due to  28.Qxf7  Kxf7  29.Rxd7  White is winning the b7-Bishop on the next move, ending up in a position with three extra pawns. }
