1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Nf3 Qb6 7. e3 Qc7 8. g4
h6 9. Rg1 b6 10. g5
{ My main recommendation is a safer move  10.Be2  However, there is nothing wrong with the move, which Andreikin played. }
10... hxg5 11. Nb5
{ An important intermediate move! We should kick the black Queen out of the c7-square so that it would not attack the white pawn on h2. }
11... Qd8 12. Nxg5
{ White threatens to sacrifice a Knight on f7, followed by Qg6. } 12... Bf8
{ Black plays too passively. It was clearly better to cover the g6-square with   12. ...Rh6!  Black is still not losing. }
13. c5
{ An incredible combination! The point behind this move is to close the f8-b4 diagonal.   13.Nd6??  it's a bad idea to deflect the f8-Bishop immediately because of  13. ...Bxd6  14.Nxf7  Bb4!  As the d6-b4 diagonal is not closed, Black can give this intermediate check and liberate the d6-square for the King.  15.Kd1  Kxf7  16.Qg6  Ke7  17.Qxg7  All would have been well had Black not had the following move  17. ...Kd6!  The black King escapes and it's Black now, who is winning. }
13... Rh5
{ 13. ...bxc5  The most straightforward continuation.  14.Nd6!  This combination works out very well with the pawn on c5.  14. ...Bxd6  15.Nxf7!  Kxf7  16.Qg6  Ke7  17.Qxg7!  The black King is forced to go to the back-rank, followed by losing the h8-Rook. }
14. Nd6+ { Forcing Black to trade the dark-squared Bishop. } 14... Bxd6 15.
cxd6 { White threatens Nxf7 again. } 15... Bb7
{ The black position is objectively lost, but Black could defend better.   15. ...Rh6  Covering the g6-square and forcing White to play a couple of precise moves.  16.e4!  Black cannot stop both Nxf7 and Nxe6 with a discovered attack on the h6-Rook and e5. }
16. Nxf7 { Finally perfoming the planned combination on the board! } 16... Be4
17. Qxe4 { The easiest and safest way to win. } 17... Nxe4 18. Nxd8 Kxd8 19.
Bg2 { It turns out that Black cannot protect the pinned e4-Knight. } 19... Rg5
{ 19. ...Rh4  doesn't help due to  20.f4! } 20. Kf1
{ Defending the g1-Rook and again threatening Bxe4. } 20... Rxg2 21. Kxg2
{ White is an exchange up and Black is hopeless. } *

