[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Nf3 Qc7 7. a3 a6 8. b4
Be7 9. e4 d6 10. Bd3
{ My recommendation is  10.Be2  here. But there is no big difference. } 10...
Nbd7 11. O-O b6 12. Re1
{ As the Bishop is placed on d3, it's a good idea to develop the f1-Rook to e1. Another Rook can go either to c1 or d1. }
12... O-O 13. Bf4 { Mareco threatens e5 on the next move. } 13... Nh5
{ Black wants to kick the white Bishop out of f4 to prevent e5. } 14. Be3 Bb7
15. Rac1
{ A Rook is more useful on c1 as we want to create a pawn breakthrough with c5 at some point. }
15... Rac8 16. Be2
{ A little confession that it was better to play Be2 earlier as analyzed in our chapter. }
16... Nhf6 17. Nd2 { White protects the c4- and e4-pawns. } 17... Qb8
{ A standard maneuver. Black wants to double the Rooks on the c-file and transfer the Queen to a8 at some point. }
18. Qb1
{ Both sides maneuver slowly in this type of pawn formation, also known as the Hedgehog. }
18... Rfe8 19. Bf4 Ne5 20. h3
{ It's a good idea to create an escape square for the King. } 20... Bd8
{ Black tries to find a better square for the Bishop. } 21. Bf1
{ White opens up the e-file and makes the Bishop a little bit safer. } 21...
Bc7 22. Na4 { This move prepares c5. } 22... Bc6
{ Black doesn't want to tolerate this Knight. } 23. Nb2
{ 23.b5!?  was extremely interesting  23. ...axb5  24.cxb5  Bb7  25.Bxe5  Exchanging an active Knight and doubling the black pawns.  25. ...dxe5  26.Nb2  Transferring the Knight to c4 and planning to advance the a-pawn. White is clearly better. }
23... Qa8 { Putting some pressure on the e4-pawn. } 24. a4
{ Mareco starts a pawn storm on the queenside and prepares b5. } 24... a5
{ This is a mistake, but it's not that easy to prove it. } 25. b5
{ 25.Bxe5!  White should have taken the Knight on e5 instantly!  25. ...dxe5  26.b5  Bb7  27.c5!  A great positional sacrifice!  27. ...bxc5  28.Nbc4  The white Knight occupies a perfect square and the black pawn structure is awful. White is going either to attack the black pawns with Nb3 at some point or to push b6, followed by Qb5. }
25... Bb7
{ 25. ...Ng6!  Black could have avoided this line with the excellent intermediate move. And only after  26.Bg5  Bb7  Black is doing still alright as White doesn't have this option to capture the Knight on e5 and damage the pawn structure. }
26. Bxe5 { White finally plays this amazing idea! } 26... dxe5 27. c5
{ What an enjoyable sacrifice! } 27... bxc5 28. Nbc4
{ The black Bishop is terrible and White totally dominates the queenside. }
28... Red8 29. b6
{ One more strong decision! White grabs more space on the queenside and liberates the b5-square for the Queen. }
29... Bb8 30. f3
{ 30.Qb5!  immediately was even better!  30. ...Bc6  31.Qxa5  Qxa5  32.Nxa5  Bxa4   32. ...Rxd2  33.Ba6!  Black's position is falling apart.  33.Ba6!  The black Rook is trapped. It was probably this move, which Mareco didn't see during the game. }
30... Ba6 { Black prevents Qb5 and comlicates White's life a little bit. } 31.
Qb2 Nd7 32. Qc3 { Attacking the a5-pawn. } 32... Qc6 33. Qxa5
{ Black's position becomes hopeless after this move. } 33... Bxc4 34. Nxc4 Bd6
35. b7 { The black Queen is tied up to the defense of the d6-Bishop. } 35...
Rc7 36. Rb1 Be7 37. Qb5 Nb8 38. Nxe5 { White is officially a pawn up. } 38...
Qxb5 39. Rxb5
{ White has two connected passers which must be more than enough to win the game. }
39... Bf6 40. f4 g5 41. g3
{ White could have played better but pretty much everything wins in this position. }
41... gxf4 42. gxf4 Bh4 43. Rc1 Rd2
{ Although the black Rook is quite active on the second rank, Black doesn't have any real threats. }
44. Nd3
{ 44.Nf3!  wins forcingly.  44. ...Bf2  45.Kg2  Ra2  46.Bc4!  Making Black trade an active Rook  46. ...Be3  47.Bxa2  Bxc1  48.Bc4!  Blocking the c5-pawn and intending to push the a-pawn. The white pawns are unstoppable. }
44... c4 45. Rc3 { 45.a5!  was better. The c4-pawn is pinned anyway. } 45...
Ra2
{ 45. ...f6!  was very strong! The idea behind this move is to transfer the Rook to g7 and create some real threats against the white King. White has to work really hard to win this position. }
46. Nb2 { The a2-Rook is out of the game and Black can't prevent Bxc4. } 46...
f5 47. Bxc4 Rg7+
{ Too late. Black's attack isn't dangerous without another Rook. } 48. Kh2
{ Black's attack is over and White is two pawns up. } *

