[Black "Nakamura, Hikaru vs. Teplitsky, Yan, 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Na6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 Nxc5 8.
b4 Nce4 9. Qb2 d5 10. c5 d4 11. e3 e5 12. Nf3 Nc3
{ We have covered only  12....Ng4  in this chapter and  12. ...O-O  in this chapter    This move is objectively worse than the above-mentioned continuations. }
13. Bc4
{ This move still maintains a big advantage but it was better to play  13.Bd2!  Attacking the c3-Knight immediately. }
13... b5 { An interesting way to liberate the b7-square for the с8-Bishop. }
14. cxb6
{ It's hard to criticize Nakamura for not choosing the best moves because the position is extremely complicated. But still, it was better to play  14.Bb3  because we have an option to push the pawn forward to c6 at some point. }
14... Bb7
{ I believe it's a good idea to develop a minor piece instead of taking a pawn on b6. }
15. Nxe5 { Attacking the f7-pawn. } 15... Bxg2
{ It's by all means overoptimistic to capture the g2-pawn as the black King is still in the center and the g-file becomes open. It was much safer to castle short instantly  15...O-O }
16. Rg1 Bd5 17. exd4 { Destroying a defender of the c3-Knight. } 17... Nfe4 18.
Be3
{ It was better to take on  d5  immediately  18.Bxd5  Qxd5  19.b7!  Distracting the black Queen from attacking our d4-pawn.  19. ...Qxb7  20.Rxg7  Attacking the f7-pawn.  20. ...Rf8  21.f3  Black loses a Knight. }
18... f6 19. Bxd5 { From now Nakamura played brilliantly. } 19... Qxd5 20. f3
{ Nakamura keeps initiative instead of retreating the e5-Knight. } 20... fxe5
21. fxe4 Nxe4 22. Rxg7
{ The position is extremely sharp but the black King is much worse and, in addition, White is two pawns up at the moment. }
22... axb6 23. Qc2 { 23.dxe5!  Time to be greedy! White is going to play Rd1. }
23... exd4
{ 23. ...Nd6!  was exceptionally strong. Black intends to transfer the Knight to c4. }
24. O-O-O
{ Pinning the d4-pawn and eliminataing black last hopes to save this game. }
24... Qe6 25. Rxd4 Rc8 26. Rc7 Rxc7 27. Qxc7 O-O 28. Qc4
{ When you are ahead in material - trade Queens! } 28... Re8 29. Qxe6+ Rxe6 30.
Rd8+ Kf7 31. Rd7+ Kg6 32. Rb7 { The Rook on the seventh rank is a beast. }
32... b5 33. Rxb5 Nc3 34. Rb6
{ Black cannot win the e3-Bishop as the e6-Rook is pinned. Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Kramnik, Vladimir, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Now we're going to analyze one of the most interesting and important games in this chapter, which was played in the World Championship match between Viswanathan Anand and Vladimir Kramnik. This game was particularly difficult for Vladimir Kramnik, as he was in a very hard psychological state after the previous game, where he lost with the white pieces in the dramatic battle. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 Nc6 8.
Bd2 O-O 9. h3
{ It is this game where this move was first played. However, Kramnik says that he expected this novelty and he was prepared. }
9... b6
{ In our chapter 'Romanishin variation' we have covered the most popular  9. ...a5  here and  9. ...Bxc3  here and  9. ...Rd8  here The text move also makes sense - Black wants to develop the light-squared Bishop to the big diagonal. However, Kramnik finds this continuation dubious at the moment and claims that Black should play ...a5 or ...Bxc3 with a complicated but very interesting position. }
10. g4 { As in our chapter, White should play directly and actively. } 10...
Qa5 11. Rc1
{ This is one more very smart move by Anand. He wants to kick out the black b4-Bishop with a3, so he gets rid of the pin on the a-file. }
11... Bb7
{ Black threatens to win the d4-pawn with ...Nxd4, using the pin on the long diagonal. }
12. a3
{ The engine says that the best move for White is  12.Rg1  with the idea to get rid of the pin on the long diagonal. }
12... Bxc3 13. Bxc3 { White forces Black to trade the Queens. } 13... Qd5 14.
Qxd5 Nxd5 15. Bd2
{ White has a very solid and pleasant ending mainly thanks to the Bishop pair and a space advantage in the center. The only chance for Black to equalize is to push the c-pawn to c5. }
15... Nf6 { Black puts pressure on the d4-pawn again, making Bg2 impossible. }
16. Rg1
{ White is forced to spend a tempo on this move to avoid the pin and develop the light-squared Bishop to g2. }
16... Rac8 17. Bg2 { White threatens Ne5. } 17... Ne7 18. Bb4
{ Creating an annoying pin and forcing Black to make an unpleasant decision. }
18... c5
{ Kramnik didn't want to play a calmer move  18. ...Rfe8  because of  19.Bxe7  Rxe7  20.Ne5  Bxg2  21.Rxg2  c5  22.dxc5  bxc5  23.Rg3!  Transferring the Rook to the queenside. Black has a poor pawn structure and is forced to play for a draw the rest of the game. }
19. dxc5 Rfd8
{ Black doesn't have enough compensation for a pawn. Black should have played  19. ...bxc5  20.Bxc5  Ne4  Using the on on the c-file.  21.b4  Nxc5  22.bxc5  Bxf3!  It's essential to eliminate the potential defender of the c5-pawn.  23.Bxf3  Rc7  With the idea to double the Rooks on the c-file.  24.Kd2  Rfc8  Black is going to win back the c5-pawn and hold this a little bit unpleasant ending. }
20. Ne5
{ Anand plays in the unbalanced positions brilliantly and this game is one more proof of it. }
20... Bxg2 21. Rxg2 bxc5
{ Black should have played  21...Ned5  but the position is still bad. } 22.
Rxc5 Ne4 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Nd3 Nd5 25. Bd2
{ A fantastic maneuver! Anand wants to defend the b2-pawn with Bc1.   25.f3?  would be a blunder because of  25...Nf4!  And it turns out that Black is much better now due to the weakness of the back rank. }
25... Rc2 26. Bc1
{ It turns out that Black cannot exploit the temporarily uncoordinated white pieces at all. }
26... f5
{ It was possible to play  26...Nc5  setting up a small trap  27.Kd1  Nxd3  28.exd3   28.Kxc2?  loses because of  28. ...Ne1!  28. ...Rc6  29.f3  White must be objectively winning but Black has a little bit more chances to make a draw than in the game thanks to the good Knight on d5. }
27. Kd1 { Driving away the black Rook from the second rank. } 27... Rc8 28. f3
{ Kicking out the e4-Knight from the center. } 28... Nd6 29. Ke1
{ A weird but very interesting move. Anand avoids complications that appear after  29.e3  Nc4  30.Re2  Rd8  31.Kc2!  White has to play precisely which is not that easy during a game. }
29... a5 30. e3
{ Now it's not possible for Black to create a pin on the d-file as the King is placed on e1. }
30... e5 { A desperate counterattack. } 31. gxf5 e4 32. fxe4 Nxe4
{ The black Knights look active but Anand played very well and repelled all the possible black threats. }
33. Bd2 a4 { 33. ...Rc2  Attacking the e3-pawn.  34.Re2!  Black has nothing. }
34. Nf2
{ This is a move that destroys the last hopes of Kramnik. Anand kicks out the centralized Knight. }
34... Nd6 35. Rg4
{ White is two pawns up and the black position is absolutely hopeless. } 35...
Nc4 36. e4 Nf6 37. Rg3 Nxb2 38. e5 Nd5 39. f6
{ Exploiting a pin on the g-file. } 39... Kf7 40. Ne4
{ Threatening a fork with Nd6. } 40... Nc4 41. fxg7 Kg8 42. Rd3 Ndb6 43. Bh6
Nxe5 44. Nf6+ Kf7 45. Rc3
{ A nice way to distract the black Rook from defending the back rank. } 45...
Rxc3 46. g8=Q+ Kxf6 47. Bg7+
{ This game proves that our opening choice can be successfully played even on a very high level. I think, that it is the deep opening preparation that allowed Anand to win this very important game, after the result of the whole match outcome was predetermined. }
*

