[White "Model games"]
[Black "Navara, David vs. Nguyen, Thai Dai Van, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Bd2 Nc6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. a3 Bxc3 8.
Bxc3 Qe7 9. e3 a5 10. Be2 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. h3
{ The first deviation from our 4. Qc2 Nc6 chapter. My recommendation is   12.O-O  There is no need to prevent ...Bg4 because it's not that dangerous and Wojtaszek could castle short immediately. }
12... Rd8 13. O-O e4
{ It helps us to centralize a Knight.   13. ...a4!  It was better to fix the white pawn structure on the queenside. }
14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4
{ This is a principled mistake. It was much better to take with the pawn.   15.exd4!  a4  16.Rad1  White has full control over the center. It's a good idea to block the e4-pawn with Qd2 and Qe3 as well. }
15... c5
{ Ohterwise, White would create a dangerous battery on the c3-g7 diagonal with Qc3. }
16. Bc3
{ At the same time, the black pawn structure on the queenside looks at least suspicious. }
16... a4
{ Black has to fix the white pawn structure on the queenside, otherwise, White will be able to create a battery again by b3 and Qb2. }
17. f4 { A great decision! Wojtaszek starts a pawn storm on the kingside. }
17... Bd7 18. f5
{ 18.Kh2  was also possible. The idea of this move is to make the King a little bit safer and play g4 on the next move. }
18... Bc6 19. Rf4
{ 19.Qc1!  was very interesting. White wants to transfer the Queen to the kingside by Qe1 and Qg3 or Qh4. }
19... Rd6
{ This is a clever move as Black prepares ... Nd7 on the next move.   19. ...Nd7?  would be a blunder because of  20.f6!  And the black pawn structure is awful after  20. .. .Nxf6  21.Bxf6  gxf6  22.Raf1 }
20. Raf1
{ Involving the last undeveloped piece in the game and kind of preventing ...Nd7. }
20... Rad8
{ 20. ...Nd7!  was still the best.  21.f6  Nxf6  22.Qc1!  With the idea to transfer the Queen to g3. White has enough compensation but nothing more. }
21. Qc1 { Wojtaszek wants to include the Queen in the attack on the kingside. }
21... Nd7
{ Black had to come up with a strong idea  21. ...Rd3!  22.Bxd3  exd3  The c6-Bishop becomes active and the e-file becomes open. }
22. f6 { Otherwise, Black blocks our pawn and the Rooks with ...f6. } 22...
Nxf6 23. Qe1
{ It's hard to imagine that Black can stop White's attack after Wojtaszek will transfer the Queen to the kingside. In addition, White has strong pressure on the open f-file. }
23... Ne8
{ Desperation. Black could still fight with the only moves.   23. ...Re6  24.Qg3  Qc7!  Pinning the white Rook on f4. However, after  25.Qg5  Black must be still losing as it's impossible to protect the c5-pawn and the f6-Knight at the same time. }
24. Rxf7 Qxf7 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Qg3
{ The Queen is much stronger than two Rooks in this position as we have a Bishop pair and the black King is exposed. }
26... Nf6 27. Qe5 { Intending to advance the g-pawn to g4 and g5. } 27... Rd2
{ An attempt to create counterplay. } 28. Bxd2 Rxd2 29. Kf1
{ White's position is very safe - everything is defended. } 29... Rc2 30. Ke1
{ Aiming to trap the black Rook with Kd1. } 30... Rc1+ 31. Kd2 Rg1 32. g4
{ White has a huge advantage and Wojtaszek played the rest of the game very well. }
32... h6 33. h4 g5 34. hxg5 hxg5 35. Qxg5 Bd7 36. Qxc5 Bxg4 37. Bxg4 Rxg4 38.
Qc7+ Ke6 39. Qxb7 { Collecting all the pawns on the queenside. } 39... Rg2+ 40.
Kc3 Re2 41. Qc8+ { White has a big material advantage. Black resigned. } *

