d6 9. Bd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Ng3 Re8 12. f4
{ We have analyzed  12.Re1  in the 4. Qc2 b6 chapter. The move in the game also makes sense as White prevents ...Ne5. }
12... Nf8 13. Bd3 { White intends to take control over the e-file with Rde1. }
13... Bg4 { This move is just a mistake as the black Bishop is trapped here. }
14. Rde1 Qb7 15. f5 { The black Bishop is running out of the moves. } 15... h6
16. h3 Bh5 17. Nge4 { Liberating the g-file for a pawn. } 17... Nxe4 18. Nxe4
Bxd2+ 19. Qxd2 Rxe4
{ 19. ...f6  Black could save the Bishop with this move but the position is still hopeless after  20.Nxd6 }
20. Rxe4 f6 21. Rhe1
{ White could also start an attack immediately with   21.g4  Bf7  22.h4! }
21... Qa6 22. a3 { Defending the a2-pawn. } 22... Nd7 23. g4 Bf7 24. h4
{ 24.g5!  It was very interesting to sacrifice a pawn instantly to open up some files on the kingside.  24. ...hxg5  25.h4!  White's attack is overwhelming. }
24... Ne5
