1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 d6 5. Qc2 O-O 6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2 Qe7 8.
Bc3 Nbd7 { This is a transposition to our chapter 4. Qc2 d6. } 9. e3 e5 10. Be2
Re8 11. dxe5
{ In my opinion, it's better to keep tension in the center with castling short  11.O-O  as was analyzed here but this move is also totally fine. }
11... dxe5 12. h3
{ White plays too careful. It was better to castle short immediately. } 12...
b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. b4
{ White should create an attack on the queenside as well as liberate the b2-square either for the c3-Bishop or for the Queen. }
14... Ne4 15. Bb2 { We don't want to trade our great dark-squared Bishop. }
15... c5 16. Rfd1 { It's important to take control over the only open file. }
16... a5 17. bxa5 { Black wanted to win our b4-pawn so we have to react. }
17... bxa5
{ 17. ...Rxa5  was much better as the Rook becomes much stronger and the white pawn structure on the queenside leaves much to be desired. }
18. Qa4
{ 18.Bd3!  It was better to get rid of the black Knight in the center.  18. ...Nef6  19.Nd2  Avoiding a fork by ...e4.  19. ...e4  20.Be2  Ne5  21.Nf1!  Transferring the Knight to g3. White is clearly better. }
18... Red8 { Black defends the d7-Knight. } 19. Rab1
{ Krasenkow x-rays the b7-Bishop. } 19... Nd6 20. Bc3
{ White threatens to take the Knight on d6, followed by Rxb7. } 20... e4
{ This is a big mistake as it helps White to activate the Knight and makes the c3-Bishop much more active. After   20. ...Be4  21.Rb2  Rdc8  White is only slightly better. }
21. Nh4 { Transferring the Knight to f5. } 21... Ne5
{ One more mistake.   21. ...Nf6  After this quiet move White still has to work a lot. }
22. Rxd6
{ A very nice combination! The black Queen is tied up to the defense of the b7-Bishop. }
22... Rxd6 23. Nf5 { The Knight lands on f5 with a powerful fork. } 23... Nf3+
{ A desperate attempt to create an attack. } 24. Bxf3 Qg5 25. Nxd6
{ It's time to eat all the enemy pieces! } 25... exf3 26. g3
{ Avoiding mate in one. } 26... Qh6 27. Qd7
{ It turns out that Black's attack is over after this simple move. } *

